<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Peru-Accident     12-11 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Peru-Accident,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirty-Five Killed In Truck Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AREQUIPA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck carrying people home from thermal
baths in a remote area of the Andes Mountains tumbled off a
mountain road and down a ravine near the Colca River, killing 35
people, police say.
   The accident occurred Saturday night near the village of Chivay,
50 miles north of Arequipa. Police said the victims had spent the
day at hot springs in the mountains and were returning home to
Chivay.
   Police said they did not know how many people had been in the
truck.
   It was the second major truck accident in a week in Peru.
Nineteen people were killed and 21 injured on Dec. 3 when a truck
carrying fans and members of a soccer team crashed near Nazca, 310
miles southeast of Lima.
   The upper Colca River region where Saturday's accident occurred
is a rugged, sparsely populated area more than 11,000 feet above
sea level, 550 miles southeast of Lima.
</TEXT>
