<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--ScalpReattached     12-11 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Scalp Reattached,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Reattach Woman's Scalp After Industrial Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors reattached the scalp of a woman
after it was ripped off when her hair got tangled in a machine at a
yarn mill.
   Sheila Mobbs, 33, was in satisfactory condition Sunday, and was
moved out of an intensive care unit at University Hospitals, said a
nursing supervisor who would only give her name as Kay.
   The accident occurred Friday at the Leesburg Yarn Mill in
northeastern Alabama, where Mrs. Mobbs works.
   Mrs. Mobbs' husband, Jimmy, said his wife didn't know how the
accident occurred, but she fell and her ponytail became entwined in
the spinning machine.
   The Gaylesville woman was taken to Birmingham along with her
scalp, which was transported in a sealed container.
   Mrs. Mobbs underwent a 14-hour operation at University
Hospitals, Mobbs said.
   ``The doctors said it went well,'' he said.
