<DOCNO> AP891211-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PlowsharesPains     12-11 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plowshares Pains,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capital Fears the Impact of Defense Cuts on the Industry's Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuts in defense spending won't hurt the
economy, analysts say, but could be traumatic for a workforce
accustomed to satisfying a single complacent customer _ the
Pentagon _ instead of the competitive marketplace.
   A third of the nation's engineers and scientists work in defense
and by some estimates 26 million people depend on the military
economy, so there's considerable concern in Washington about the
recoil that will be felt the defense budget is sharply reduced, as
seems likely.
   Analyst William W. Kaufmann of Harvard University and the
Brookings Institution thinks defense spending could be half its
current size in 10 years.
   Both the new era opened by President Bush and Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev at Malta and the pressures of the deficit
point to dismantling the Reagan Era defense buildup. John Ruby,
chief operating officer of Ford Aerospace, says a number of firms
are already planning ``downsizing.''
   Some economists say the government also should be designing
retraining, counseling, job search and relocation programs to ease
the transition for defense workers.
   ``We put over a billion and a half dollars into building planes
we didn't need'' to preserve jobs, says Lawrence J. Korb, who was
an assistant defense secretary in the Reagan administration.
   ``I'd like to see the government come up with a plan to help
people in a graceful and humane way, but you talk about an
industrial policy in this country and they call you a communist,''
he says.
   Congress' Joint Economic Committee is looking at the issue. It
has scheduled hearings for Tuesday on ``the economic consequences
of reduced defense spending and the winding down of the Cold War.''
   ``Depending on its size and speed, a substantial cut in defense
spending phased in over a number of years could be one of the best
things that could happen to the economy and should not be looked on
as something likely to cause recession or unemployment,'' says
Charles Schultze, who was President Carter's chief economic adviser.
   ``One thing this country does not have is a surplus of is
skilled engineers and skilled workmen.''
   But conversion of defense workers, technicians, managers and
plants to the civilian economy will be trickier than it was after
World War II, when Detroit stopped making tanks and resumed making
DeSoto automobiles without missing a step. There was enormous
pent-up demand for civilian products, too.
   But government planners cite society's needs _ for environmental
cleanup, recycling of plastics, health care _ which may be able to
adopt defense industry technology.
   ``I hope trade associations will see the relationship between a
mayor who is worried about defense cuts in his community and about
waste management; if you're smart, you can walk in and say, `I can
solve them both at once,''' says John Tepper Marlin of the Council
on Economic Priorities.
   Defense managers have grown accustomed to working in the
hothouse environment of Pentagon contracting, with no competition
from overseas, a single, cooperative customer and cost-plus-profit
accounting.
   ``Defense contractors are used to being told what the market
is,'' says consultant Jacques Gansler, author of ``Affording
Defense'' and a Pentagon procurement official in 1972-77. ``The
commercial world isn't like that.''
   But Seymour Melman, retired professor of industrial engineering
at Columbia University and a pioneer advocate of planned
conversion, rejects the view that the economy can absorb defense
budget cuts without severe dislocations.
   He argues for an elaborate government efforts to prepare defense
workers and to create productive civilian jobs for them.
   ``What are they going to work at?'' he demands. ``Making shoes?
Eight-five percent of our shoes are imported. Consumer electronics?
All imported. Machine tools? Half are imported.''
   Moreover, Melman argues, defense managers are incapable of
making the leap without retraining.
   ``No major military-serving enterprise has demonstrated an
autonomous ability to carry out the sort of occupational switch
that is needed to go civilian,'' Melman wrote in his book,
``Profits Without Production.''
   ``If you unleash these people, the U.S. will turn into a
third-rate economy,'' Melman says. ``They can't hack it. We will
lose the capability of repairing the damage.''
   Under a conversion legislation sponsored by Rep. Ted Weiss,
D-N.Y., defense contractors would be required to put 1.25 percent
of receipts into a fund to pay the costs of economic adjustment.
Laid-off workers might get 90 percent of their lost salaries while
they are retrained for civilian jobs.
   Gordon Adams, director of the Defense Budget Project, a
Washingon research outfit, says, ``Workers find work when the
economy is healthy; you can plan the dickens out of what to do with
a worker but when we're in a recession you can't do anything for
him.''
   Adams says although counseling, retraining and relocation
programs are critical, ``income supplements, however, slow the
adjustment process.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
