<DOCNO> AP891211-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion-Congress     12-11 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Congress,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Says Administration Plays Down Safety of Abortions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion politics at the White House has
``interfered with scientific evidence and research'' on abortion in
the Department of Health and Human Services, the chairman of a
House panel contends.
   Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., charged in a report released Sunday that
the federal government has failed to report evidence of the
relative safety of abortions for women.
   His panel concluded after an investigation that the federal
Centers for Disease Control has censored research on abortion, and
urged that the Department of Health and Human Services take steps
to assure public health research is not affected by politics.
   It also recommended increased federal support for contraceptive
research to help decrease the 1.5 million abortions obtained by
American women every year.
   ``This report provides important evidence of the relative safety
of abortion for women, since more than 90 percent of abortions
performed in the U.S. are much safer than pregnancy and childbirth,
and even the most dangerous types of legal abortions are equal in
risk to carrying a pregnancy to term,'' said Weiss.
   His statement was included with the report by the House
Government Operations Committee, based on an investigation by its
subcommittee on human resources and intergovernmental relations,
which Weiss chairs.
   In charging that scientific research by the CDC has been
``restricted by the political considerations'' in the Reagan and
Bush administrations, the committee cited a change in CDC
statistics gathering.
   Five years ago, it said, the CDC stopped comparing the mortality
and morbidity of women who had abortions with women carrying
pregnancy to term. Comparisons had indicated women were between
seven and 25 times more likely to die from childbirth than from
legal abortion, the report said.
   Jim Brown, a spokesman for James Mason, assistant secretary for
health at HHS, said that while Mason was director of CDC from 1983
until last winter, ``there was not censorship on the abortion
issue.''
   Six Republican House members filed a dissent, charging the
report was written with ``pro-abortion bias'' and ``paints a
misleading and inaccurate picture.''
   The panel conducted an investigation into the efforts by the
Reagan administration to have its surgeon general, C. Everett Koop,
prepare a report on the health effects of abortion on women. After
conducting meetings and research, Koop in January wrote to
President Reagan saying there was insufficient information on which
to base a report.
   A draft of Koop's unreleased report was made public by the
subcommittee in March. It concluded that valid scientific studies
have documented that modern abortion is a medically safe procedure
and does not increase a woman's subsequent risk of infertility,
miscarriage or premature births. It concluded the frequency of
long-term psychological effects is uncertain, however.
   In releasing its final report, the panel included material from
transcripts it subpoenaed of 27 confidential meetings Koop held
with anti-abortion and abortion-rights advocates.
   According to the subcommittee, Koop stated in those meetings
that legal abortion was safer than pregnancy and childbirth and
posed no public health risks to women's mental or physical health.
It concluded Koop's letter to Reagan was ``not consistent with the
weight of evidence'' or Koop's own statements on health effects of
abortion.
   Koop did not respond to a reporter's call for comment last week.
   The report cited CDC evidence that the risk of death from
abortion doubles every two weeks after eight weeks gestation, and
that after the 16th week the risks are similar to those for
childbirth.
   Don Berreth, a spokesman for the CDC in Atlanta, declined to
comment on the report Sunday, saying officials there had not seen
it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Singh Bjt   12-11 0914</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Singh, Bjt,0937</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Prime Minister Out To Prove He's In Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   V.P. Singh, the man who reluctantly
agreed to become prime minister of India, has set out to prove he's
in control.
   As head of India's first minority government, Singh doesn't have
a blank check to launch the revolutionary economic and social
reforms that could allow India to join the ranks of the great
powers in the next century.
   But political observers and associates say the 58-year-old prime
minister has two things working in his favor _ a clean slate and a
clean name.
   Within a week of taking the oath of office, Singh had reassured
two embittered religious minorities they indeed have an important
place in officially secular, predominantly Hindu India.
   He appointed influential colleagues to lower-ranking Cabinet
posts, thereby denying them new power bases. The more powerful
posts went to men with the experience to push through change and
the reputations for incorruptibility.
   Singh's five-party National Front coalition denied Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi's Congress Party a majority in the Nov. 22-26
elections and brought down the Nehru family dynasty that dominated
Indian politics since the country became independent from Britain
42 years ago.
   But Singh needs the continuing allegiance of both the Hindu
fundamentalists and the Communists for his middle-of-the-road
alliance to muster a majority in Parliament.
   Given the fragilility of this alliance, many political observers
are skeptical of the new government's ability to enact any major
changes in the world's largest democracy, a country of 880 million
people skewed between abject poverty and space-age achievements.
   The problems Singh inherited are enormous, but the
mild-mannered, introverted politician who reluctantly agreed to
head India's newest government has not been shy about what he
intends to accomplish.
   He lists his missions thus: to eliminate poverty, halt rising
food prices that have doubled in the past year, decentralize
federal power, reduce bureaucratic regulations and political
meddling, open the economy to Western investors eager to do
business with India and patch up differences with neighboring
Pakistan, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
   Foreign policy is a low priority for change.
   Singh has said he will not deviate from the course India has
already charted between the world's superpowers. India, he said,
will remain non-aligned and continue to build on its friendly
relations with Moscow and Washington.
   The first major test of Singh's government _ provided it
survives a confidence vote in Parliament later this month _ will
come during legislative elections in nine states in March and
April. All but two of the states now are dominated by Gandhi's
Congress Party.
   ``If Congress loses, it will split and the National Front
alliance will become stronger. If Congress defends its territory,
it will give renewed confidence to Gandhi and his party and weaken
our coalition. Then any constructive cooperation between us and the
opposition will end,'' said one National Front member, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   But analysts say Singh's most immediate problems stem from
factional disputes within his own Janata Dal, or People's Party,
the largest group in the five-party National Front. Those
differences surfaced again recently during wrangling for Cabinet
posts.
   Singh appointed a Moslem as head of the powerful Home Ministry,
a move seen as an attempt to span the growing rifts between the
majority Hindus and the minority Moslems that erupted into riots in
which at 300 people were killed this fall.
   Later, he visited the northern state of Punjab, the hotbed of
the Sikh separatist movement, and offered prayers at the Sikhs'
holiest shrine, the Golden Temple. The visit by Singh, a Hindu, was
the first by an Indian prime minister in more than five years and
an effort to end the bloody secessionist campaign that has claimed
more than 12,000 lives since 1982.
   ``A nation is not a map on a piece of paper,'' Singh later said.
``It lives in the hearts of the people, and if the hearts are
divided, the nation stands divided. We will not allow this to
happen.''
   Despite speculation that Singh would keep the finance portfolio,
which he held for two years under Gandhi, he gave it to a veteran
lawmaker who is expected to continue, if not speed up, the reforms
Singh sees as needed to make India a competitor in the world
markets.
   Instead, Singh kept the defense portfolio, a signal that he will
wield considerable power since defense spending has received the
biggest chunk of the national budget.
   The move prompted speculation Singh would be directly involved
in investigation into controversial arms deals during the Gandhi
administration.
   Government corruption was the linchpin in the National Front's
campaign against Gandhi and the Congress Party and earned Singh the
nickname, ``The New Mr. Clean,'' a reference to similar promises
that Gandhi made to clean up India's bureacracy.
   Gandhi was buffeted by accusations that highly placed Indians
received up to $50 million in kickbacks from the Swedish arms firm
AB Bofors, winner of a 1986 contract to sell $1.4 billion worth of
howitzers to the Indian government.
   Gandhi's denials that any Indians profited from the Bofors deal
paled before detailed newspaper investigations, but the accusations
have not been proved.
   Singh said there will be an investigation, but not a vendetta.
   ``I want to make it clear that we will not be vindictive,''
Singh said. ``No scandal will be cooked up against him or anyone
else. The law of the land will prevail.''
</TEXT>
