<FIRST>r p PM-LelandSeat     12-11 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leland Seat,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rep. Mickey Leland's Successor Talks About Re-Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Sen. Craig Washington was already talking
about being re-elected to Congress shortly after he won a runoff to
fill the unexpired term of Rep. Mickey Leland.
   Washington, 48, said he wants his name added to March's
Democratic primary ballot for the seat, which was left vacant in
August when his fellow Democrat was killed in a plane crash while
on an Ethiopian famine relief mission.
   Washington's opponent in Saturday's runoff, Democrat Anthony
Hall, said he was unsure whether he would contest the race.
   ``I haven't even thought about it,'' said Hall, a 45-year-old
city councilman. ``I'll think about it in the next week or so.''
   Washington won the non-partisan runoff by 57-43 percent.
   The two emerged as the top vote-getters in a field of 11
candidates in the Nov. 7 special election.
   Despite his interest in retaining his new post, Washington said
he won't take his seat until the Texas Legislature settles the
issue of workers' compensation.
   Washington, a 17-year veteran of the Legislature, is a key
backer of a compensation bill favored by workers and opposed by
business.
   Lawmakers are considering the bill in a special session that
ends at midnight Wednesday. Gov. Bill Clements has said he will
extend the session if an agreement isn't reached by then.
</TEXT>
