<FIRST>r a PM-BushHuntingTrip     12-11 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Hunting Trip,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Townfolk Await President's Annual Hunting Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEEVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He'll come in out of the sky, then
quickly disappear. Folks here have been looking forward to his
annual visit, and some are even thinking of treats for him to eat.
   Santa?
   No, President Bush.
   For 25 years, Bush has been coming to hunt at the Lazy F ranch
of Will Farish. The annual chase for scurrying quail is scheduled
this year for the week after Christmas.
   Even though he has a complement of press and Secret Service
agents, Bush manages to pull a disappearing act. He arrives at
nearby Chase Field Naval Air Station, then vanishes onto the ranch.
   ``I didn't know he was here last year until after he left,''
said Sherry Cruz, a Bee County courthouse secretary.
   ``Actually, to get to the ranch he hunts on, I don't think he
even comes through town,'' said County Judge Bill Streitman.
   But people have ways of knowing when he's around. For instance,
Rosie Moya stays a little busier at her Moya's Mexican Cafe. She
said she will have to stock extra food and hire extra help again
just to handle the business during this year's three-day visit.
   Last year, Ms. Moya served ``Bush burgers'' with plenty of
jalapenos to the entourage that accompanied the president. The cafe
is the only restaurant in Berclair, a small town northeast of
Beeville that is near Farish's ranch.
 
</TEXT>
