<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Riot 1stLd-Writethru a0775 12-11 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Riot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0775,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Opposition March Turns Into Riot; 1 Dead, 20 Reported Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with reports of one killed, details,
quotes from witnesses. ADDS byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto MGA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASATEPE, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A campaign march by hundreds of
opposition supporters turned into a riot Sunday. Police said at
least one person was killed and witnesses said 20 people were
injured.
   Two vehicles were burned, and a private home and the local
headquarters of the ruling Sandinista Front were sacked.
   The fighting broke out during a rally by the National Opposition
Union, or UNO, when a group of about 20 Sandinista loyalists and
opposition followers exchanged insults and then blows in this town
of 15,000 people about 30 miles south of Managua.
   Sandinistas accused sympathizers of the opposition coalition of
starting the riot.
   Opposition leaders admitted their people took part but accused
the Sandinistas of provoking the riot, saying Sandinista
infiltrators posing as opposition militants encouraged the attack
on the houses and vehicles.
   The local organizer of the opposition coalition, Jeremias
Mahmud, said he saw a police officer draw his gun and shoot a man
in the arm.
   Lt. Fernando Montoya, the Masatepe police chief, said police
were following orders in not intervening in the riot until it was
nearly over.
   ``We had instructions not to get near the march,'' Montoya said.
``Going to the disturbances meant giving them (UNO) a pretext to
say that we were there to repress them.''
   National Opposition Union leaders have accused Sandinista gangs
of disrupting earlier opposition rallies for the Feb. 25 elections.
   Montoya said one person was killed, but did not elaborate.
Witnesses said at least 20 people were injured.
   Witnesses said groups of opposition activists attacked a house
that was used by the Sandinistas as a campaign office as well as
another nearby house. They said some activists set fire to a
motorcycle and to a jeep with license plates from the U.N. Food and
Agriculture Organization.
   Mahmud, the opposition coalition organizer, said he arrived as
opposition sympathizers were stoning the Sandinista headquarters.
He said a Sandinista from the nearby town of La Concepcion was
leading the mob.
   ``I told them that this man was an infiltrator and they beat him
up,'' Mahmud said. ``In the fray, he dropped this pin and I grabbed
it and showed it to them.''
   Mahmud showed an enamel-and-gold pin commemorating the 10th
anniversary of the Sandinista revolution. Such pins are awarded by
the Sandinista Front for meritorious service to the party.
   He said the man, whose name he did not know, fled.
   Mahmud said by the time he tried to calm the mob, police had
arrived. He said a 9-year-old girl who was walking next to him
during the march was hit on the head by a rock ``which was meant
for me'' and she was knocked out.
   He said at least three men were stabbed and other people were
attacked with broken bottles and hit with stones and sticks.
   Ricardo Lopez Cerda, a Sandinista campaign committee member,
said he and 12 other people were in the party headquarters when it
was attacked by a mob of about 200 people. He said they escaped
through a back room.
   After destroying furniture and other articles in the Sandinista
headquarters, the crowd moved to the second building, allowing its
occupants to leave before stoning it.
   Both buildings were heavily damaged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
