<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Salvador-Casolo     12-11 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Casolo,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Try to Win American's Release From El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends of an American woman being held in El Salvador have
recorded four songs on her behalf, and the Rev. Jesse Jackson said
he plans to meet with Salvadoran and U.S. officials to help gain
her release.
   Jackson said he hoped to have the meetings concerning
28-year-old Jennifer J. Casolo this week. She is being held on
suspicion of helping leftist insurgents after authorities uncovered
a weapons cache that was buried in the garden of her rented San
Salvador home.
   She has insisted that she knew nothing about the weapons.
   ``Jennifer, you are not alone,'' Jackson told the several
hundred people at an ecumenical service Sunday at St. Joseph's
Cathedral in Hartford, Conn.
   ``We shall seek to meet with the Salvadoran ambassador to this
country. We shall seek to meet with (State Department) personnel in
this country. We shall seek to visit you. We shall seek to bring
you home.''
   There was no answer early today at El Salvador's embassy in
Washington.
   Casolo's father, John, asked the audience to join him in prayer.
   ``I would like you all to bow your heads and pray for the
release of my daughter,'' he said. ``Please send Jennifer home soon
safely to us. ... I know she's doing your work, and I know she's
innocent.''
   The four-song cassette, ``For Jennifer,'' was recorded Saturday
by folk singer Michael Stern. He said he plans to send it Casolo in
the Salvadoran prison.
   The cassette also is being sent to radio stations around the
United States.
   Stern said he met Casolo six years ago at University Baptist
Church in Seattle, where she lived for two years and was active in
the sanctuary movement of harboring illegal aliens fleeing turmoil
in Central America.
   Casolo, of Thomaston, Conn., went to El Salvador in 1985 to work
for Christian Education Seminars, a group dedicated to influencing
U.S. policy by organizing fact-finding tours for Americans.
   ``There's no doubt in my mind as a personal friend of hers that
she is totally innocent,'' said Stern, 36, a nurse at the
University of Washington student health clinic. ``She's a religious
person. She's committed to non-violence.''
</TEXT>
