<FIRST>r w PM-US-Soviet     12-11 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Received Secret Report on Soviet Military Cuts in May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, who until last month
maintained that Soviet defense spending was growing, received a
classified Pentagon report in May in which U.S. intelligence
analysts expressed the opposite view, a published report says.
   Bush ordered the secret study of U.S. defense strategy shortly
after his election as an aid for dealing with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, The Washington Post reported in today's
editions.
   A 26-page executive summary of the report states that ``there is
broad agreement within the U.S. intelligence community'' that the
Soviet Union under Gorbachev ``has decided to reverse a 20-year
pattern of growth in Soviet military spending and force structure
in order to boost the civil economy and Soviet foreign policy.''
   Until a month ago, Bush and senior advisers criticized what they
said was an increase in Soviet defense spending as they pressed
Congress to approve the nearly $300 billion defense budget for
fiscal 1990.
   Meanwhile, Bush said in interviews released Sunday that he
gained ``more respect'' for Gorbachev at the Malta summit and
thinks he can trust the Soviet leader.
   Gorbachev is ``up against some tremendous problems and is
determined to solve them,'' Bush told Newsweek magazine.
   Asked if his view of Gorbachev had changed, Bush replied,
``There is certainly an element of respect for the way he has
managed the change in Eastern Europe and (his) determination to
fight for perestroika reform at home.
   ``I have more respect for him than I did back when he first came
into office, back when I first met him or when I saw him last
year.''
   Perestroika, the Russian word for restructuring, is shorthand
for the economic changes that Gorbachev is pushing to revive the
ailing Soviet economy.
   ``I think I can trust Gorbachev,'' Bush said in an interview in
Time magazine. ``I looked him in the eye, I appraised him. He was
very determined. Yet there was a twinkle. He is a guy quite sure of
what he is doing. He has got a political feel.''
</TEXT>
