<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0782 12-11 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0782,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Close Higher in Tokyo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against the yen in Tokyo
Monday, while stock prices also rose.
   The dollar closed at 144.65 yen, up 0.38 yen from its 144.27-yen
close on Friday and slightly higher than its opening of 144.50 yen.
It ranged between 144.45 and 144.73 yen during the day.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues gained 28.61 points, closing at 37,752.67. On
Friday, the index lost 134.05 points after marking new highs on
each of the previous four days.
   In the currency market, the dollar was apparently bolstered by
dollar-buying intervention by the Bank of Japan shortly after the
market opened and by purchases by major trading companies, dealers
said.
   A large number of export contracts usually due for settlement on
Monday tightened demand for the dollar in the morning, dealers
said. The Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank, does not
comment on its market activities.
   ``There is no particular (market-affecting) news'' this morning,
said Shinzo Yamamoto, a dealer with Daiwa Bank. He indicated,
however, that Tokyo dealers were taking their cue from a
strengthening of the dollar in New York on Friday.
   Trading got off to a slow start on the Tokyo Stock Exchange as
participants waited to see the market's performance after its
strong advances last week, traders said.
   After opening lower, the Nikkei rebounded toward the end of the
morning session on buying of natural resource-oriented shares, they
said.
   Volume was estimated at 380 million shares, down from an
estimated 550 million shares Friday.
</TEXT>
