<FIRST>r a PM-CollegeRacism     12-11 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-College Racism,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>5 Weeks After Racial Incident, MacMurray College has Quieted Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH OKESON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five weeks after racist letters were
sent to black students at MacMurray College, the incident has
prompted race-awareness activities and, some say, a new climate on
the campus.
   ``Before the letters, there was a lot of tension, but now it's
suppressed, and everybody's making an effort,'' said Kevin Ray, a
black freshman at the small liberal-arts school.
   ``I think before the letters MacMurray was to some extent a
closed community with the blacks on the outside looking in,'' said
Ricky Bragg, a black sophomore. ``Since the letters, I've noticed a
lot more interaction between blacks and whites.''
   On Nov. 2, letters containing racial slurs and threats were
found in campus mailboxes of the 35 to 40 black students at the
620-student school, as well as that of the college's only black
staff member.
   The letters were addressed to students by name and campus mail
box number. They contained epithets such as ``Uncle Tom'' and slurs
specifically tailored to each recipient, according to students who
saw the letters.
   Four days later, students marched in protest across the campus
of the private college in west-central Illinois.
   Jacksonville Police Chief Tom Weeks says his department hasn't
identified a suspect, although police were able to take
fingerprints from the letters.
   ``It's pretty much a dead issue right now,'' Weeks said.
   Student body president Michelle Sharp holds little hope that the
culprit will be found.
   ``I don't think we'll ever know who wrote the letters,'' said
Ms. Sharp, a junior majoring in education for the deaf. ``I don't
think it would be possible to fingerprint everyone on campus.''
   Ms. Sharp, who is white, said it may be best that the writer
remain unknown.
   ``If it's a white student, it's going to cause a lot of tension
between blacks and whites,'' she said. ``If it's a black student,
the blacks will be embarrassed. I think many students would feel
better not knowing.''
   Since the letter-writing, there haven't been any racial
incidents reported on campus. The college has sponsored a forum for
students to talk about racism, and seminars on cultural diversity
and a workshop on racism are in the works. Officials say more
classes may include subjects of black interest.
   The student government is planning an ethnic festival and the
sale of T-shirts promoting racial equality, and the administration
plans to make Martin Luther King's birthday a holiday.
   College president Edward Mitchell said he wants to recruit more
black faculty members but that it's difficult because blacks who
receive doctoral degrees are intensely sought by other colleges.
   ``It's just very difficult because of the small number in the
pipeline and because in a school of this size and in a town this
size there's just not the support network of other professional
minorities,'' Mitchell said.
   ``Our best hope to recruit additional role models is going to be
from our own students, and that's going to take a while.''
   Philosophy professor Richard Palmer said the incident gave a
false picture of MacMurray, which he said has traditionally
welcomed black students.
   Black senior Marquita Archie, who said she cried each day for
five days after the incident, said the letters reflected the bias
that is everywhere.
   Ms. Sharp, the student body president, said the students now
realize that.
   ``I think it affected the majority of the students on campus and
opened a lot of students' eyes about racial tension,'' she said.
``I know it opened mine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
