<FIRST>r a PM-RhodesScholars Bjt   12-11 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rhodes Scholars, Bjt,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>32 Americans Selected as Rhodes Scholars</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY22 of Dec. 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A women's basketball player who tutors
Cambodian refugees and a woman who worked in a Brazilian orphanage
were among 32 Americans to join the ranks of Rhodes Scholars.
   The 18 men and 14 women selected Sunday receive two years of
study at Oxford University in England.
   Yale and Princeton universities led with four each, Harvard had
three, and Georgetown, Kansas State University and the U.S.
Military Academy at West Point, N.Y., each had two.
   The winners were chosen from among 102 finalists interviewed
last week by the Rhodes Scholarship Trust, whose American branch is
based at Pomona College in suburban Claremont.
   ``It was one of the most nerve-wracking experiences I've had,''
said Yale's Michael Warren, a history major from Blacksburg, Va.,
who plans to study modern liberal political philosophy.
   Other winners were Bridget Clarke, a philosophy major at the
University of Montana who has worked in shelters for battered women
and the homeless in Missoula; and Suzanne Lee Corley, who majors in
religion, Spanish and French at Presbyterian College in Clinton,
S.C., and worked in the orphanage in Brazil.
   Ms. Corley, 21, said her family was ``incredulous'' upon hearing
of the honor. ``I've applied for so many other scholarships and
haven't gotten them,'' she said.
   Andrew John Dechet of Vancouver, Wash., who studied flamenco
guitar in Spain with Gypsies, is a Germanic language and literature
major at Princeton.
   ``I've sort of recovered from the shock by now,'' he said.
   Dechet said he has been to England once before _ on a plane
layover just long enough to get ``sick on the fish and chips.''
   ``I'm trying to contain it as much as possible,'' said Paul W.
Muench, Jr., a 22-year-old psychology and philosophy major at Reed
College in Portland, Ore. ``When I found out, I was really
dumbfounded and very excited about the whole thing. I'm still kind
of in a state of disbelief.''
   Amy Deane Matthews, an English major and member of Mount Holyoke
College's varsity basketball and crew teams, tutors Cambodian
refugees. Rhodes officials said she has a perfect academic record.
   West Point's recipients are women. Jennie Koch, of Potomac, Md.,
ranks fifth in her class as an international relations major, and
is considering a career in public service with an emphasis on
foreign policy.
   Carolyn A. Ford of Pensacola, Fla., who was appointed to the
academy through the enlisted ranks, is a specialist in Chinese. She
also is a brigade swimming champion, a graduate of the Airborne
School, and a battalion commander. She plans a career in military
intelligence.
   Rhodes Scholars were chosen from 17 other countries.
   Winners must be unmarried and between ages 18 and 24.
Recipients' school fees are paid and they receive a stipend for
expenses.
   Among the qualities sought are proven intellectual and academic
excellence, integrity, respect for others, and the ability to lead
and to use talents fully.
   Athletic prowess also is sought as ``an indicator of the stamina
a person must have to act energetically as a leader and to work for
other people,'' said David Alexander, American secretary of the
trust and Pomona president.
   Rhodes scholarships were established in 1902 by the estate of
Cecil Rhodes, the British philanthropist and colonialist. Rhodes
had hoped the scholarships would contribute to world understanding
and peace. Women have been eligible since 1976.
   The scholarships have gone to 2,564 Americans, including Sen.
Bill Bradley, D-N.J., entertainer Kris Kristofferson, former Los
Angeles Rams quarterback Pat Haden and U.S. Supreme Court Justice
Byron White.
</TEXT>
