<FIRST>r a PM-AntarcticaTrek     12-11 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antarctica Trek,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antarctica Team Expected to Reach South Pole This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international ski and dog sled team
trekking across Antarctica is expected to reach the South Pole this
week, according to an expedition spokeswoman.
   ``They are about 50 miles from the pole right now, and they have
been averaging 25 miles per day,'' the spokeswoman, Jennifer
Kimball Gasperini, said Sunday. They could reach the pole tonight
or Tuesday, she said.
   The St. Paul-based International Trans-Antarctica Expedition
already has traveled more than 1,900 miles since leaving the
northern tip of the Antarctic Peninsula on July 27.
   The men and dogs trudged the length of the treacherous peninsula
in winter, never tried before.
   The group's co-leader, Will Steger of Minnesota, made history
three years ago when he led a similar assault on the North Pole.
   ABC-TV scuttled plans to broadcast live from the South Pole, but
hopes to rush out fresh video for the third of its five prime-time
specials on the expedition, to be aired next Sunday.
   For all the fanfare, the South Pole is little more than a
milepost. The goal is to reach Mirnyy, a Soviet science station on
the continent's Indian Ocean shore. That's another 1,600 miles and
three months to complete the $11 million, seven-month journey.
   ``I say Mirnyy or die,'' Steger said earlier.
   The expedition's other members are co-leader Jean-Louis Etienne
of France, Victor Boyarsky from the Soviet Union, Geoff Somers from
Great Britain, Keizo Funatsu from Japan and Qin Dahe from China.
</TEXT>
