<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0612EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-US     12-11 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-US,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Says Scowcroft Visit Will Help Improve Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's official media today heralded the visit
of National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft and quoted Deng
Xiaoping and other leaders as saying the time had come to restore
good relations with the United States.
   The surprise one-day visit by over the weekend effectively ended
a U.S. ban on high-level exchanges imposed after Beijing
authorities sent in the military to crush the pro-democracy
movement in June.
   Both sides expressed their hopes for a truce in recent
U.S.-Chinese feuding, with Deng saying good relations are crucial
for world peace and security. However, no concrete measures to ease
frictions between the two sides were announced.
   The ruling Communist Party's official People's Daily today
carried two lengthy front-page stories on Scowcroft's meetings with
Chinese leaders, including three separate pictures of the American
emissary with Deng, Premier Li Peng, and party chief Jiang Zemin.
   ``Deng Xiaoping Says Sino-U.S. Relations Should Finally
Improve,'' one headline said.
   It noted that Jiang spoke of the ``broad prospects'' for
cooperation and Li said both countries should ``do more practical
work'' to improve relations.
   Li's remarks were at variance with previous Chinese statements
that the United States was entirely at fault for strained ties and
must take the initiative in normalizing relations.
   However, a U.S. official said it ``remains to be seen'' whether
the good intentions expressed by both sides will result in any
substantive progress in resolving conflicts.
   Those include U.S. concerns over China's human rights record and
the issue of astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, the pro-democracy dissident
who has been hiding in the U.S. Embassy with his wife, Li Shuxian,
since June and who is wanted by Chinese police as a
``counterrevolutionary.''
   There is also speculation that Beijing will retaliate against
U.S. measures to extend the visas of Chinese students in the United
States by halting widely popular student exchange programs.
   In Washington, Secretary of State James A. Baker III defended
President Bush's decision to send the delegation six months after
China began its crackdown by driving protesters from Beijing's
Tiananmen Square.
   Hundreds of unarmed civilians were killed in the military attack.
   Speaking on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley'' program,
Baker said, ``The president ... deplores the tragedy of Tiananmen
Square. But he's of the view that we shouldn't run the risk of
compounding that tragedy by trying to isolate China from the
international community.''
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, was among congressional critics of the trip.
He said: ``At the very time that freedom is sweeping through
Eastern Europe, we should be sure the United States stands for
freedom and democracy in Asia as well.''
   Bush suspended high-level exchanges and military-related sales
and contacts after troops fought their way into Beijing on June 4,
driving pro-democracy protesters out of the city center.
   He also joined other Western leaders in supporting cancellation
of talks on new development loans to China.
   Scowcroft, accompanied by Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger, also briefed the Chinese on the Malta summit and other
international issues before leaving Sunday for Tokyo, where they
briefed Chinese leaders on the visit. He was to return to
Washington today.
</TEXT>
