<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Argentina     12-11 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Devalues Currency By More Than Half, Raises Fuel Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort to cool an
overheated economy, the government has cut the value of the
currency by more than half and ordered sharp fuel price increases.
   The Economy Ministry, in a communique issued minutes before
midnight Sunday, said it was making ``corrections'' in the economic
policy followed by the government of President Carlos Menen since
his July 8 inauguration.
   All banks and currency exchange houses were ordered closed today
so the economic adjustments could be made more smoothly.
   The corrections were required, the ministry said, ``to combat
disturbances experienced in the exchange market in recent weeks.''
   The Ministry said it would devalue the austral by 53.4 percent _
setting the official value of the national currency at 1,000 to one
U.S. dollar, compared to the 650-1 official rate in effect since
July 10.
   The official exchange market will be used for sale and purchase
of dollars in export-import and financial operations, the ministry
said.
   At the same time, the ministry said, it will permit the
operation of a ``free'' exchange market for all other dollar
transactions on which the value of the austral will be allowed to
float.
   An illegal although widely tolerated black market previously had
operated in Argentina and a widening gap between the official and
black market values of the dollar had provoked concern in recent
weeks.
   On Thursday, the dollar sold for 1,020 australs on the black
market, compared to the official value of 655.
   The ministry also announced that the price of regular gasoline
would rise by 61 percent to the equivalent of $1.44 per gallon.
   Economy Minister Nestor Rapanelli said new rates for public
utilities, such as telephones, natural gas and electricity, would
be announced today.
   Current public service rates were set July 9 when they were
increased by 200 percent, and were to have remained frozen for all
of 1990.
   The communique, issued after Menem met for three hours with his
Cabinet, also announced a $30 monthly pay increase for public
employes and a $24 raise for the private sector.
   The communique said the Treasury will cease to provide aid in
financing deficits of state companies and provincial governments.
   The government has moved cautiously on the issue of modifying
current economic policy. A devaluation was considered likely to
fuel price increases, wage demands and inflation. Also, higher
utility bills and transport fares might erode public support for
the 5-month-old government.
   The cost of living, which soared to nearly 200 percent in July,
had dropped by 5.6 percent in October, but rose by 6.5 percent in
November. Independent economists predicted the December rate could
be in double digits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
