<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     12-11 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Obstacle to Israeli-Arab Talks, Nine Palestinians Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a move that could further delay the first
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, Israel is asking stronger U.S.
assurances the PLO will not be involved, officials said today.
   Israeli wants the new assurances before Foreign Minister Moshe
Arens agrees to attend a preliminary meeting in Washington expected
to work out a Palestinian delegation to the first direct talks with
Israeli representatives, officials said.
   In the occupied lands, meanwhile, soldiers today shot and
wounded seven Palestinians in clashes with stone-throwing youths,
Arab reports said.
   The confrontations were touched off by the fatal shootings of
two Palestinians Sunday, apparently by Israeli civilians who opened
fire after attacks on their vehicles by stone-throwers, Israeli and
Arab reports said.
   A total of 631 Palestinians have been killed by Israelis during
the 2-year-old uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip. At least 155 other Palestinians have been killed by
fellow Arabs as alleged collaborators with Israel. Forty-three
Israelis also have died.
   The army also said troops on Sunday night demolished the homes
of three suspects in the slaying of an alleged Palestinian
collaborator with Israel.
   In comments on army radio, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said he
still was suspicious that Egypt was indirectly representing the
Palestine Liberation Organization. ``If this is what will be, I
fear that we won't get very far,'' Arens said.
   Arens had planned a trip to Washington next month for a meeting
with U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Egypt's foreign
minister, Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
   Asked about the Washington trip today, Arens said, ``Firstly,
I'm not going yet. We will first conduct contacts concerning the
guarantees that our Cabinet has asked.''
   Avi Pazner, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's spokesman, said
Cabinet Secretary Eliakim Rubinstein would go to Washington later
this week to discuss the promise sought by Israel.
   Israel had asked U.S. guarantees against any PLO role last month
in its acceptance of Baker's proposal for the Washington meeting.
   The latest possible obstacle to talks followed weekend news
reports that secret contacts already were under way among Israeli,
Egyptian, American and Palestinian officials to draw up a list of
Palestinian negotiators.
   A PLO spokesman in Cairo, Said Kamal, was quoted in the Yediot
Ahronot daily today as saying the organization had been asked to
draw up three lists of names for presentation to the Israelis.
   On Sunday, the newspaper listed some of the Palestinians under
consideration as east Jerusalem activist Faisal Husseini,
journalist and union leader Radwan Abu Ayyash, newspaper editor
Hannah Siniora, and Assad Saftawi, a school principle in Gaza City.
   Saftawi confirmed the reported behind-the-scenes contacts to The
Associated Press and said he was heading to Cairo for talks on the
subject.
   But Pazner denied the report, saying the contacts had not
reached the stage of putting together a list of negotiators.
</TEXT>
