<HEAD>Palestinians Must Choose Their Envoys to Peace Talks, Arafat Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Incorporates correction in a0485 to make verb in 3rd graf `criticized'
sted `rejected'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians should be able to choose their
own representatives at U.S.-backed talks between Israel and
Palestinians on the Middle East peace process, says PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat.
   Israel has said it will refuse to negotiate with anyone
connected with Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization, which
the Israelis consider a terrorist group.
   The PLO has criticized the U.S.-backed plan for a dialogue in
Cairo that could lead to elections in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   Asked about Israel's refusal to negotiate with the PLO, Arafat
said, ``With whom they are going to make peace? With ghosts?''
   Arafat was speaking by satellite from Baghdad, Iraq, on NBC-TV's
``Meet the Press,'' which was taped Saturday and aired Sunday.
   Asked if he could assure Israel that a Palestinian state would
pose no threat to the Jewish state, Arafat replied, ``We want to
live in peace with all our neighbors, including the Israelis.''
   ``We are looking for a brave man, a brave leader among the
Israeli leadership, to accept, to start the peace processes, to
implement real peace in the land of peace,'' he said.
   He acknowledged that if a Palestinian state were created, it
would seek to confederate with Jordan.
   ``The Palestinians and their leadership have the right to
designate their representatives, as well as the Israeli government
will designate their delegation,'' he said.
   ``If they want the PLO to participate in this negotiation,
definitely, we have the right,'' the PLO chairman said.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir in May proposed that
elections be held in the occupied territories to allow Palestinians
to choose their own representatives under a plan for limited
self-rule. Shamir ruled out Israeli withdrawal or recognition of a
Palestinian state.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak proposed a 10-point
modification of Shamir's plan under which Israel would accept the
idea of trading land for peace. He later called for hold direct
Israeli-Palestinian talks in Cairo.
   U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III then formulated his
own five-point plan to advance the negotiations, which both Israel
and Egypt agreed to with reservations.
