<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Lenin 1stLd-Writethru a0488 12-11 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Lenin, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battered And Burned By Demonstrators, Lenin Quietly Removed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at end with Jaruzelski condemning attacks, Lenin
museum closed in Krakow.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in the southern steel town of
Nowa Huta have quietly removed a statue of Vladimir I. Lenin that
youthful demonstrators have repeatedly defaced and tried to destroy.
   The removal was ordered Friday after demonstrations the past two
Wednesdays in which youths who threw paint and flammable liquids on
the monument clashed with police, who used water cannon and tear
gas to disperse them.
   The state PAP news agency said the 30-foot statue was emoved
from its plinth and ``in perfect condition transported to the
locality of Wroblowice ... For necessary conservation works.''
   Its future will be be decided by the municipal and district
councils, PAP said, but it is unlikely that anyone in Nowa Huta
will want it back.
   The monument to the founder of the Soviet state, placed on a
central square, had been the centerpiece of the city built around a
huge steel mill outside Krakow in the 1950s as a model socialist
community.
   For residents of Nowa Huta, a Solidarity stronghold, it has long
been a despised symbol of Poland's past forced dependence on the
Soviet Union.
   The attacks by the youthful demonstrators had created a delicate
problem for the non-Communist government of Prime Minister Taduesz
Mazowiecki.
   The Solidarity-led government is trying to maintain good
relations with the Soviet Union and said it would not tolerate more
violence. Mediators had called on the local government to move
quickly to remove the monument.
   The statue has suffered several ignoble attacks over the years.
In 1979 it was dynamited by activists and had to be rebuilt by
Communist authorities.
   A spokesman for Communist President Wojciech Jaruzelski said the
``acts of vandalism ... met with his highest condemnation.''
   ``He believes these acts are manifestations of exceptional
rampant fury. They do harm to the good name of Poland worldwide,
not only to the good relations with the Soviet Union,'' said the
spokesman, Wlodzimierz Losinski.
   The cultural commission of the Krakow city council on Saturday
also closed the city's Lenin Museum and another cultural
institution bearing his name, the pro-Solidarity Gazeta Wyborcza
newspaper reported today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
