<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionProtests     12-11 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Protests,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Operation Rescue Plans Renewed Anti-Abortion Protests in Atlanta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operation Rescue leaders say they will bring
their anti-abortion activities back to Atlanta starting Friday,
including picketing at clinics and the homes of those perceived as
backers of legal abortions.
   Thousands of the group's followers have been arrested in
demonstrations across the country since Operation Rescue rose to
prominence in Atlanta with demonstrations during the 1988
Democratic National Convention.
   ``We are going to have rescues and they are going to be
reinforced,'' said Michael Hirsh, Atlanta director of Operation
Rescue. ``It's going to be a concerted effort from a number of
different directions.''
   Crowd control has been taken from the Atlanta Police
Department's 5th Precinct and given to the Special Operations
division.
   Division chief Maj. W.W. Holley said officers will be taken from
other details such as robbery stakeouts to keep order.
   ``We will give them a reasonable time to disperse from the
property and if they refuse they will be subject to arrest,'' he
said.
   Holley said the behavior of the demonstrators will determine
whether controversial, painful ``come-along'' holds are used in
making arrests. Police were criticized for overuse of the tactics
in some previous demonstrations.
   Pro-choice groups say they will hold counterdemonstrations
wherever Operation Rescue appears.
   Operation Rescue's national director, Randall Terry, is serving
a two-year term in a state prison north of Atlanta for his part in
past demonstrations. He chose the jail term over a fine and
banishment from the Atlanta area.
</TEXT>
