<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Casino     12-11 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Casino,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nevada Casino Owner Loses Appeal in Bank Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by
a former gambling casino owner convicted of bank fraud and ordered
to pay $7.5 million in restitution.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling against
businessman Ronald Cloud stemming from the 1985 sale of his
hotel-casino complex in the Lake Tahoe area on the
California-Nevada border.
   Cloud purchased the complex, the Cal-Neva Lodge, for $10 million
in 1980 and decided to sell it a few years later because of
mounting operating losses.
   Jon Perroton agreed to buy the complex for $17 million. But
Perroton got a $20 million loan from the Hibernia Bank to finance
the purchase after misrepresenting the sale price as $27.5 million.
   Perroton pleaded guilty to bank fraud and other charges, and was
sentenced to 20 years in prison.
   Cloud was convicted by a federal jury of aiding and abetting
bank fraud and conspiracy to commit bank fraud.
   He was placed on probation for five years, fined $500,000 and
ordered to pay $7.5 million to Continental Insurance Co. to
reimburse it for some of the money it paid to the Hibernia Bank.
   Cloud said he went along innocently with the phony loan amount
on assurances from Perroton that there was nothing wrong with it.
Cloud said he never intended to defraud the bank and was a victim
of Perroton's scheme.
   Cloud also said he should not be forced to pay the insurance
company $7.5 million because he previously reached a settlement
with the Hibernia Bank to repay it $1.5 million.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected his appeal last
April.
   The appeals court said there was sufficient evidence to convict
Cloud, and a federal judge who ordered the restitution acted under
proper authority granted by the federal Victim and Witness
Protection Act.
   The case is Cloud vs. U.S., 89-455.
</TEXT>
