<FIRST>r a PM-NAACPResignation     12-11 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NAACP Resignation,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Beverly Hills-Hollywood Chapter President Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The embattled president of the NAACP's
Beverly Hills-Hollywood chapter has resigned, just days before the
national organization begins an investigation into allegations he
mismanaged the chapter.
   Willis Edwards announced his resignation during the taping of
the Image Awards ceremony honoring blacks in the entertainment
industry and to be aired next month on NBC-TV.
   ``Two years ago I vowed that if the Image Awards would
successfully be on television for four years and if the Beverly
Hills-Hollywood NAACP developed a strong bond with the industry, my
job was done,'' Edwards said Saturday night during the taping at
the Wiltern Theater.
   But his resignation comes several days before an inquiry by the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People into
allegations Edwards mismanaged the chapter.
   Edwards was criticized for accepting $25,000 for helping produce
last year's Image Awards show. He has also drawn fire from some
chapter members for what they claim is his lack of aggressiveness
in pursuing civil rights issues and alleged mismanagement of
chapter funds.
   ``We're glad he resigned,'' said Connie Watson, leader of the
chapter's dissidents, on Sunday.
   Ms. Watson was one of several protesters who picketed outside
the Wiltern on Saturday night, waving placards that accused Edwards
with statements such as: ``What Have You Done For Civil Rights
Lately?''
   After his statement Saturday, Edwards would only say, ``I
resigned because I wanted to resign.''
   An NAACP national panel scheduled a Dec. 19 hearing in Hollywood
on the mismanagement allegations. Last September, chapter members
voted for Edwards' resignation after he accepted the $25,000 for
his work on the 1988 Image Awards show.
   Edwards has denied any wrongdoing.
   ``There has been lots of turmoil. We've got some bridges to
mend,'' said the new chapter president, Sandra Evers-Manly, who
will remain at the post until elections are held in 1990.
</TEXT>
