<FIRST>u i PM-Bulgaria 2ndLd-Writethru a0511 12-11 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bulgaria, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0511,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Committee Meets Amid Demands for Democratic Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Central Commitee meeting,
registration of first independent political group; Picks up 8th graf, `The
Central ...'; ADDS 3 grafs at end with further on Ecoglasnost.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communists' policy-setting Central
Committee met today following the nation's largest pro-democracy
rally in which tens of thousands of people demanded that party
leaders share power.
   Also today, the municipal court in Sofia approved the
registration application of Ecoglasnost, making the environmental
organization Bulgaria's first legal independent political group.
   Party leader Petar Mladenov opened the Central Committee session
with a speech on ``the situation in the country, the party and the
immediate tasks,'' the state news agency BTA said. The dispatch
gave no further details.
   About 5,000 people held a silent vigil in 14-degree temperatures
earlier in the day outside party headquarters to show the Communist
leadership the people were watching its work, according to
organizers.
   On Sunday, more than 50,000 people chanted ``Democracy!'' and
applauded demands for the Communist leadership to quit. It was the
biggest rally of its kind since Bulgaria's pro-democracy movement
began less than a month ago and since the party consolidated power
43 years ago.
   Many people held candles in the bright sunshine at today's
vigil, and a white, red and green Bulgarian flag waved on a
platform set up behind the Central Committee building.
   Police set up barriers to keep the gathering from disrupting
morning traffic, and a few officers stood at a distance around the
crowd. After one hour, the crowd dispersed quietly.
   Organizers said similar vigils would be held later today and on
Tuesday.
   The Central Committee meeting was expected to last at least two
days and focus on growing grass-roots demands for the kind of
democratic reforms that have swept Poland, Hungary, East Germany
and Czechoslovakia.
   The Central Committee also met Friday in a session that was not
announced, and 22 people were removed from the Committee and four
from the ruling Politburo.
   If the Committee were to resign, a new one would have to be
elected at a party congress.
   The Communist Party daily Rabotnichesko Delo today carried a
guest commentary in which the author urged an extraordinary
congress to be held as soon as posible and suggested the end of
February as a possible date.
   The paper said it had received more than 4,000 letters and
telephone calls from people demanding reforms since Nov. 10, when
Mladenov replaced Todor Zhivkov, who was Communist Party chief for
35 years.
   A poll conducted by a Central Committee polling group indicated
that only 23 percent of those questioned had a lot of trust in the
party, the newspaper reported.
   It said 1,513 people from 127 work collectives were questioned
in the poll, conducted Nov. 28.
   The newspaper said only 32 percent showed general trust in any
political organizations. It concluded that the Communists had
``discredited themselves in the eyes of the people,'' while
opposition groups had not had a chance to test their political
ability.
   Sunday's rally was organized by 19 independent groups that
drafted a resolution urging talks between the Communists and the
groups.
   Protesters waved their hands in the air to show approval of the
resolution, which recognized moves toward liberalization since
Zhivkov was ousted. But it complained that reform was too slow in
coming.
   Popular pressure for the party to give up its constitutionally
guaranteed leading role has been growing, and the crowd repeatedly
cheered that demand.
   Last week, Mladenov told a news conference in Moscow that he
foresaw changes in the constitution and indicated the party's
leading role was an open question.
   The municipal court in Sofia has previously rejected
Ecoglasnost's application for legal status as an independent
political group. It changed its mind three days before Parliament
is to meet to discuss issues including a proposed law on
associations.
   Ecoglasnost has played a key role in mobilizing people to press
for reforms. It also a member of the newly formed umbrella Union of
Democratic Forces, which comprises the 10 most influential
independent groups.
   Petar Slabokov, a well-known actor and the president of
Ecoglasnost, said one of the group's first projects will be to
determine whether the general health of people has been damaged by
air and river pollution.
</TEXT>
