<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0522 12-11 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Leader Calls Multi-Party System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 11th graf pvs, `Ultimatums and...' to
UPDATE with Slovenian president's comments on Serbia's action; Pickup 12th
graf pvs, `Croatia's state...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leadership of Yugoslavia's
second-largest state today for the first time called for the
establishment of a multiparty system in this Communist country.
   Communists have been slow in realizing the ``historic exhaustion
of the single-party system,'' Stanko Stojicevic, head of the
Croatian Communist Party's ruling presidium, said at the opening of
a regional party congress in the Croatian capital of Zagreb.
   ``There can be no democratic socialism without political
pluralism based on the right of association and competition of
political (movements) and programs,'' Stojicevic said in his
keynote speech carried by the state Tanjug news agency.
   Until now the liberal northern state of Slovenia was the only
one of Yugoslavia's six constituent republics to openly advocate
the introduction of Western-style democracy.
   About a dozen independent movements and parties have been set up
in Slovenia over the past year, and the region plans to hold its
first free legislative elections next March.
   On Sunday some 25,000 people in several Croatian cities signed a
petition urging legalization of numerous parties that would make
possible the holding of free elections in the republic bordering
Slovenia in the West.
   ``We consider that (Yugoslavia's new constitution) should
provide for a political system that will include ... parties and
movements representing the political interests of citizens,'' said
Stojicevic, according to a report broadcast by Zagreb radio.
   Croatia and some other republics have in the past been
non-committal about multiparty democracy, which is vehemently
opposed by the Communist leadership of the country's largest state
of Serbia.
   Earlier this month Serbia, in an apparent move to stifle
burgeoning democratic trends in the country, severed all business
and official ties with Slovenia. The unprecedented action shook the
foundations of Yugoslavia's loose federal system.
   Stojicevic sharply denounced Serbia's break with Slovenia,
describing the consequences as ``dramatic with a possibly
catastrophic outcome.''
   ``Ultimatums and the severance of economic relations,
accusations and threats represent a direct attack on the
constitutional order of the country and its economic and political
integrity,'' Stojicevic said.
   Slovenia's parliament met today to discuss Serbia's actions,
which Slovenian president Janez Stanovik said were a ``heavy blow
to the Yugoslav federation.''
   He said Serbia was trying to ``eliminate all those who hold
differing opinions and to produce a change of the constitutional
order.''
   ``The blockade of Slovenia, therefore, represents an act of
aggression against Yugoslavia,'' he told lawmakers.
   Croatia's state leadership, which had earlier sought to remain
on the sidelines of the dispute between Serbia and Slovenia, came
out strongly last week in favor of Slovenia.
   Croats and Serbs are traditional arch-rivals in Yugoslavia's
patchwork of nationalities, and an open clash between the two
regions could seriously threaten the unity of this Balkan nation.
   Yugoslavia has for years been a socialist showcase despite its
one-party system.
   But political, economic, social and ethnic problems have
mushroomed since the death in 1980 of President Josip Broz Tito,
whose charisma was seen as a major force in bounding together the
divergent ethnic groups in the country.
</TEXT>
