<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Disbarred     12-11 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Disbarred,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Disbars Biaggi and Suspends License of Ousted Federal Judge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former congressman convicted of racketeering
was disbarred by the Supreme Court today, and an ousted federal
judge had his high court license suspended, a first step in the
disbarment process.
   In a brief order, the justices stripped former Rep. Mario
Biaggi, D-N.Y., of his license to practice law at the nation's
highest court.
   And in a separate order, the court suspended former U.S.
District Judge Walter L. Nixon Jr.'s license.
   Biaggi, who served 10 terms in Congress, resigned from the House
of Representatives last year following his conviction on charges
that he illegally took $1.8 million in stocks and cash from the
scandal-ridden Wedtech Corp., a defense contractor based in New
York City. He was sentenced to eight years in prison.
   Biaggi was disbarred from practicing law in New York last
September.
   In a separate order, the court suspended Nixon's license to
practice in the Supreme Court and gave him 40 days ``to show cause
why he should not be disbarred from the practice of law in this
court.''
   The former judge was convicted in 1986 of two counts of lying to
a grand jury about his handling of a drug-smuggling case against
the son of a businessman with whom Nixon had invested. Nixon is
serving a five-year sentence.
   He was impeached, and then convicted by the Senate on Nov. 3.
</TEXT>
