<FIRST>r p PM-Louisiana-Senate     12-11 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana-Senate,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Klan Leader Duke Swamped in GOP Caucuses For Louisiana Senate
Nod</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state senator beat former Ku Klux Klan
leader David Duke in Republican caucuses to stake an early claim to
the GOP endorsement in next year's U.S. Senate race.
   By winning Saturday's caucuses, Sen. Ben Bagert of New Orleans
became the front-runner heading into the Republican's Jan. 13 state
convention. Bagert won 383, or 70 percent, of the 544 delegates
selected at 14 caucuses.
   At stake is which Republican will win the right to challenge
Democratic incumbent Bennett Johnston.
   Duke, who was elected as a state representative last year amid
controversy because of his racial views, won 27 delegates.
Secretary of State Fox McKeithen won 25 delegates and 109 were
uncommitted.
   However, the victory does not guarantee Bagert the nomination.
An additional 656 delegates still must be chosen, and pledges of
support made at party caucuses are not binding.
   Bagert said the caucus victory gave his candidacy ``a stamp of
approval.''
   Both Bagert and McKeithen have said they'll drop out of the race
if they don't get the party nomination. Duke has said he'll run
even if he isn't endorsed.
   Formal endorsement against Johnston, D-La., also would mean
Republican financial support _ money, party newsletters and
volunteers. However, in Louisiana's unique open primary system,
anyone can register as a candidate, regardless of party, and be
placed on the ballot. The primary is set for Oct. 6, 1990; if no
one gets a majority, the two top finishers will advance to the
November election.
   ``Bagert was by far the strongest candidate,'' said Darryl
Gissel, state Republican Party director.
   Duke, who said he does not expect the party's endorsement,
blamed his weak showing on his late entry into the race.
   ``We've organized this thing for three days. They've been at it
for three months,'' Duke said. ``I'm encouraged, given the time we
spent on it.''
</TEXT>
