<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-AgeBias 1stLd-Writethru a0540 12-11 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Age Bias, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges May Help Plaintiffs in Age Bias Suits Try to Find Other Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 6-12, In other action, with other cases.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today that federal
judges may help plaintiffs in age discrimination suits try to find
other possible victims and seek their participation in such suits.
   The justices, by a 7-2 vote, ruled against Hoffmann-La Roche
Inc., which is accused of bias against older workers in laying off
some 1,200 employees at New Jersey plants.
   The high court said judges in such ``class action'' suits may
help plaintiffs locate other possible victims of discrimination,
who may be unaware of the lawsuit, and solicit their participation.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, writing for the court, said judges
have discretion to authorize such notices to potential plaintiffs.
That ``serves the legitimate goal of avoiding a multiplicity of
duplicative suits and setting cut-off dates to expedite disposition
of the action,'' he said.
   But, he said, judges ``must be scrupulous to respect judicial
neutrality'' and not give even the appearance that they are
endorsing the suit.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Refused to reinstate former White House aide Lyn Nofziger's
conviction on charges of illegal lobbying after he left the Reagan
administration.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court
ruling that overturned Nofziger's 1988 conviction, 90-day jail
sentence and $30,000 fine.
   _ Shielded the FBI from having to give Grumman Corp. documents
received from another government agency, narrowing the reach of the
Freedom of Information Act.
   By a 6-3 vote, the court said the documents can be withheld
because they were ``compiled for law enforcement purposes'' and
therefore are exempt from the 1966 law aimed at curtailing
government secrecy.
   _ Turned away an appeal by an Iowa woman battling her state's
mandatory seatbelt law.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear Linda Diane
Clark's arguments that the law, similar to those in most states,
violates her constitutional rights.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia
dissented in the age-discrimination case.
   Scalia, writing for both, said nothing in the federal law
against age bias authorizes judges ``to undertake the unheard-of
role of midwifing'' lawsuits against employers.
   Hoffmann-La Roch dismissed some 1,200 workers on Feb. 4, 1985. A
group of older workers, who called the day ``Black Monday'' for
many veteran workers, said a disproportionately high number of
laid-off workers were over 40 years old.
   The group filed a lawsuit, charging the company with violating
the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act.
   The group's leaders then sought to contact all fired workers
over 40 eligible to join the lawsuit.
   Some 400 fired employees agreed to join. But leaders of the
court battle against the company said they believed there might be
200 additional fired workers who are members of the class allegedly
victimized by age discrimination.
   The leaders sought to contact the missing workers by mail and
notices posted at Hoffmann-La Roche plants.
   U.S. District Judge Harold A. Ackerman ordered the company to
provide the names and addresses of all fired workers. And Ackerman
said once the missing workers are found, they may be sent an
explanation of the suit and a form seeking their consent to join
the court fight.
   The form said the judge authorized the mailing but took no
position on the merits of the case.
   An increased number of plaintiffs in such suits can be a big
advantage for the workers because it spreads out court costs. In
seeking workers to join the suit, the leaders of the court fight
asked, but did not require, a $200 contribution to help defray the
costs.
   The Supreme Court today upheld a ruling by the 3rd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
   The case is Hoffmann-La Roche vs. Sperling, 88-1203.
</TEXT>
