<FIRST>r a PM-MoneyBags     12-11 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Money Bags,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Gives Away Thousands in Cash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A well-dressed woman has disappeared after
bringing early Christmas cheer to surprised patrons of a motel bar
by handing out $100, $50 and $20 bills.
   A woman who identified herself as Judy Kelly of Boston said she
was competing in a national ``treasure hunt'' against 40 or 50
other people that required her to give money away, according to a
truck driver at the bar who asked that his name not be used.
   The woman checked into a motel on Chicago's southwest side on
Saturday, walked into the lounge and gave $100 bills to each of
three flight attendants sitting at a table, witnesses said.
   ``Merry Christmas,'' said the white-haired woman, in her 50s.
   She pulled the cash from a brown paper lunch bag in her purse.
When she ran out of $100 bills, she apologized and gave out $50s.
When she ran out of those, she apologized and gave out $20 bills,
witnesses said.
   ``It's like `Miracle on 34th Street,''' said waitress Maria
Cross, referring to a movie about a man who says he is the real
Santa Claus.
   By one estimate she gave away $5,000, the Chicago Sun-Times
reported in today's editions.
   Police today could offer no further information on the episode.
   ``As far as I know, she went back to Boston,'' said Patrolman
Charles Nawrocki.
   The woman's identity was not immediately confirmed. The Boston
telephone book has two full pages of Kellys, and those with the
first initial ``J'' fill half a column, and that does not include
suburbanites who might say they are from Boston.
   Ms. Kelly checked out of the motel early Sunday morning, though
she left her car behind in the parking lot, said Sally Mascorro, a
front desk clerk at the Carlton Midway Motor Inn.
   Ms. Kelly had said the car wasn't working and that she would
send a tow truck to get it.
   ``It was towed sometime during the night,'' Linda Wierz,
assistant manager of the motel, said today. ``She said she was
going to arrange for that,'' added Ms. Wierz, who said she had no
further information.
   Police were called when the woman was giving away money.
   An officer at the Chicago Lawn district police station, who
would not give his name, said police took Ms. Kelly to the Bobby
Wright Comprehensive Community Mental Health Center.
   A man there who identified himself as an evaluator there said
Ms. Kelly was taken in and evaluated Saturday night. The man, who
would not give his name, said the woman later left in the company
of the police. He would not provide any other information.
   The woman's generosity caused quite a commotion.
   People tried politely to make Ms. Kelly's acquaintance.
Waitresses called friends and flight attendants from the airport
rushed back to tell co-workers.
   ``They were all coming up and playing stupid like they didn't
know what was going on,'' said Jose Gallegos, 21, an employee of a
neighboring rental car agency, adding that he gave Ms. Kelly a kiss
in return for $100.
</TEXT>
