<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Profits     12-11 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Profits,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Limits How Multinational Corporations Can Use Laws to Reduce
Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today limited the way
multinational corporations can use foreign tax laws to reduce their
U.S. taxes, a ruling the Bush administration said may save the
government hundreds of millions of dollars.
   The court ruled unanimously against Goodyear Tire and Rubber Co.
in a case stemming from operations of Goodyear's British subsidiary
in the early 1970s.
   The British subsidiary of the Ohio-based corporation incurred
net losses in 1972 and 1973, at least under British tax law. The
subsidiary's 1973 loss included British tax deductions that were
not allowed under American law.
   As a result, the British government refunded to the subsidiary
tax payments made there for 1970 and 1971.
   The refunds prompted the U.S. Internal Revenue Service to
recompute the taxes it said Goodyear owed in this country.
   Multinationals are entitled to claim a share of taxes paid by
subsidiaries overseas as credits against U.S. taxes.
   In Goodyear's case, since the IRS said American law did not
recognize the 1973 deductions permitted the company in Great
Britain, the corporation's loss was converted into a profit.
   The redetermination had the further effect of wiping out, for
U.S. tax purposes, the foreign tax credits previously allowed
Goodyear in 1970 and 1971.
   As a result, the IRS assessed Goodyear $791,240 in taxes and
interest for 1970 and 1971.
   Goodyear then filed suit in the U.S. Claims Court, saying the
IRS erred in applying American law instead of British law to
determine the company's accumulated profits.
   The claims court ruled against Goodyear. But a federal appeals
court here reversed the decision last year.
   The appeals court said a multinational company is entitled to
use a foreign nation's tax laws to determine accumulated profits
made by a subsidiary in that country.
   The Supreme Court today overruled the appeals court.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall, in his opinion for the high court,
said the approach favored by Goodyear would lead to unequal tax
treatment for subsidiaries _ as opposed to companies set up as
foreign branches of U.S. corporations _ whenever a foreign
government calculates income differently than in this country.
   That result would not square with federal laws aimed at assuring
tax parity between corporations that operate through foreign
subsidiaries and those that operate through foreign branches,
Marshall said.
   The Justice Department said hundreds of millions of dollars are
at stake, even though U.S. tax law was changed in 1986 to bar
multinationals from using a foreign country's calculation of its
accumulated profits for most future tax payments here.
   The department said more than 25,000 foreign subsidiaries of
U.S. companies do business in more than 100 countries. The
government's most recent figures show the companies claimed more
than $9 billion in foreign tax credits in 1982.
   The IRS said it is reviewing claims for $150 million in refunds
in such cases.
   The case is U.S. vs. Goodyear, 88-1474.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
