<FIRST>r a PM-KansasInvestigation     12-11 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kansas Investigation,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>KBI Director Dave Johnson Resigns in Aftermath of Joke Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 4th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HANNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the Kansas Bureau of
Investigation has resigned in the face of criticism over a
newspaper report that he told a racist joke in the presence of two
Statehouse reporters.
   Dave Johnson announced Saturday he was leaving his job after
almost 2{ years, the same day a column about the joke appeared in
the Kansas City Times.
   Within hours of the column's publication, 22 legislators signed
letters expressing anger to Attorney General Robert Stephan, and
the chairwoman of the state Republican Party was preparing to call
for Johnson's resignation.
   In the column, reporter Ted Frederickson wrote that Johnson told
a joke that referred to a ``nigger.'' Frederickson is an associate
professor of journalism at the University of Kansas who worked for
the Times this fall.
   In his letter of resignation, Johnson acknowleged making the
joke, but said Frederickson took it out of context.
   ``I am sure you are aware that my performance has not indicated
that I am a racist,'' Johnson said in his letter.
   The legislators who condemned Johnson's conduct did not call for
his resignation, though they did suggest that Stephan discipline
him. Twenty-one legislators signed a letter to Stephan drafted by
state Rep. Sheila Hochhauser. Rep. Sherman Jones, one of four black
legislators, drafted another letter.
   Frederickson said Johnson told the joke last week, when
questioned by him and another reporter about a triple murder in
Topeka for which two teen-agers, one black and one white, were
arrested.
   The second reporter, Associated Press Correspondent Lew
Ferguson, said he initially did not report the joke because it was
not made in a public forum, but wrote a story Saturday when he
learned of legislators' reactions to Frederickson's column.
   Johnson, 59, became KBI director in July 1987, replacing
retiring director Thomas E. Kelly. Johnson had been an investigator
for the state Insurance Department for three years before taking
the position. He had retired as a KBI agent in 1984.
</TEXT>
