<HEAD>Snow Over Midwest; Storm Hits Utah, Colorado Mountains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with pile-up in Colorado, frigid
wind-chills in North Dakota, and update number of dead in North Carolina
to eight, sted seven. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `The entire...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow and low temperatures combined to make the Rockies' roads
slick early today, causing numerous road pile-ups. Elsewhere, snow
fell in much of the Midwest, and wind-chills far below zero numbed
parts of the Dakotas.
   A winter storm warning was posted for locally heavy snow along
with gusty winds and low temperatures in a portion of Colorado
including the southern foothills and the Sangre de Cristo mountains.
   In northern Utah, slippery roads were blamed for accidents
involving more than 20 cars near Salt Lake International Airport on
Sunday night. Numerous minor injuries were reported.
   Most of Colorado east of the Continental Divide was hard hit by
the storm, which left a slew of motor vehicle accidents in its wake
Sunday, including a 20-car pileup on Interstate 25 near Johnstown
that closed the highway for two hours. Three people suffered minor
injuries in that accident.
   Much of the country's northern tier, the northern Rockies and
Iowa and Nebraska registered temperatures in the single digits this
morning. Wind chills as low as 50 degrees below zero were reported
in North Dakota.
   Snow was reported early today from Denver to Albany, N.Y. Cities
blanketed with snow included St. Louis, Cleveland, Detroit, Chicago
and North Platte, Neb.
   The cold reached down into the panhandle of Texas, where snow
was possible today. A winter storm watch for snow and freezing rain
also was forecast for tonight and Tuesday over northern Mississippi.
   Out West, high winds were expected today across Southern
California, where gusts up to 70 mph were possible in the mountains.
   In North Carolina, the first wintry storm of the season was
blamed for the deaths of eight motorists. The storm knocked out
power to thousands of households and toppled two television towers
before moving out to sea Sunday.
   Towers for WPTF-TV and WRAL-TV, both Raleigh stations, collapsed
Sunday within a half-hour of each other, spokesmen for the stations
said. The towers stand side-by-side in Auburn just south of Raleigh.
   The entire nation, however, wasn't under a wintry grip.
   In El Paso, Texas, the temperature reached 73 degrees Sunday,
breaking the record for the date. The nation's high Sunday was 83
degrees at San Angelo, Texas.
   Other reports at 4 a.m. EST today:
