<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-China     12-11 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-China,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong-China Committee Resumes Discussions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives from Hong Kong and China met
Monday for the first time since Beijing crushed internal dissent in
June, and they agreed the British colony should not serve as a base
for subversion against China after 1997, press reports said.
   Meeting in the southern Chinese city of Canton, the committee
that is drafting the Basic Law, or constitution, for Hong Kong
after it reverts to Chinese rule in 1997 Hong Kong, accepted the
proposal after a heated debate, the reports said.
   The Basic Law is supposed to ensure that Hong Kong can maintain
its capitalistic system for at least 50 years after 1997 and enjoy
a ``high degree of autonomy,'' as promised by China in negotiations
on the territory's reversion.
   China recently has attacked its critics in Hong Kong, who have
condemned the June 3-4 crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in
Beijing that killed hundreds, and perhaps thousands, of people.
   Li Hou, a top Chinese official involved in drafting the Basic
Law, said last month that China was considering prohibiting
contacts with overseas political groups.
   The Basic Law drafting committee, made up of more than 50
Chinese and Hong Kong members, began its deliberations 2{ years
ago. The final draft law is to be put to a vote in March at a full
session of China's legislature.
</TEXT>
