<HEAD>Three Hungarian Journalists Expelled From Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Hungarian journalists who went to
Romania last week to meet a dissident clergyman were detained by
police, expelled from the country and banned from re-entering for
five years, it was reported Monday.
   Police also confiscated their film and video cassettes.
   Szilvia Izso, a reporter for Nepszabadsag, the official
newspaper of the ruling Socialist Party, and two other reporters of
a regional newspaper went to Romania on Thursday to interview
Protestant clergyman Laszlo Toekes, who has been harassed for his
criticism of human rights violations in Romania.
   Last month, Toekes and his pregnant wife moved into a boarded-up
church in Timisoara, in western Romania, after ``hooligans,''
believed to be members of the secret police, broke the windows in
their home repeatedly and threatened them.
   The journalists said that as they were being detained, they saw
Toekes being escorted out of the church by three police officials.
They said they did not know what happened to him.
