<FIRST>u i PM-Canada-Shooting 2ndLd-Writethru a0539 12-11 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Shooting, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0539,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Montreal Mourns Victims of Worst Canadian Mass Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with further color, quotes from
services; Picks up 9th graf, ``We're sort ...'; SUBS penultimate graf to
conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and thousands of
others at Notre Dame cathedral today mourned the 14 women killed by
a gunman last week, and listened to appeals that their deaths help
build a better world.
   ``We have the tools in our hand to build a better world, a world
of peace,'' said Alain Perreault, president of the students'
association at the University of Montreal engineering school.
   He spoke of the victims' dreams and hopes and urged, ``Let's
achieve these great things ... of hope, of understanding.''
   Schools and universities throughout Quebec province observed a
minute of silence as the joint funeral Mass for nine of the victims
started. Families of five of the victims of Canada's worst mass
murder chose private services.
   Nearly 4,000 dignitaries including Mulroney and his wife, Mila,
students from the engineering school and families of the victims
filled the cathedral in Montreal's historic center.
   A gunman identified by police as Marc Lepine, 25, killed the
women in a rampage through three of the engineering school's six
floors on Wednesday before turning his semiautomatic assault rifle
on himself.
   Despite temperatures below freezing, several thousand people
listened quietly outside the cathedral to the 80-minute service
broadcast on loudspeakers.
   Cardinal Paul Gregoire, the city's Roman Catholic archbishop,
said in his homily that the women were ``brutally mowed down in the
beauty of their youth at a time when everything seemed to assure
them of a brilliant future.''
   He urged that, with the influence of their deaths, ``We should
seek to build a world of solidarity, a world of friendship.''
   The funeral followed a day when more than 7,000 people paid
final respects to the victims, eight of whose white, flower-draped
coffins lay in state at the university's hall of honor.
   ``We're sort of helpless in a way, but you feel you have to do
something,'' said Jennifer Jonas, an artist waiting in line with a
small floral bouquet.
   The gunman burst into the university's engineering school late
Wednesday afternoon on the last day of classes, shouting ``I want
the women!'' and ``You're all a bunch of feminists. I hate
feminists!''
   A suicide letter showed he carried a special grudge against
feminists, police said.
   Thirteen of those who died were students; the other was a school
employee. All were between the ages of 21 and 31. The gunman also
wounded nine women and four men. Their condition was reported today
to be improving.
   The engineering school started psychological counseling for
students and the victims' families and postponed exams until
Wednesday.
   Documents obtained by the Montreal Gazette of the divorce of
Lepine's parents, which occurred when he was seven, showed that his
mother said his father beat her, the boy and his sister.
   The father believed ``women are not men's equals and that women
are servants to men,'' the mother, Monique Lepine, said at the 1976
hearing.
   The father, Rachid Liass Gharbi, denied the allegations. Lepine
was named Gamil Gharbi but took his mother's name when he was 18.
   Today's service was for Maria Klueznick, 31; Genevieve Bergeron,
21; Helene Colgan, 23; Nathalie Croteau, 23; Barbara Daigneault,
22; Anne-Marie Edward, 21; Maud Haviernick, 29; Maryse Leclair, 23;
and Annie St-Arneault, 23.
   Private funerals have been arranged for Michele Richard, 21,
Maryse Laganiere, 25, Anne-Marie Lemay, 22, Sonia Pelletier, 28,
and Annie Turcotte, 21.
</TEXT>
