<FIRST>u a PM-Salvador-Fast 2ndLd-Writethru a0478 12-11 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Fast, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0478,a0499,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>8 Eight Hunger Strikers Say The Will End Protest Over Salvador Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with protesters saying they will end fast.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight hunger strikers who have occupied
the Cathedral of St. Paul since beginning a fast on Thanksgiving to
protest U.S. military aid to El Salvador said today they are ending
the fast.
   Striker Rene Hurtado said the fast was being called off in part
because of pleas from Gov. Rudy Perpich and other politicians, and
also to encourage others who did not want to take part in a hunger
strike to join their cause.
   ``By ending the hunger strike, we are allowing everybody to
participate with us in fighting to stop military aid to El
Salvador,'' he said.
   Their water-only fast began shortly after the murder of six
Jesuit priests in El Salvador last month. It was in its 19th day
today.
   Doctors had said the the strikers, who were ingesting nothing
but water, were entering a critical period that would greatly
stress their systems by causing vitamin deficiencies, mineral
imbalances and psychological strains.
   On Sunday, Perpich went to the church and asked the strikers to
suspend their fast until Congress acts on the issue. The governor
made the request after joining hands with the strikers in seeking
an end to military aid to the Central American country.
   On Friday, House Speaker Tom Foley called the hunger strikers to
urge them to end their strike and he promised that military aid to
El Salvador would be a major issue when Congress reconvenes next
month. U.S. Rep. Gerry Sikorski, a Democrat from Minnesota, also
urged for the strike to end.
   The hunger strikers included three refugees from El Salvador.
Another striker is from Guatemala, one from Bolivia and three from
the United States.
   Roman Catholic church officials have allowed the protesters to
stay in the cathedral during the strike, saying they could remain
as long as they didn't interrupt services.
</TEXT>
