<FIRST>r a PM-TylerSupport 1stLd-Writethru a0446 12-11 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tyler Support, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0446,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supporters Still Turn Out For Man They Feel Was Wrongly Charged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf pvs, `Petitions with...', to add
that this will be pardon board's first ruling. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `In
October...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 15 years, members of the ``Free Gary
Tyler'' movement across the nation have sung, marched, signed
petitions, and put their cause on T-shirts and bumper stickers.
This week they hope for results.
   Tyler, now 31, has served nearly half in his life in jail for a
murder his supporters say he didn't commit.
   The Louisiana Pardon Board is expected to announce Thursday its
recommendation to Gov. Buddy Roemer on whether Tyler should be set
free. The governor has final say.
   Petitions with more than 12,000 signatures have been sent to the
board and the governor by The Committee to Free Gary Tyler. Amnesty
International in London and West Germany wrote in support of Tyler,
said Mary Howell, his defense attorney.
   Tyler applied to the pardon board in 1980 but let the
application lapse while he pursued other appeals. An October
hearing was the first the board gas held in the case, and the
decision expected this week will be its first ruling.
   In October 1974, Tyler, a black, was in the midst of a heated
confrontation over the desegration of schools in Destrehan, a small
town about 25 miles north of New Orleans. He was 16.
   State police in riot gear were patrolling the streets of the
town, as were members of the Ku Klux Klan.
   David Duke, now a Republican state representative, was a young
Klan leader who promised to lead armed patrols of Klansmen into
town.
   ``We will help protect white people from rampaging black savages
and murders,'' Duke announced then.
   The situation came to a head when Destrehan High was closed
early because of a series of racial fights. Teachers tried to put
the 1,200 students onto school buses for the trip home.
   As whites surrounded buses of black students, shouting and
hurling bottles, cans and rocks, a shot was fired. Timothy Webber,
a 13-year-old white student standing with his mother across the
school yard, fell dead.
   An all-white jury sentenced Tyler to death for the shooting. The
sentence was commuted to life imprisonment when the U.S. Supreme
Court struck down the state's death penalty law.
   The conviction has withstood appeals, although a federal appeals
court at one time found enough evidence to say that Tyler was
prevented from getting a fundamentally fair trial.
   Tyler, who turned down a request for an interview on the advice
of his lawyer, always has maintained his innocence.
   His lawyer said he was a natural target for authorities.
   ``Gary Tyler was outspoken. He had what was called a smart
mouth,'' Howell told the state pardon board.
   Support for his cause from famous and ordinary citizens has
never stopped over the years. Hundreds ringed the state Supreme
Court chanting ``Free Gary Tyler'' during a 1976 appeal. Several
dozen, many of them wearing T-shirts bearing the slogan, sat
quietly at the November pardon board hearing.
   In 1976, protest marches and rallies were held in Detroit,
Pittsburgh, Boston, New York, Chicago and other cities.
   Pravda wrote about Tyler in 1978, calling him a ``political
prisoner.''
   The British reggae band UB40 recorded a song about Tyler.
   Howell said much of the money for Tyler's appeal has come from
the committee, which he and a core group of about a dozen workers
reactivated about two years ago.
   Several hundred T-shirts and buttons have been sold. In March, a
fund-raiser featured local musicians and poets. The Neville
Brothers headlined another money-raising concert in August.
   ``A terrible injustice has been done to Gary Tyler. It's our
duty to do everything within our power to set him free,'' said the
Rev. Avery Alexander, a state representative. ``The committee is as
committed as ever to doing that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
