<FIRST>u a PM-BusCrashTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0558 12-11 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Crash Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0558,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Opens in Bus Crash Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to DELETE reference to driver being drunk, which is
one of the charges against him. He has admitted to drinking before the
crash but has not pleaded guilty to drunken driving.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution rested today in the
murder trial of a driver who crashed into a church bus, and the
defense opened its case with testimony aimed at showing that the
bus wasn't safe.
   Kentucky Fire Marshal John William Martin testified that the
seat coverings and cushions on the bus ``were in fact combustible
and will burn very rapidly when ignited.''
   Lawyers for Larry Mahoney contend an unsafe bus is to blame for
the 27 deaths and multiple injuries in the May 14, 1988, disaster
south of this Ohio River community. The bus was built before more
stringent federal safety standards went into effect.
   However, not all of Martin's testimony supported that
contention. The fire marshal also testified that dense black smoke
that rolled through the bus could have been caused by the burning
of gasoline alone, not by the seat covers. And he said a protective
cage around the bus' gas tank wouldn't have prevented the fire that
followed the crash.
   Mahoney, who was driving a black Toyota pickup, admits drinking
the day of the crash, driving on the wrong side of Interstate 71
and striking the loaded church bus.
   He is charged with 27 counts of murder, 42 counts of wanton
endangerment, 12 counts of assault and a count of drunken driving.
The defense phase of the trial is expected to wind up by Friday.
   Last week, Assistant Attorney General Paul Richwalsky Jr.
presented a detailed reconstruction of the accident, based largely
upon weeks of study by Kentucky State trooper Henry ``Sonny'' Cease.
   The jury also heard testimony from relatives of 26 of the 27
victims, from police and a medical expert about Mahoney's level of
drunkenness, and from the state's chief medical examiner about the
victims' autopsy results.
   One survivor of the crash testified that he saw two girls flick
cigarette lighters to see inside the darkened bus following the
crash. The survivor recalled the fire getting worse the moment the
lighters were flicked.
   Asked about that today, Martin said he didn't believe an
additional source of ignition would have made any difference if the
fire had already been started.
</TEXT>
