<FIRST>u i PM-EastGermany 2ndLd-Writethru   12-11 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0515,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Speaks With Gysi, Demonstrators Keep Pressure On For Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Leipzig rally; Picks up 4th
graf pvs, `Earlier, West ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 people rallied tonight in
Leipzig and many urged German unity, a proposal that Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the new Communist Party chief would harm
East Germany.
   Gorbachev, speaking with party chief Gregor Gysi on Sunday,
praised the party's ``rejection of attempts to damage the
sovereignty of the country,'' the state-run news agency ADN said.
Gysi became party chief Saturday.
   Also today, the four Allied occupiers of divided Berlin _ the
United States, Britain, France and the Soviet Union _ held their
first meeting in 18 years. The Soviets expressed ``favorable
interest'' in a Western plan to boost the international role of
Berlin, according to a joint statement.
   In Leipzig, it was the fourth straight week that calls for
German unity had played a major role in the protests. Pro-democracy
demonstrators continue to pressure East Germany's beleaguered
government to carry through with promises for reforms.
   ``We in Leipzig and those in Hanover (a West German city) are
and will remain Germans,'' said one Leipzig speaker, drawing a huge
roar of approval from the flag-waving crowd. ``What belongs
together will grow together.''
   Earlier, West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl insisted that
reunification will come one day, but acknowledged that for now such
a step remains a ``vision.''
   The questions of East German sovereignty have become
increasingly important with the growing turmoil in the Communist
nation. There have been predictions the rapid changes could lead to
steps toward unification with West Germany.
   In his conversation with Gysi, Gorbachev also promised Moscow
would consider providing support ``within the current framework of
conditions,'' ADN said, without elaborating. The dispatch also did
not make clear who called whom.
   On Sunday, tens of thousands of demonstrators braved bitter cold
in eight East German cities to keep up the pressure for change, and
Gysi called for a clear separation of party and government.
   Pro-democracy supporters rallied in freezing weather in Rostock,
Erfurt, East Berlin, Kronskamp, Plauen, Cottbus, Suhl and Ilmenau,
according to ADN.
   In the southern city of Plauen, about 15,000 demonstrators
turned out for a pro-democracy rally called by the New Forum
opposition group.
   Hartmut Krausse, a physician and member of the New Forum
opposition group, told 15,000 people in the southern city of
Ilmenau that talk of ``anarchy, chaos and violence'' was out of
place.
   Despite that appeal, there was a renewed round of calls for
people not to resort to violence as they seek to punish discredited
former Communist rulers, many of whom have been arrested or are
being investigated for abuses of power.
   Mayor Wolfgang Berghofer of Dresden warned Sunday that
``violence has not been dispelled. An escalation is possible at any
moment.''
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany, in a
speech Sunday, urged East Germans to exercise restraint and keep
protests free of violence.
   Citizens have been disgusted by the reports of high-living and
corruption by ousted party officials, and in some cases they have
surrounded or stormed local offices of the once-dreaded secret
police.
   The government has claimed that angry citizens have stormed army
bases.
   In the face of massive protests, the Communist Party in the last
two months has ousted two sets of leaders, lifted travel
restrictions, opened the Berlin Wall and abandoned its
constitutionally guaranteed hold on power.
   Gysi, 41, said in a television interview that he backed a
``strict division of party and government.'' But he added, ``This
can't be done in one day. It is a long-term job that is being taken
very seriously.''
   Such separation would be a striking change in East Germany
where, despite recent democratic reforms, party members still hold
most of the important positions in the country.
   There have been warnings that a push toward German
reunification, which some recent demonstrations have urged, could
cause further troubles in East Germany.
</TEXT>
