<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Kidnap     12-11 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Kidnap,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Separatists Agree to Free Cabinet Minister's Daughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARUN JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem separatists who kidnapped a Cabinet
minister's daughter agreed Monday to free her, apparently after an
agreement was reached to release some of their jailed colleagues, a
government negotiator said.
   Rubaiya Mufti Sayeed, the youngest daughter of Home Minister
Mufti Mohammed Sayeed, will be released ``any moment,'' said Moosa
Raza, the chief secretary in the northern state of Jammu-Kashmir.
   Raza made his announcement shortly after the Monday evening
deadline set by the militants of the Kashmir Liberation Front to
kill the woman unless the government released seven jailed
colleagues, including the group's top leader who was arrested last
month.
   Ms. Sayeed, 22, was kidnapped at gunpoint Friday in the city of
Srinagar as she was going home from work.
   The abduction was the first major crisis to face the 10-day-old
government of Prime Minister V.P. Singh. His appointment of Sayeed
to the ministry that oversees internal security was seen as a move
to appease Moslems who bore the brunt of Hindu-Moslem religious
riots in the fall.
   The kidnapping came a day after Sayeed was appointed head of a
government committee aiming to end separatist campaigns in
Jammu-Kashmir and neighboring Punjab, where Sikh militants are
demanding an independent nation.
   Formed in 1965, the Kashmir Liberation Front wants
Jammu-Kashmir, the only Indian state with a Moslem majority, to
either become independent or part of neighboring Pakistan, an
Islamic state.
   Raza did not disclose the contents of the agreement that he said
was reached ``using the services of respectable citizens of
Kashmir.''
   ``The deadline has no relevance since the negotiations are going
on. We hope positive results will come out very soon,'' he said.
   One of the negotiators contacted by telephone in Srinagar said
Ms. Sayeed may be released Tuesday. Srinagar, the summer capital of
Jammu-Kashmir, is about 93 miles north of Jammu, the state's winter
capital.
   The negotiator, who did not wish to be identified, said the
militants had demanded safe passage for their colleagues freed in
the swap. They had agreed to reduce their demand to freedom for
five militants, he said.
   Earlier in the day, a bomb exploded inside an air cargo complex
in Srinagar, injuring at least 15 people and severely damaging the
building, officials said. No one claimed responsibility and it was
not immediately known if the blast was related to the kidnapping.
   Jammu-Kashmnir is the only Moslem majority state in the
officially secular, predominantly Hindu India. Moslems make up 64
percent of the state but nationwide comprise only 11 percent of the
population. Hindus comprise 80 percent of India's 880 million
people.
   Kashmir is claimed both by India and Pakistan, and the two
countries have fought three wars over the territory since they
gained independence from Britain in 1947.
</TEXT>
