<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     12-11 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>65 Bodies of Suspected Sinhalese Radicals Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities found the bodies of 65
suspected Sinhalese radicals _ some shot, others burned _ and
military officials said Monday that pro-government vigilantes had
done the killings.
   The bodies were discovered after Sinhalese radicals set fire to
dozens of public buses over the weekend in central and southern Sri
Lanka.
   The officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said the victims were believed members of the People's Liberation
Front, an ultra-nationalist Sinhalese guerrilla group trying to
overthrow the government for making peace overtures to Tamil
secessionists in the northeast.
   The front began its campaign in 1987 and has continued to attack
the government although its six top leaders were killed last month
by government forces.
   On Sunday, the militants burned 32 government-owned buses in
Ambalantota, about 90 miles south of Colombo, a government
statement said.
   Also Sunday, at least 16 more government-owned buses were set
ablaze in other attacks and two railway engines and a railroad
station were burned at Gampha district's Yagoda village, 15 miles
northeast of Colombo, the government said.
   To counter the militant violence, human rights groups say, the
government this year set up vigilante groups which have killed
hundreds of civilians suspected of associating with the front. The
government denies the charge.
   The military officials on Monday, however, blamed pro-government
vigilantes for the killings that were reported since Sunday in the
Sinhalese heartland of central and southern Sri Lanka, where the
front's campaign has focused.
   Military officials said 21 bodies were found in Wellawaya
village in Monaragala district, 100 miles east of Colombo. Most of
the victims were Sinhalese men between the ages 18 and 30, the
officials said.
   They said 18 bodies were found at Mavaralla village in central
Kegalle district, 11 at southern Hakmana town, six in the central
town of Kandy and the nine in other towns.
   More than 6,000 people have died in the Sinhalese violence that
was sparked by an India-sponsored peace accord signed by the
government in July 1987 with Tamil rebels demanding a separate
homeland for their minority community.
   The front alleged the accord too many concessions to the Tamils,
who are mainly Hindus and comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people. Tamils claim they are discriminated against in jobs
and education by the Sinhalese who are mainly Buddhists and make up
75 percent of the population. The Sinhalese also control the
government and the military.
   The Sinhalese rebels also opposed the presence of Indian
peacekeeping troops, deployed in the north and the east to
supervise the peace accord. India has begun withdrawing its
soldiers from most areas ahead of a Dec. 31 deadline, but the
vacuum has resulted in a power struggle among Tamil groups.
   Three Tamils were killed late Sunday and early Monday in
fighting between two groups, the officials said.
   At least 10,000 Sri Lankans have died in the Tamil rebellion
that started in 1983 and the post-accord violence.
</TEXT>
