<FIRST>u a PM-MasonTrial     12-11 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mason Trial,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Lord Found Guilty Of Ordering Officer's Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug lord Howard ``Pappy'' Mason was found
guilty today of ordering the execution-style murder of police
Officer Edward Byrne, a slaying that came to symbolize the nation's
battle against illegal drugs.
   The 31-year-old defendant was convicted on all 11 counts of drug
conspiracy. Prosecutors charged he had ordered the officer's
slaying in the course of running a drug empire that brought in as
much as $10,000 a week.
   He faces a mandatory life prison term when he is sentenced by
U.S. District Judge Edward R. Korman.
   The killing of the rookie policemen on Feb. 26, 1988, while he
guarded a witness in a drug case became an issue in last year's
presidential campaign. Byrne's parents gave their dead son's police
badge to then-Vice President Bush during a campaign appearance, and
Bush cited the slaying as an example of why he believed the death
penalty was needed.
   The verdict came in the third day of deliberations. The panel
met for 3{ hours Friday and a full day Saturday before resuming
this morning.
   Mason was not present at Byrne's slaying. Two days before, he
had been convicted and jailed for weapons possession.
   But prosecutors say he sent word from his jail cell to his top
lieutenant that he wanted the blood of any police officer.
   In his closing arguments Friday, defense attorney Harry C.
Batchelder Jr. countered by saying the government's witnesses were
admitted murderers, drug addicts and thieves who were given deals
for their cooperation.
   Byrne, 22, was killed instantly by four members of Mason's gang
who pumped five bullets into his head as he sat in his patrol car
guarding the firebombed home of a witness in a drug case.
   The killers were convicted earlier this year and sentenced to
the maximum 25 years to life in jail.
   Mason hasn't been seen much during his trial, which began about
two weeks ago. Most days, including today, he has elected to stay
in his courthouse holding cell, which is rigged with closed-circuit
TV to let him follow the proceedings.
</TEXT>
