<FIRST>b w PM-US-China 4thLd-Writethru a0607-etal 12-11 1173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0607-et al,1,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says He'll Keep Looking for Common Ground with Chinese Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines a0607, a0611, a0613, a0585; new information, editing
throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today defended his decision to
send two top aides to Beijing over the weekend, and said he would
``keep looking for ways to find common ground'' with Chinese
leaders despite continuing unhappiness with their crackdown last
spring against pro-democracy forces.
   Bush stressed that the trip by national security adviser Brent
Scowcroft and a top State Department aide did not amount to
normalization of relations. Those who suggest otherwise ``simply do
not know what they are talking about,'' he said.
   Democrats were criticizing Bush even as he spoke. Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine said the mission by
Scowcroft and Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger was
``embarrassing kowtowing'' to a brutal regime.
   But Bush said he took the action because ``I do not want to
isolate the Chinese people.''
   The president said the United States maintains contacts with
several countries that have ``egregious records on human rights.''
As for the crackdown in Beijing last June, Bush said, ``The Chinese
know they have to address themselves to the problems that were
inherent in this episode.''
   Sanctions imposed by Bush after the crackdown remain in effect.
   The president made his comments to a group of editorial writers
gathered in an auditorium across the street from the White House.
   He opened the session with a review of his first year as
president. Citing an improved U.S.-Soviet relationship and other
developments, he said, ``I'm not overly satisfied but I think
generally the first year has gone pretty well.''
   Bush said the economy has continued to expand and create new
jobs and that he had ``been able to keep my pledge of no new
taxes.''
   Congress, he said, has enacted a savings and loan bailout bill
and made a start on clean air and ethics legislation.
   At the same time, Bush said he differed with the Democratic
majorities of the House and Senate over child care legislation, and
would press Congress to pass his anti-crime package when it returns
in January.
   ``All in all it's been a productive year, we've proposed a lot
of new initiatives,'' he said.
   Bush said he still planned to attend a drug summit scheduled for
next year in Cartegena, Columbia, despite concerns that the visit
would pose a security risk.
   ``I don't want to send the signal that nobody should go to
Columbia,'' Bush said, praising the government's efforts to bring
the drug traffickers to justice.
   He added, however that he would reassess the situation prior to
the trip. ``I will not do anything imprudent,'' he said. ``Nobody
has ever accused me of being too daring.''
   As for China, Bush responded with an emphatic ``No'' when asked
if he worried that the Scowcroft-Eagleburger trip would signal the
Soviets that he would tolerate a crackdown on pro-democracy
demostrators in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   ``I have no concern about that at all as long as we are properly
positioned in favor of human rights ... and as long as the Soviet
Union knew that we are not sending a signal of quote total
normalization unquote. I will be careful that we do not send that
signal,'' he said.
   At the same time, Bush said he was ``very pleased today in the
wake of General Scowcroft's visit to notice that the Chinese
Foreign Ministry stated that they would not sell missiles to any
Mideast countries.'' He added that Scowcroft had raised the issue
in his weekend talks with Chinese leaders, and the Chinese made
their announcement before the national security adviser and
Eagleburger had returned to Washington.
   Scowcroft planned to brief Bush later today on the trip.
   Bush said he had sent his top aides to Beijing to discuss the
results of the Malta summit with the Chinese leaders.
   ``I do not want to isolate the Chinese people. I don't want to
hurt the Chinese people,'' he said.
   ``I realize the difficulty of this relationshiop but I don't
want to make it any worse,'' he said, referring to the strains
following the bloody crackdown against demonstrating students last
June.
   He said he was ``going to keep looking for ways to find common
ground'' with China.
   The president made no mention of Fang Lizhi, the prominent
Chinese dissident who has been given sanctuary from Chinese
authorities in the American Embassy in Beijing.
   Bush spoke against a backdrop of stepped up Democratic criticism
of his decision to send Scowcroft and Eagleburger.
   ``The administration supports human rights in its words,''
Mitchell said. ``It does not do so in its deeds ... These actions
make a mockery of our profession of concern for human rights and
are inconsistent with our stated ideals.''
   The trip was not announced until after the officials had landed
in Beijing at 1 a.m. EST on Saturday. Scowcroft toasted China's
leaders at a televised banquet and called for improved relations.
   ``This trip was not intended to develop normal relations with
China in any immediate sense,'' White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said. ``It's going to happen over a longer period of
time, we hope, but they're not much different today than it was
three days ago.''
   ``We have the same concerns. We have the same indignation. We
have the same principles. We have the same urgings for their
country that we had before,'' said Fitzwater.
   He acknowledged that the United States has seen no changes in
China's behavior since leaders sent in tanks and troops to
Tienanmen Square, killing hundreds of pro-democracy demonstrators
and crushing a months-long protest.
   ``Enormous changes are taking place in the world. ... We need
some uinderstanding of their position'' on the breakthroughs for
democracy and freedom in the East bloc nations, Fitzwater said.
   The Chinese government has been critical of the changes in
Eastern Europe.
   ``The sanctions have not changed. It's not business as usual.
... It simply is the fact we feel China is a country that has to be
dealt with,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush, former U.S. envoy to China, barred high-level contacts
with Chinese leaders after they sent tanks into Tiananmen Square.
He also cut off military sales to the communist regime. The
president said relations could not be normalized until the
government honored basic human rights. He also gave refuge to
Chinese students in the United States, although he recently vetoed
a bill that would have written that protection into law.
   At the State Department, spokesman Richard Boucher declined to
specify issues raised by the two U.S. officials on their visit. But
he acknowledged that the proliferation of ballistic missiles ``has
been and remains high on our agenda with the Chinese.''
   And he noted that China's government-controlled media termed
reports of an impending missile sale to Syria ``groundless'' and
said China has no plans to sell such missiles to any Middle Eastern
country. ``We think it's noteworth that they reiterated'' the
denials, Boucher said.
</TEXT>
