<FIRST>r a AM-DeckedtoThrill     12-11 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Decked to Thrill,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Businessman Stops Traffic With Elaborate Christmas Light
Display</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It just wouldn't be Christmas for
thousands of South Carolinians if M.L. Corley didn't turn his home,
yard and pond into the stuff fairy tales are made of.
   A dozen trees in the front yard are abloom with colored lights,
as are the house, two bridges leading to the pond and the gazebo on
an island in the water. Poinsettias form collars at the bases of
the trees.
   Each tier and railing of the white, two-story, colonial-style
home is draped with green garland, and wreaths with red bows peek
out from every window. From the kitchen window, Santa Claus and
Mrs. Claus, standing 2{ feet tall, nod and open and close their
arms.
   The bridges to the pond behind the house also are strung with
garlands, and 6-foot candy canes and lollipops stand sentry on the
bridge to the island.
   ``I don't know whether it's elaborate or not, but it's right
attractive,'' Corely said.
   Some 25,000 people followed homemade traffic signs around his
circular driveway last year to view the display in this suburb of
Columbia.
   Two weeks after it went up this year on Thanksgiving Day, a
traffic counter indicated more than 6,200 people had already taken
the tour, which takes visitors from the front of the house around
to the back yard and pond.
   ``And that's not including the people who just drive by the
house,'' Corley said. ``We get quite a jam here.''
   ``The neighbors don't mind the traffic because they do it,
too,'' Corley said, referring to less elaborate Christmas displays
on his block.
   Corley, 73, began decorating his home in the late 1940s, then
started devoting more time to the display after retiring eight
years ago from his sawmill and wood procurement business.
   Now, the most elaborate setup might be around the gazebo.
Poinsettias spread like patches of fiery snow. Giant red, yellow
and green lollipops adorn the posts and sides, and a life-sized
Santa stands at the back entrance.
   Despite all the glowing and brightly colored decorations, ducks
still come by for a dip in the pond.
   When Christmas Day draws nearer, a friend posing as Santa Claus
comes by and hands out candy to visiting children.
   Corley hasn't even tried to count the number of wreaths
decorating the property, and as for the number of lights, ``I don't
want to know,'' he said.
   ``I just wanted to thank the good Lord that I was able to
decorate so people could come by and see it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
