<FIRST>r a AM-ZenLawsuit     12-11 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zen Lawsuit,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Reduces Award in Lawsuit Claiming Zen Retreat a Nuisance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge on Monday reduced to
$45,000 a $1 million award given to a man by a jury that found a
Zen Buddhist community next to the plaintiff's property had created
a nuisance.
   The Buddhists had placed 200 fluorescent stakes around the man's
property in Pound Ridge and used chain saws and other power
equipment at odd hours.
   State Supreme Court Justice Matthew Coppola agreed the
Wellspring Zendo created a nuisance, but found there was no basis
for so big an award.
   In addition to cutting the award to $45,000, he ordered the
religious community to remove the stakes and restrict the use of
power equipment to Monday through Saturday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. He
also directed the group to close windows and doors before their 5
a.m. chant.
   The jury award was made Friday in a lawsuit filed by homeowner
Bradley Nitkin, who sought $2.5 million, claiming the religious
community was trying to intimidate him into moving from the
community in southeastern New York state.
   The community's lawyer, Douglas Hoyt, said the ruling would be
appealed because of the requirement that the community close its
windows and doors during services, which he said was an
interference with freedom of religion.
   ``I don't think the court has the right to impose such
restrictions,'' said Hoyt. ``We didn't come here just to fight
Bradley Nitkin, but because of our religious freedom.''
   Coppola's ruling caps a two-year struggle between Nitkin and the
Wellspring Zendo community.
   Nitkin, a real estate lawyer, claimed the religious community
had consistently harassed him and his family by clanging cymbals
and chanting at 5 a.m. He said the group used power equipment and
chain saws at all hours and on weekends and Christmas.
   He said he and his wife and 2-year-old daughter spend most of
their time in a New York City apartment, even though they had
planned to move to Pound Ridge permanently. He said Monday had not
yet decided about moving permanently to Pound Ridge.
   ``Freedom of religion had nothing to do with it,'' said Nitkin's
lawyer, Paul Robbins. ``The Nitkins wanted to enjoy their property.
The monetary damages were incidental.''
   Wellspring is used as a retreat by 20 to 30 people at a time.
   The group is suing Pound Ridge for $65 million, claiming new
ordinances for non-residential uses in residential areas violate
their freedom of religion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
