<DOCNO> AP891211-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     12-11 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a Santa here who knows that the
little ones are sometimes naughty instead of nice. So he wears
extra thick clothing to guard against bites and scratches.
   ``Santa Paws'' also wears flea and tick powder and keeps a red
towel handy for accidents.
   Santa Paws is Bill Stovall, a retired Army major who played
Santa last weekend for about 100 animals in a fundraiser for the
Pensacola Humane Society. For $5, Rover could climb into Santa's
lap and ask for that extra juicy Christmas bone.
   Stovall, who has played Santa to children as well as animals at
the society's animal shelter, said he preferred the latter.
   ``I've never had a pet that is obnoxious, but every once in a
while you get a kid that is,'' said Stovall, seated in front of a
Christmas tree surrounded by unopened Alpo.
   In four years, he has played Santa to dogs and cats of all
sizes, ferrets, rabbits, goats and one ``maladjusted mallard''
whose owners said she lays green eggs and hates the water.
   ``I'm happy no one has brought a snake,'' Stovall said.
   He has been bitten only once: last year by a rare Chinese
crested dog named Fievel. The tiny terror took a parting nip at his
fingers this year but missed.
   Donna Arnett of Pensacola Beach brought two nervous cats,
``Lorelei'' and ``Molly,'' and told Santa, ``They want shrimp and
livers for Christmas.''
   And yes, Virginia King discovered, there is a Santa Paws. The
Pensacola woman brought her two poodles, ``Trixie'' and
``Samantha'' to sit on Santa's lap.
   ``My children have already grown up,'' she said. ``These are
part of my family.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RUDOLPH, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The holidays are here and for many people
Christmas won't be complete until they get a piece of mail from
this tiny central Wisconsin village.
   The U.S. Postal Service office here is inundated with requests
for a rubber-stamped symbol from the village that stakes claim as
home of Rudolph, the Red Nosed Reindeer.
   ``I think it's nifty,'' said Bruce Hayry, who is running the
Rudolph post office until a permanent postmaster is found. ``I
really do. It's something different.''
   With a rubber stamper, post office workers press a stamp of
Rudolph _ complete with a shiny nose _ on mail. The stamp measures
1.5 inches wide and 2 inches high and is underscored with:
``Rudolph, Wisconsin, Home of Rudolph, The Red Nosed Reindeer.''
   Hayry said some want the stamps to dress up their Christmas
cards, while others want it for their stamp collections. Collectors
send stamped envelopes with their addresses to the post office and
ask that they be sent back with the Rudolph stamp, he said.
   Past years' requests have come from more than a dozen states.
   The idea and original design for the stamp came from Lillian
Blonien, Rudolph postmaster from 1951 to 1971.
   The Rudolph character was created in 1939 by Ron May, a catalog
copywriter for Montgomery Ward &amp; Co., who wrote a poem about the
famous reindeer. A song by Johnny Marks followed in 1949, and the
rest is history.
   The village has been around considerably longer. It got its name
in 1856 from Rudolph Hecox, the first settler to live there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0117 </DOCNO>
