<FIRST>u a AM-DefenseProbe     12-11 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Probe,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marine Procurement Fraud Trial Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense consultant Thomas Muldoon and a
former corporate executive went on trial Monday on charges of
conspiring to bribe a Marine Corps procurement officer to help a
private company get Pentagon contracts.
   The trial is the second since the government's investigation of
Pentagon procurement fraud, nicknamed ``Operation Ill Wind,''
became public 18 months ago. More than 25 individuals and four
corporations have been convicted.
   Muldoon, described in court papers throughout the government
investigation of defense procurement fraud as a major figure in the
case, is accused along with Leonard L. Ingram of participating in
the scheme to bribe former Marine Corps official Jack Sherman.
   ``This is a case about bribery and corruption,'' prosecutor
Robert DeHenzel told federal court jurors. ``Thomas Muldoon and
Leonard Ingram were involved in a six-year pattern of making
payments to Jack Sherman.''
   DeHenzel said that in return for receiving more than $80,000
over the six-year period Sherman helped Lee Telecommunications
obtain Marine Corps electronics contracts.
   In addition Sherman would modify the contracts to increase their
value to the company, which became a subsidiary of the Whittaker
Corp. in 1986.
   Sherman, who has pleaded guilty to separate charges in the
investigation, is expected to testify as a government witness.
   Ingram, a minority stockholder in Lee Telecommunications,
opposed the scheme to bribe Sherman, argued his lawyer, Marcus
Topel.
   When Ingram protested to company officials, ``he was told to
mind his own business,'' Topel told jurors.
   On several occasions, Topel argued, Ingram appeared to support
the scheme in discussions with defense consultants who served as
conduits for the payments to Sherman, but Ingram privately opposed
the payments in meetings with company officials, Topel said.
   ``He is not guilty of the offenses,'' Topel said. ``He is an
innocent man who was in the wrong place at the wrong time.''
   Topel described Sherman as being as ``crooked as the Mississippi
River.''
   ``He is on the take everywhere,'' the defense lawyer said.
   Topel said that Scott M. Lamberth and John Franklin Van Tassel,
both former corporate executives, were prepared to testify that
Ingram was not involved in the bribery scheme. Both men have
pleaded guilty and are awaiting sentencing by U.S. District Judge
Claude M. Hilton.
   If convicted, Muldoon could receive up to 70 years in prison and
be fined as much as $1.04 million. Ingram could receive a 95-year
sentence and be fined up to $1.53 million if convicted of the
charges.
</TEXT>
