<FIRST>u i AM-Baker     12-11 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Cautions Kohl on Reunification</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III
cautioned West German leaders Monday that they alone cannot decide
the pace of reunification with East Germany.
   Baker flew here for talks with Chancellor Helmut Kohl and
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher and a visit to the
now-porous Berlin Wall after a stop in London.
   There he reaffirmed a special U.S. relationship with the
government of Prime Minister Marager Thatcher and said he did not
believe the two close allies were drifting apart.
   ``I don't think there are any fences that need mending,'' Baker
said after a 50-minute conversation with Mrs. Thatcher at No. 10
Downing St. ``We feel a special relation to the United Kingdom and
to the prime minister.''
   He said there had been ``some minsuderstanding'' of President
Bush's call at a meeting of NATO leaders on Dec. 4 in Brussels for
``perhaps even an intensified effort'' at economic and political
integration of Western Europe.
   Mrs. Thatcher has resisted most moves in that direction, but
gone along reluctantly. Overriding her objections, the European
Community on Saturday made steps toward creating a central bank and
a common currency for the 12-nation region.
   ``I don't think the differences were as real as they were
portrayed in the British press,'' Baker told reporters later as he
flew to West Berlin.
   Besides, he said the United States does not take a position on
the pace of integration because it is not a member of the European
Community.
   But Baker then went on to offer some pointed advice to Kohl,
whose 10-point program for German reunification has raised concerns
in the Soviet Union, France, Britain, Poland and elsewhere in
Europe.
   Baker said the four World War II allies who have final say in
running Berlin have ``roles and responsibilities'' that must be
respected in deciding the country's destiny.
   ``There has never been any peace treaty signed between the
allies and Germany, and there are certain retained rights which the
four powers have,'' Baker told reporters.
   He cited as an example access to Berlin by the four wartime
powers: the United States, the Soviet Union, Britain and France. In
that regard, Baker recalled former President Ronald Reagan's call
for improved air service.
   ``So there are some reserve roles and responsibilities there,''
Baker said.
   Asked if the Germans would require the concurrence of the four
powers to reunite the country, Baker said that was a legal question
that would keep U.S. and other foreign ministries busy.
   But when asked for the U.S. policy position, he said ``There is
a certain reserved role and certain responsibilities reserved under
the allied powers that have got to be considered when you deal with
the question of German reunification. These things have to be
considered and dealt with.''
   Baker will have breakfast with Kohl on Tuesday, ceremonially
sign the city's Golden Book, and make a low-key visit to the Berlin
Wall, the concrete Cold War symbol of East-West division.
   Millions of East Germans have passed through the wall in the
month since the Communist government lifted travel restrictions.
   Baker then will make a speech to the Berlin press club in which
he is expected to elaborate on his theme that German reunification
should be anchored to the North Atlantic Treaty Organiyation, the
European Community and the 1975 Helsinki Agreement signed by 32
European countries, the United States, Canada and the Vatican.
   He said the Bush administration would like to see reunification
develop in a peaceful and productive way
   ``Working together with all of our allies, and that includes the
Federal Republic of Germany, France and the United Kingdom, and
taking into consideration the concerns of Germany's neighbors, we
can have influence on the process,'' Baker said.
   He agreed with a reporter's suggestion that the upheaval in East
Germany comes partly from the streets and may not be manageable by
the superpowers.
   ``But we are doing, I think, what we should be doing, and what
is responsible under the circumstances.'' Baker said.
</TEXT>
