<FIRST>r a AM-ChildrenKilled     12-11 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children Killed,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Charged with Murder, Arson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kankakee County Board member was charged
Monday with murder and arson in the deaths of his three children
and a fourth youngster in a fire at their mother's home,
authorities said.
   Bernon I. Howery, 38, in his second term on the board, was
ordered held without bond on four charges of first-degree murder
and one of aggravated arson, Police Chief Timothy O. Nugent said.
   During questioning, ``Mr. Howery implicated himself in the cause
of this fire,'' Nugent said, declining to elaborate.
   The case is to go to a grand jury Friday, said Assistant State's
Attorney Brenda Gorski. Howery is scheduled for arraignment Dec. 18.
   The bodies of Justina Howery, 5; her sister, Prima, 10; their
brother, Joel, 9; and half-sister Ledonja Walls, 11, were found
early Saturday in an upstairs closet a short time after fire
engulfed their mother's home in this community of 31,000 about 60
miles south of Chicago.
   The fire appeared to have been started in piles of clothes
placed at several locations in the house, according to police Lt.
William Cantrell.
   Fire Chief James Dupuis said investigators were still trying to
determine if an accelerant had been used.
   All four children were left Friday evening by their mother,
Linda Walls, in the care of her 27-year-old brother, Johnny Walls,
who lives with her and the children, Cantrell said.
   Later in the evening, Howery visited and Walls left, Cantrell
said. Later, Howery also left to run an errand, leaving the
children unattended, Cantrell said.
   Authorities believe the fire was started before Howery departed,
Nugent said.
   Firefighters found no sign of a smoke detector in the house, and
considered it odd that the children had not broken an outside
window in the walk-in closet where their bodies were found,
Cantrell said.
   ``Breaking the window would have saved their lives,'' he said.
   Authorities backed off Sunday from their allegations that two of
the children may have been sexually molested before they died.
   Kankakee County Coroner James Orrison said autopsies gave no
indication of sexual molestation. He said high levels of carbon
monoxide found in the children's blood confirmed earlier
speculation that the victims were alive at the time the fire
started, and died of smoke inhalation.
</TEXT>
