<FIRST>r a AM-HungerStrike     12-11 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunger Strike,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight End Hunger Strike Over El Salvador Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight hunger strikers protesting U.S.
military aid to El Salvador said Monday they had ended the fast
they began Thanksgiving Day at the Cathedral of St. Paul.
   ``The hunger strike was something that just a few people could
participate in,'' said Rene Hurtado, a Salvadoran refugee leading
the protest. ``By ending the hunger strike, we are allowing
everybody to participate with us in fighting to stop military aid
to El Salvador.''
   Hurtado also said the group was persuaded partly by pleas from
Gov. Rudy Perpich, U.S. House Speaker Thomas Foley and U.S. Rep.
Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn.
   Doctors had said the strikers were entering a critical period
that would greatly stress their systems.
   On Sunday, Perpich and Sikorski attended a nondemoninational
prayer vigil at the church that drew more than 3,000 participants,
organizers said.
   Perpich said the fast should be suspended until Congress acts on
the issue. Sikorski said the strikers' strengths were needed to
continue working toward resolving the issue.
   Foley had called the strikers Friday, urging them to end their
fast, and promised that military aid to El Salvador would be a
major issue when Congress reconvenes next month.
   The hunger strikers included three refugees from El Salvador.
Another is from Guatemala, one is from Bolivia and three are from
the United States, including a Maryknoll priest.
   Their water-only fast began shortly after the murder of six
Jesuit priests in El Salvador last month. The fasters had said they
would die in the cathedral unless their demands were met.
   But in a joint statement Monday, the eight said they ``have seen
a serious response from political and religious leaders, along with
a tremendous outpouring of support from Minnesotans and others
throughout the country.''
   ``The voiceless are making their voices heard,'' they said.
   Church officials had said the strikers could remain in the
cathedral as long as other church services and activities were not
disrupted.
</TEXT>
