<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Czech-Police     12-11 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Police,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revolution Turns Tables on Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students have turned the tables on
the secret police and are keeping 24-hour watch on state security
headquarters.
   Three students hovered close to the entrance of the police
headquarters on Bartolomejska Street on Monday, serving their time
on the front lines in a psychological war against the despised
security force.
   For decades the shadowy force, known as the STB, threatened,
blackmailed and used every means imaginable to control and silence
citizens.
   A network of vicious spies and informers, the STB wove a web of
phone taps and bugs and cameras set up on street corners throughout
Prague.
   But everything in Czechoslovakia has suddenly been turned upside
down, and those who not long ago were behind bars as dissidents are
now leading the nation as ministers.
   Jiri Dienstbier and Jan Carnogursky, two former dissidents, on
Sunday became members of the cabinet and Carnogursky joined a
three-man commission overseeing the police. Once interrogated, they
now will have some questions of their own.
   Student leaders warn that when the locked drawers are finally
opened, thousands of incriminating files may be missing.
   In the Moravian town of Brno, students began keeping an eye on
police Friday after accusing them of burning documents in a nearby
forest, a charge reported by the state news agency CTK.
   ``To say openly what they may be trying to do is the greatest
danger to a group that operates in secrecy,'' said student
spokeswoman Monica Bajerova. ``Every citizen will be watching.
   ``The surveillance in Brno and here is part of the pressure we
want to put on to keep the secret police under control,'' she said.
   But the police plead innocence.
   Jiri Bitcanek, chief of uniformed police for Central Bohemia,
denied in an interview with Western reporters that any documents
have been removed from his office. Trouble is, Bitcanek only took
the job four days ago. His predecessor abruptly found a new career.
   Bitcanek voluteered to interview in place of the head of secret
police. He said he did not know who was now head of the furtive
force since the former chief was removed last week.
   He confessed that morale among his comrades has hit a new low
and that the force is in shambles.
   ``You have to realize that this is a corps set up along military
lines and that right now we are not receiving any orders,'' he
said, while chanting from a small street demonstration drifted
through his office window.
   Bitcanek said police, especially secret police, were only
following orders from the Communist Party hierarchy. Now they're
being held responsible.
   ``I went down to talk to the students when they came on Friday.
They photographed me,'' Bitcanek complained. ``They were taking
pictures of every person who came in or out of our building.''
   ``I asked them to stop. I don't havu any guarantee that a
picture of a policeman in this emotionally charged, psychotic
atmosphere will not be used against the agent or his family,'' he
said.
   The police, who are estimated to number over 100,000, are just
the latest security force to come under citizen attack.
   On Dec. 2, the Communist Party disarmed its paramilitary force,
the People's Militia. On Dec. 7, Defense Minister Miroslav Vacek
gave his assurance to opposition leader Vaclev Havel that the army,
estimated by Western experts at 145,000, would never be used
against the citizens.
   Despite such assurances, many Czechoslovaks suffer the psychic
scars of the last 40 years and are finding it hard to shed their
fears.
   They remember philosopher Jan Patocka, the guiding spirit of the
human rights group Charter 77, who died after eight hours of police
interrogation 12 years ago.
   ``We are still nervous,'' said a 32-year-old writer who
requested he not be identified. ``Maybe we are demanding too much
too fast. Will the secret police stand for this?''
   A student in front of the station on Monday said they didn't
have any choice: ``Now it's not the Soviets, it is the people who
are here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
