<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--MultipleTransplant     12-11 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Multiple Transplant,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heart-Liver-Kidney Recipient Back on Ventilator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first person to undergo a simultaneous
heart, liver and kidney transplant was placed back on a ventilator
after she developed a pancreas inflammation, hospital officials
said Monday.
   Cindy Martin, 26, of Archbald was in critical condition Monday
at Presbyterian-University Hospital of Pittsburgh.
   Her condition was downgraded from serious over the weekend when
her pancreas became inflamed, a complication that doctors believe
is related to the Dec. 3 transplant operation, said hospital
spokeswoman Lisa Rossi.
   But doctors said her transplanted organs were functioning well.
   ``It is a temporary setback, but it seems to be getting
better,'' Ms. Rossi said.
   Mrs. Martin underwent a heart transplant in 1985 because of a
congenital condition, but suffered chronic rejection and eventually
developed hepatitis and kidney dysfunction.
</TEXT>
