<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     12-11 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Christian Militiamen Wounded in Highway Shootout with Army</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Christian militiamen were wounded
in a shootout with Gen. Michel Aoun's troops on a highway Monday,
sending commuters fleeing for cover and underscoring growing
friction between Christian forces.
   Police said the three wounded men belonged to Samir Geagea's
6,000-member Lebanese Forces, which favors an Arab League-brokered
peace plan to end Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   A quarrel developed over traffic rights in the afternoon rush
hour, police said. A Lebanese Forces jeep tried to overtake an army
patrol at the Death River intersection of the main coastal highway
in east Beirut.
   ``Militiamen in the jeep opened up with submachine guns at the
patrol. The soldiers retaliated by tossing a hand grenade that blew
up the jeep,'' said a police spokesman who cannot be identified
under standing rules.
   Hundreds of motorists in the bumper-to-bumper traffic panicked.
Many crashed into others' cars and then leaped out to duck for
cover, leaving their doors ajar, the spokesman said.
   It took traffic police half an hour to remove the three victims
to hospital and restore order on the highway, the spokesman added.
   ``The incident appeared spontaneous, but the underlying tension
between the two sides is unmistakable,'' the spokesman said.
   The Lebanese Forces and Aoun's army have been on a collision
course since the general rejected the Arab peace plan under which a
new president, Elias Hrawi, was elected Nov. 24. Aoun rejected the
plan for not specifying when Syrian troops would leave Lebanon.
   Hrawi has fired Aoun from all his posts. But the general is
holding out with 20,000 loyal troops in the presidential palace,
located in the Christian enclave.
   Hrawi, Aoun and Geagea are all Maronites, the Christian sect
that has dominated power in Lebanon since it gained independence
from France in 1943.
   Aoun has rejected Hrawi's presidency, calling him a ``Syrian
puppet'' because he was elected by Parliament in an area controlled
by the Syrian army in east Lebanon.
   The Syrians moved in reinforcements two weeks ago and have
threatened to evict Aoun by force from the Baabda place, five miles
east of Beirut. But tens of thousands of supporters have since
formed a human wall around the hilltop palace in a massive display
of pro-Aoun sentiment in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave.
   Geagea has declared his militia would fight alongside Aoun's
army if the enclave was attacked by the Syrians, who maintain
40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the
Arab League.
   But Geagea also made it plain in televised speeches to his
supporters that he recognizes Hrawi's legitimacy, always referring
to him as ``President Hrawi.''
</TEXT>
