<FIRST>r a AM-EversSlaying     12-11 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Evers Slaying,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Epected To Review 1963 Slaying Of Civil Rights Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury that convened Monday is
expected to make a preliminary examination of evidence in the 1963
slaying of civil rights leader Medgar Evers.
   However, Hinds County District Attorney Ed Peters has said he
expects no indictment by this grand jury in the Evers slaying.
Prosecutors say they are continuing to investigate the killing and
could present more evidence to a later grand jury.
   ``In fact that is probably what is going to happen,'' said
Assistant District Attorney Bobby DeLaughter. ``All we wanted to do
with this grand jury is advise them what has happened. It doesn't
mean we are quitting. We have to start somewhere, sometime, and
this is it.''
   Evers, field director of the Mississippi chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, was shot to
death June 12, 1963, outside his Jackson home.
   White supremacist Byron De La Beckwith, a former Greenwood
fertilizer salesman, was tried twice in Hinds County Circuit Court
in 1964. Two all-white juries were unable to reach verdicts and the
charge was dropped.
   Newspaper reports on Oct. 1 said he state's defunct segregation
spy agency, the Sovereignty Commission, had screened potential
jurors for Beckwith's second trial to aid the defense. Beckwith now
lives in a suburb of Chattanooga, Tenn.
   The reports raised questions about jury tampering. However, Erle
Johnston of Forest, who served as executive director of the
commission during the time of Beckwith's trials, insisted that
there was no tampering.
   Representatives of the district attorney's office have since
talked to all but one or two of the jurors from the second trial.
DeLaughter would not say what the jurors said.
   DeLaughter and two investigators have examined records and
conducted interviews in the Evers case.
   ``For right now we have been focused on the second trial,''
DeLaughter said. ``There were no allegations concerning the first
trial.''
   The grand jury that convened Monday is expected to meet through
most of the week. Prosecutors declined to say when the Evers matter
might be discussed. The panel's proceedings will not be open to the
public.
   Evers' widow, Myrlie, met privately Friday with Peters and
DeLaughter for an hour-long briefing. She said she was not asked to
testify before the grand jury on her husband's slaying.
   ``I cannot tell you ... if I am satisfied with the actions of
that office because I have not seen enough,'' she said.
   ``I would simply hope that as the investigation goes on,
whatever happens, that justice be done ... that there will be
enough evidence to convict,'' Ms. Evers said.
</TEXT>
