<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages     12-11 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Urges Release of Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOHA, Qatar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has urged its ``friends'' in Lebanon to
free the Western hostages, a senior Iranian official said in an
interview published Monday.
   ``We have directed our advice to our friends in Lebanon to cease
their acts with respect to the kidnapping of the Western
hostages,'' the newspaper Al-Raya quoted Deputy Foreign Minister
Ali Mohammed Besharati as saying.
   ``But the problem is that every time the atmosphere becomes
propitious for the release of the hostages, there are
counterincidents that cloud the atmosphere,'' said Besharati, who
ended a two-day visit to this Persian Gulf nation on Sunday.
   The paper said he was referring to the kidnapping by Israeli
commandos of Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, a Shiite Moslem preacher from
south Lebanon, on July 28.
   On July 31, Shiite Moslem kidnappers of the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth said they killed their American hostage Lt. Col.
William Higgins in retaliation for the kidnapping.
   Most of the 18 hostages held in Lebanon are believed to be in
the hands of Iranian-backed Shiite groups. They are eight
Americans, four Britons, two West Germans, two Swiss, an Irishman
and an Italian.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985 in west Beirut.
   The death of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and the election of the
more pragmatic President Hashemi Rafsanjani gave rise to some hopes
of Iranian pressure on the kidnappers to free their captives.
   Before coming to Qatar, Besharati visited the United Arab
Emirates as part of Iran's active contacts with the conservative
Gulf Cooperation Council member states ahead of their annual summit
Dec. 18 in Oman.
   Qatar, the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Kuwait, Bahrain and Saudi
Arabia make up the council, which generally supports the policies
of Iraq, Iran's long-time enemy.
   Relations between Iran and the council states, with the
exception of Saudi Arabia, have been steadily improving since
Persian Iran accepted the U.N.-sponsored cease-fire to the
eight-year war with Arab Iraq.
