<FIRST>r w AM-US-Yugoslavia     12-11 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Yugoslavia,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Urges Support For Yugoslav Premier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed concern Monday
about rising tensions in Yugoslavia and urged the people to unite
in support of the reform efforts of Prime Minister Ante Markovic.
   ``Mutual respect, adherence to democratic principles, and a
commitment to avoiding violence are crucial to resolving this
situation,'' State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   Tensions among Yugoslavia's loose federation of six republics
were exacerbated Monday when the leadership of the Communist
country's second-largest state _ Croatia _ called for the
establishment of a multiparty system.
   Until now the liberal northern state of Slovenia was the only
one of Yugoslavia's six constituent republics to openly advocate
the introduction of Western-style democracy.
   Earlier this month Serbia, in an apparent move to stifle
burgeoning democratic trends in the country, severed all business
and official ties with Slovenia. The unprecedented action shook the
foundations of Yugoslavia's system.
   The United States supports ``a united federal Yugoslavia in
which human rights and civil rights of all citizens are
protected,'' Boucher said. ``The U.S. strongly supports the ongoing
efforts of Yugoslav Prime Minister Markovic to create a
market-based economy and to promote greater political pluralism.
   ``We urge all Yugoslavs to put aside their differences and to
focus their energies on this important reform effort,'' he said.
