<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Treasurer 1stLd-Writethru   12-11 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Treasurer, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0591,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Treasurer Sworn In</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs `Ms. Villalpando ...' with 1 graf to ADD her
hometown. Picks up 5th graf pvs `She is ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catalina Vasquez Villalpando took the oath of
office Monday as U.S. Treasurer, the official whose signature goes
on every bill.
   President Bush was on hand for the ceremony in the Indian Treaty
Room of the Old Executive Office Building, as were Ms.
Villalpando's parents, grandmother, three sisters and other
relatives.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady administered the oath, and
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, held the Bible.
   Ms. Villalpando, of San Marcos, Texas, is a former senior
executive of Communications International Inc., a
telecommunications company. She worked for President Reagan in
1983-85 as a special assistant for public liaison.
   She is also a past chairwoman of the Republican National
Hispanic Assembly.
   Bush called her a ``remarkable woman'' with a reputation as a
strong adminstrator.
   ``During her White House service, Cathy demonstrated outstanding
creativity in working on issues of direct importance to our
nation's Hispanic citizens,'' Bush said.
   Her duties include overseeing the Bureau of Engraving and
Printing, the U.S. Mint and the U.S. Savings Bond program, along
with putting her signature on U.S. currency. Brady's name also goes
on the bills.
