<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Casolo     12-11 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Casolo,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Salvadorans Are Treating Arrested Connecticut Woman Fairly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Central America and AM-US-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday he has asked
Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani to ensure that a Connecticut
woman arrested on suspicion of storing arms for rebel forces
receive a fair trial.
   In his first public remarks about the Nov. 26 arrest in San
Salvador of Jennifer Casolo, Bush said all indications are that
Casolo will be treated fairly.
   ``I think it's essential that she receive a fair trial,'' Bush
said at a White House news conference. ``So far I have not received
any indication that she will not receive a fair trial.''
   The Bush administration came under sharp criticism from
congressional Democrats after presidential spokesmen made comments
indicating that the Salvadoran government had a case against Casolo.
   Bush made no mention of the criticism. He said nothing
indicating that the government is seeking amnesty for Casolo or
considers her innocent.
   ``I have instructed our ambassador, (William Walker) and indeed
talked to Cristiani personally, to represent to the Salvadorans
that it's essential that a fair trial be granted,'' Bush said.
   ``I am satisfied so far that that will take place,'' he added.
``But it is essential that it not only take place but that it have
all the appearances of fairness, and I think that's what Mr.
Cristiani is determined to do.''
   Casolo, a 28-year-old resident of Thomaston, Conn., went to El
Salvador in 1985 to work for Christian Education Seminars, a group
dedicated to influencing U.S. policy by organizing tours for
Americans to learn about the 10-year-old civil war.
   She and two Salvadoran friends were arrested Nov. 26 after a
police raid on her white stucco house in San Salvador. From the
walled garden behind the house, police said they uncovered 103
mortar grenades, 213 blocks of dynamite, 405 detonators, 150 feet
of slow-burning fuse and 21,945 rounds of ammunition for
Soviet-made automatic rifles.
   Casolo was ordered held Friday for 90 days while an
investigation continues into possible links between her, the
explosives and Salvadoran rebel forces.
   Casolo's friends and family insist she is innocent, the victim
of a setup. The Rev. Jesse Jackson attended a service Sunday in
Hartford attended by Casolo's parents and friends during which
Jackson criticized Bush saying it was ``sad'' that the president
``will not argue Jennifer's case.''
   U.S. Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., among those to criticize
Bush for his handling of the Casolo case, arranged for former U.S.
Attorney General Ramsey Clark to represent Casolo in El Salvador.
Salvadoran law prevents Clark from actually defending Casolo in
court. A Salvadoran attorney will represent her at trial while
Clark serves as a legal advisor.
</TEXT>
