<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Elections     12-11 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Elections,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early Results: People's Front Gains Over Half of Vote in Latvia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preliminary results of weekend local elections in
Latvia show the grassroots People's Front gaining over half the
vote in most regions and winning landslides in the countryside, an
activist said Monday.
   The People's Front, which favors independence for the small
Baltic republic, is now expected to win about 60 percent overall
and 80 percent of the rural vote in the final count, said member
Christian Rozenvalds.
   In Estonia, where elections also were held Sunday for seats in
local councils, results were not expected for several days, but
polls have indicated environmentalists were likely to receive half
the vote there.
   The elections were the first in a series of local votes to be
held in the coming months in all 15 republics as part of the Soviet
transition to multicandidate races and greater democracy.
   They are considered critical for Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms
because it is the vast numbers of local and regional bureaucrats
who are blamed for blocking implementation of his new programs.
   In the Latvian capital of Riga, Communist Party boss Arnolds
Klautsens received only 40 percent of the vote for a seat in the
local council, and Rozenvalds said he was unlikely to win a run-off
because a citywide scandal had arisen about ballots faked in his
favor.
   Officials have predicted widespread defeats for Communist
leaders in both republics.
   There were 33,500 candidates running for city council and other
regional ``soviets'' in the two republics.
</TEXT>
