<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DrugSummit     12-11 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Summit,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Not Going to Colombian Summit Would Send Wrong Signal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a high-level U.S. advance team left to
prepare for a drug summit in violence-torn Colombia, President Bush
said Monday he wants to go, despite some aides' misgivings, to
avoid sending a signal that traveling there is unsafe.
   ``Right now I'm very hopeful that the meeting will take place in
Cartagena,'' Bush told a group of editorial writers at the White
House.
   The administration advance team that left Monday will be
pressing for a stronger commitment from the cocaine-producing
countries of Peru and Bolivia on eradicating their large coca
crops, officials said.
   Bush acknowledged the security concerns some officials have
raised about taking his entourage to Colombia, but added:
   ``I don't want to be the one that sends a signal that nobody
should go to Colombia if they can't be protected.''
   He said a final decision has not been made on going to
Cartagena, a major center of drug-trafficking operations for the
Andes.
   ``I will listen to the experts. I will not do anything
imprudent. Nobody has ever accused me of doing anything too daring.
   ``But I don't want to undermine this courageous leader,'' he
said of Colombian President Virgilio Barco. He said he did not want
to ``send some signal'' that Barco ``can't provide the security for
three heads of state visiting his country.''
   The administration advance team, headed by Assistant Secretary
of State Bernard Aronson, left for Cartagena on Monday to work on
an agenda and lay groundwork for the summit. The team will also
visit Peru and Bolivia to push for greater evidence of commitment
on the part of those two countries in the antidrug efforts, said
officials.
   The summit will include Peruvian President Alan Garcia and
Bolivian President Jaime Paz Zamora in addition to Bush and Barco.
   The advance group also will try to coordinate with the other
nations on strategy and will discuss future U.S. assistance. Among
the items that will be addressed are cooperation on money
laundering, sharing intelligence, extradition and crop substitution
for the coca fields.
   Bush's drug policy coordinator, William Bennett, said the
administration finds Colombia's antidrug actions and commitment
``exemplary.''
   But he told reporters last week that ``the jury is still out''
on Peru and Bolivia, both of which receive drug-fighting aid from
the United States.
   He did not elaborate, but one administration official, speaking
on the condition of anonymity, said, ``They could be more
aggressive.''
   Drug Enforcement Administration officials have said that the
eradication program in Peru and Bolivia is still developing and is
improving.
   Bush has repeatedly praised Barco's efforts in the face of
escalating bombings and violence laid to drug lords against
civilian and government targets.
   Colombia's problems revolve mostly around drug-processing
activities and smuggling, with the major cocaine cartels operating
from there.
   But Peru and Bolivia have the agricultural fields where large
quantities of coca leaves are cultivated for processing into
cocaine.
   ``There is definitely a lot of coca out there that has not been
eradicated,'' an administration official said Monday. ``Clearly,
people need to get energized and intensify their efforts.'' He also
requested anonymity.
   Officials have said that the extent of U.S. assistance to the
three Andean countries is tied to their performance on the drug
efforts.
   The administration wants to see more emphasis by those
governments on economic alternatives for the farmers whose
livlihoods would be stripped by eradication of their coca crops,
officials said.
   By law, the White House must certify each year that countries
are cooperating in the war on drugs before they can receive foreign
aid.
   Negligible progress in reducing coca production has been
achieved despite spending of more than $100 million on the problem
over the last 17 years, according to a State Department report to
Congress in July.
   The department says that coca production has increased every
year.
   Figures provided by Bennett's office say Peru produced 249
metric tons of coca in 1988 and Boliva 160 metric tons, while
Colombia's crop was put at 49 metric tons.
   Among those accompanying Aronson to Colombia this week are
Bennett's deputy, John Walters, and Michael Skol, the deputy
assistant security of state for South American affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
