<FIRST>r w AM-RockyFlats     12-11 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Plutonium Managers to be Removed in Nuclear Plant Shakeup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Managers of five of the six plutonium
processing buildings at the idled Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant
likely will be replaced next month as part of a broad plan for
improving safety, officials said Monday.
   Some details of the plan were spelled out for an Energy
Department advisory panel by David B. Van Leuven, who will be
associate general manager for defense programs at Rocky Flats when
EG&amp;G Inc. takes over as plant operator Jan. 1.
   The current operator, Rockwell International Corp., announced in
September it was quitting Rocky Flats because of a dispute with the
Energy Department over potential criminal liability for past
environmental violations.
   The plant, on the outskirts of Denver, is owned by the Energy
Department and is the nation's only maker of plutonium triggers for
nuclear weapons.
   A phased halt to Rocky Flats plutonium operations began in
mid-November to give EG&amp;G time to develop an improvement plan. The
plant has been criticized by government and independent inspectors
for a wide variety of shortcomings, including inadequate safeguards
against worker exposure to radiation.
   Van Leuven told the Advisory Committee on Nuclear Facility
Safety that he would inspect the management of all six plutonium
buildings in the next few weeks, and that he would bring five
executives from other EG&amp;G-operated facilities to be on ``ready
standby'' to replace up to five of the building managers.
   Van Leuven said he already had determined that five of the six
managers, who work for Rockwell International, are unlikely to meet
EG&amp;G's managerial standards.
   ``One has the capabilities I'm looking for, the rest are
questionable,'' he said.
   Van Leuven said Energy Secretary James D. Watkins ordered EG&amp;G
to develop by the third week in January a timetable for restarting
Rocky Flats plutonium operations. He declined to speculate on how
long the plant would be idled, but said it would not be restarted
until all safety-related questions had been answered.
   ``We'll take however long it takes'' to ensure safe operation,
he told a reporter.
   Phil Warner, the designated EG&amp;G general manager at Rocky Flats,
told the panel an ``integrated plan'' for running Rocky Flats
probably would be ready by the end of March.
   Van Leuven said later that referred to a long-range plan for
improving the plant, and that a phased restart of plutonium
operations could begin before that plan is ready.
</TEXT>
