<HEAD>Mexican Businessman Charged with Conspiracy to Kill U.S. Drug Agent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother-in-law of a former Mexican
president was charged Monday with conspiracy in the slaying of a
U.S. drug agent as part of a plot to keep a major international
drug trafficking cartel in business.
   Rubin Zuno Arce, 59, was to be arraigned later Monday on the new
charges linked to the 1985 torture-killing of Drug Enforcement
Administration agent Enrique Camarena Salazar.
   Zuno Arce, among 13 people charged in connection with Camarena's
death, was charged with conspiracy to commit violent crimes,
conspiracy to kidnap a federal agent and committing violent crimes
in aid of racketeering. If convicted, he faces a maximum of life in
prison.
   Juan Jose Bernabe Ramirez, a co-defendant, is charged with the
felony murder of a federal agent, among other things.
   Zuno Arce, a businessman and brother-in-law of former Mexican
President Luis Echeverria, was arrested Saturday by the DEA as he
got off a plane arriving from Mexico at Los Angeles International
Airport.
   The agents arresting Zuno Arce were part of a task force that
was set up in 1985 exclusively to investigate the slayings in
Mexico of Camarena and his Mexican pilot.
   DEA agents believed Zuno Arce was visiting Los Angeles to help
his attorneys prepare a defense for his federal perjury trial
slated to begin this month, said Lochridge.
   Zuno Arce first was arrested Aug. 9 in San Antonio, Texas and
escorted to Los Angeles to testify before the grand jury probing
Camarena's slaying.
   Camarena, 37, was abducted in Guadalajara in February 1985. His
severely beaten body and that of his pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar,
were found in a remote area 70 miles north of the city.
   Zuno Arce was charged with lying when he told the grand jury he
didn't know two alleged Mexican drug kingpins connected to the
killings.
   The businessman owned a house in Guadalajara that was sold to
reputed drug baron Rafael Caro Quintero shortly before the
slayings. The government alleges Camarena was tortured and killed
in the house.
   Zuno Arce was released on $200,000 bail on the perjury charge
despite a federal prosecutor's contention that he was a flight
risk. But he appeared in court in late October for a hearing.
