<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Building,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Dismisses Suit to Bar Africa's Tallest Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's highest court Monday
dismissed an environmentalist's lawsuit that tried to prevent the
ruling party from building Africa's tallest building in a city park
that is popular with the poor.
   The High Court dismissed a suit filed Nov. 24 by
environmentalist Wangari Maathai that sought to prevent the Kenya
African National Union from building a 60-story tower in Nairobi's
downtown Uhuru Park.
   Justice Norbury Dugdale, in his ruling to a packed courtroom,
said only the attorney general can sue on behalf of the public.
   Mrs. Maathai, who before the ruling accused the court of being
more concerned with ``politics than law,'' said she was
disappointed with the decision but had written to acting Attorney
General Timothy Mibei asking him to take up the matter.
   ``The most important thing is to rise and express one's opinion
and say no when you should say no,'' she said. ``If we are not
listened to then at least we have done what we could do within our
own constraints.''
   Mibei was unavailable for comment Monday.
   The controversy involves the ruling party's plans to build a
media complex in 10-acre Uhuru Park that would include the 60-story
tower, two 10-story wings, malls, an auditorium, parking for 2,000
people, and conference facilities for 5,000 people.
   Scores of people have written letters to Kenya's two independent
newspapers criticizing the plan and pleading with the government to
move the complex elsewhere.
   But President Daniel arap Moi told critics two weeks ago to
``shut up'' and succeeded in silencing all but Mrs. Maathai. A
four-story statue of Moi is planned for the front of the tower.
   Mrs. Maathai has continued to pursue her efforts to get the
building relocated to one of the vast open areas around Nairobi
despite Parliament's threats to ban her environmental organization,
the Green Belt Movement.
   She says the $197 million project is not in the public interest.
   Lawmakers said her court effort to bar the complex was
tantamount to suing the head of state and accused her 12-year-old
environmental group of being subversive.
</TEXT>
