<SECOND>AM-People-De Lorean,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed Auto Maker John De Lorean Battles Lawsuits and Plans New Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five years after his acquittal on cocaine
trafficking charges, auto maker John Z. De Lorean remains embroiled
in litigation that has stalled his plans to launch a new, more
exotic car company.
   ``It's incredible. What happens in the legal system is they keep
you there until you run out of money and then they move on to
someone else,'' De Lorean said in a telephone interview Friday from
his New York apartment.
   But the 64-year-old onetime golden boy of Detroit's executive
suites isn't discouraged. He says he sees an end to all the
lawsuits and is delighted about a recent British High Court
decision throwing out a $60 million default judgment against him.
   ``All these things, if they don't kill you they make you
stronger,'' he said.
   De Lorean has counter-sued the British government for $200
million _ one of the lawsuits still pending. In another, De
Lorean's California lawyer, Howard Weitzman, has sued him over fees.
   De Lorean said he's spent $6 million to $7 million on legal fees
since 1982. But he's not hurting for money. With bankruptcy
proceedings resolved, he has regained access to a snow grooming
company in Utah that he said is being sold for $26 million.
   DeLorean also said he's back on good terms with his former wife,
model Cristina Ferrare, with whom he underwent a bitter divorce.
   ``We're really getting along very well,'' he said. ``It's great
for the children.''
   As for his present love life, he said, ``I've been going with a
nice girl. But I'm not sure I'm good at being married.''
   What's left is his first and forever love _ cars.
   ``I've got another car I'm working on,'' he said. ``I'm building
it in Germany. I have a number of patents.''
   The new company, he said, won't start up until all of his
lawsuits are settled, and it won't half as ambitious as DMC.
   ``It's going to be an exotic,'' he said of his new dream car,
``a V-12, very high performance car and it will be very expensive,
in the $175,000 range. The more expensive and more limited, the
less it costs to go in.''
