<SECOND>AM-Congress-Eastern Europe,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panels to Hold Hearings on Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations and Armed
Services committees will hold a series of hearings early next year
to explore the changes occurring in Eastern Europe and the Soviet
Union and their implications for the United States.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, said Monday
that a central question is the extent to which the military threat
posed by the Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact has been reduced and
how U.S. military strategy and defense spending should be adjusted.
   Mitchell said administration officials, including Secretary of
State James A. Baker III, and outside experts will be called as
witnesses.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the Armed Services Committee chairman,
said his panel also would focus on the implications for
conventional and strategic arms control and the military role of
U.S. allies.
   Mitchell said that while there is much speculation that a
reduced military threat from the Soviet Union will lead to reduced
defense spending, it is not clear whether that will result in a
``peace dividend'' that can be used to meet other domestic spending
priorities.
