<FIRST>u a AM-SproutingCrosses     12-11 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sprouting Crosses,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Raise Crosses in Defiance of Atheist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUCONDA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An atheist forced village officials to
remove lighted crosses from two water towers, but residents are
fighting back with scores of home-made crosses in businesses, front
yards and windows.
   Christmas spirit and town unity have never been stronger,
residents of this community 30 miles northeast of Chicago said
Monday.
   ``We felt very badly that this man could come in here that
doesn't even live here, and say that we had to stop a tradition
we've been doing for years,'' said Katie Wolter. ``This is people's
way of speaking out.''
   Robert Sherman, a Midwest official of American Atheists Inc.,
contends the two disputed crosses _ which sat atop the village
water towers for almost 40 years and traditionally were lighted for
the Christmas season _ represented an unconstitutional mingling of
church and state.
   He threatened to sue the village if the crosses, removed last
winter for repairs, were used this Christmas season. The village
board decided Nov. 21 to replace them with lighted stars rather
than risk a costly legal battle.
   Sherman said the board's decision was a ``smashing victory'' for
American Atheists, which has challenged the use of crosses and
nativity scenes on public property across the country.
   ``This is the first time in the history of this country that
illuminated Christian crosses have been forced down from government
property without necessitating a lawsuit,'' said Sherman, of the
Chicago suburb of Buffalo Grove.
   But if there are no crosses on the water towers, they've sprung
up nearly everywhere else as the community of about 6,000 counters
the move.
   One of the first appeared on top of Mers Restaurant, a block
from the towers.
   ``When you see the crosses up, it's Christmas time,'' said
restaurant co-owner Bobby Mers, a lifelong village resident. ``I'm
still kind of upset that it's not on the tower. I grew up with it.''
   Hand-made crosses have appeared at Ms. Wolter's jewelry store
and other businesses and homes at the urging of Mayor James Keagle
and others.
   The Rev. Byron Maher has counted 95 crosses ``in just a fifth of
my parish'' since he exhorted his congregation at the
Transfiguration Roman Catholic Church to show their faith.
   ``Some are on the homes, some are in the yards, some are in the
windows, some people have used their TV antennas to make crosses _
they've put lights on them,'' Maher said.
   Kevin Kennebeck, vice president of Performance Paving, scaled a
110-foot telephone pole at his business to attach a 12-foot lighted
cross near the top that he hopes will mark a new tradition.
   The effect is not just visual, Maher said.
   ``Many people have come and told me that there's never been such
unity and Christmas spirit as there's been now,'' he said.
   Sherman said he thinks the response is more a show of resentment
toward atheists than a display of Christian faith or Christmas
spirit.
   Maher disputes that.
   ``It's not attacking him at all, it is showing our
Christianity,'' the priest said.
   ``In fact, we've got countless people here praying for him.''
</TEXT>
