<FIRST>u w AM-WhiteHouseChristmas     12-11 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House Christmas,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storybook Characters Come To White House For Christmas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The likes of Mary Poppins, Babar, the Mad
Hatter and the Tin Man enliven the White House this Christmas in a
decoration theme highlighting first lady Barbara Bush's commitment
to literacy.
   Mrs. Bush said Monday she hopes her holiday choice will
encourage families to read together.
   ``There is sort of a little message to our Christmas this year _
which is a family oriented, reading to their children message,''
she said as she showed off the majestic 18-foot Christmas tree in
the first floor Blue Room.
   The tree is decorated with 80 soft dolls each representing a
character from a storybook or literature. Among them: a
tafetta-bedecked Scarlett O'Hara with wide-brimmed southern lady's
hat; an ax-wieling Paul Bunyon astride his blue ox, Babe; a
satin-clad Aladdin with his genie bottle in hand; and a
school-marmish Jo from the classic ``Little Women.''
   Tiny books also adorn the tree, and beneath it have been placed
an array of books wrapped with bows.
   ``This is sort of a celebration of libraries and books,'' said
Mrs. Bush, who for many years has devoted herself to the cause of
literacy.
   The tree also has the traditional 100 four-inch velvet balls,
two representing each state in the nation.
   Mrs. Bush, fresh from her daily 1{-mile swim, gave reporters a
tour of the lavish White House decorations, which include 14 large,
snow-flocked Blue Spruce trees in the entrance and cross halls at
the main entrance.
   Planning for the decorations began last February when the first
lady discussed her wishes with the White house chief floral
designer, Nancy Clarke.
   In the East room stand two 14-foot Blue Spruce trees, ornately
garlanded with copper-red metallic ribbons and bursting with
life-size grapes, pears, apples, oranges, tangerines and
pomegranates.
   Also in the East room against a central mirror is displayed the
baroque 48-figure creche that has been in the White House every
Christmas since 1967 when it was donated by a New Jersey woman.
   Numerous poinsettias deck the halls and in the State Dining
Room, a giant gingerbread house is tempting the Bush grandchildren,
Mrs. Bush said. It was created by White House Executive Chef Hans
Raffert, who has baked a gingerbread house for the presidents
annually for the last 20 years.
   The table in the State Dining Room features two boxwood
topiaries decoated with densely packed candy canes, peppermint
balls and cookies.
   Mrs. Bush said there was a time when she did all the
Christmas-cookie baking for the family but now their cook makes and
decorates them.
   The Bushes will have their five children, spouses and 11
grandchildren on hand for the holiday. The entire clan will travel
to the presidential retreat at Camp David, Md., next week to spend
Christmas there.
   The family opens presents on Christmas day in what the first
lady predicted will be ``chaos.''
   She and the president will not exchange gifts, Mrs. Bush said.
   ``We do not give presents, the president and I,'' she said
adding that it is an arrangement they have followed for many years
because ``We felt we just had so much.''
   The Bushes were on hand this past weekend as 40 volunteers put
up the Christmas decorations. They had intended to spend the
weekend at Camp David, but were prevented by snowy weather. Mrs.
Bush said they enjoyed being there for the decorating.
   ``We bounced up and down the stairs, George and I, talking to
these people.''
   They came in Saturday night to find the decorators engaged in a
snow fight with the fake snow, she added.
   The Bushes have their own personal Christmas tree in their
private upstairs quarters and it is decorated with cookies, she
said.
</TEXT>
