<FIRST>r a AM-MasonTrial     12-11 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mason Trial,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Howard `Pappy' Mason Guilty in Murder of Police Officer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a violent crack ring was found
guilty Monday of ordering the murder of a rookie police officer who
was guarding the firebombed home of a witness in a drug case.
   Howard ``Pappy'' Mason, 31, faces mandatory life in prison
without parole for a slaying that had come to symbolize the battle
against illegal drugs.
   Jurors in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn deliberated 13 hours
over three days before finding Mason guilty on all 11
drug-conspiracy charges, including one specifying that he ordered
the February 1988 murder of Officer Edward Byrne, 22.
   Byrne's parents, Matthew and Ann Byrne, who had attended the
trial daily, embraced and thanked Assistant U.S. Attorney Leslie R.
Caldwell, before quickly leaving court by a rear door.
   The elder Byrne, a lawyer and former police lieutenant, gave his
slain son's badge to George Bush, who used it as a potent symbol
during his presidential campaign. Bush now keeps the shield in his
Oval Office desk.
   Mason boycotted most of his trial and remained in a courthouse
holding cell, presumably watching on closed-circuit television.
   Four other people were convicted in state court earlier this
year of carrying out the murder and have been sentenced to the
maximum of 25 years to life in prison.
   ``This accounts for all the people who had a hand in the brutal
murder,'' U.S. Attorney Andrew J. Maloney said of Mason's
conviction.
   State authorities let Mason be tried in federal court because
New York state rules of evidence restricting testimony by
codefendants made conviction in state court less likely.
   During the trial of the four convicted murderers, there was
frequent testimony that the order to assassinate Byrne had come
from Mason's cell at the Brooklyn House of Detention. He had been
convicted on a weapons charge and jailed two days before the
slaying.
   The prosecution's key witness, Viola Nichols, testified Mason
had directed the officer's murder because another patrolman
``disrespected'' him in front of his colleagues by upbraiding him
for drinking beer in public.
   Defense lawyer Harry C. Batchelder Jr. filed a motion to set the
verdict aside, asserting Mason was not mentally competent to
participate in his trial, which lasted about two weeks.
 
</TEXT>
