<DOCNO> AP891211-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush     12-11 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gives Self Good Grades for `Frustrating' Year With Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Friday cited ``enormous
frustrations'' in dealing with the Democratic-led Congress but said
he will hunt again next year for bipartisan support for his
sometimes-battered agenda.
   ``I'm disappointed in some ways with the Congress and with our
progress,'' Bush told a group of editorial-page editors. He cited
crime, clean-air legislation and child-care programs as examples.
   Democratic leaders in turn have said that those are all
important issues but that Bush's proposals would do too little to
solve problems or would take unwise approaches.
   Bush also suggested that the $50 billion approved by Congress to
rescue the ailing savings and loan industry ``might not be enough.''
   In a half-hour question-and-answer session, Bush cited
``negative, highly partisan comments'' from the Democrats in
Congress.
   Still, Bush, who began his term pronouncing an ``era of the
offered hand,'' said: ``I'm determined, when the Congress comes
back, to hold out the hand and try again.''
   On another partisan issue, the president dismissed as
``balderdash'' suggestions that Republicans are losing support
among voters because of the abortion issue.
   ``The American people have not changed their fundamental views
that had them support me over my opponent,'' Bush said. ``The
Democrats hold a seat, hold a gubernatorial seat, and they dance
around the grave of what they hope is the Republican party,'' he
added.
   He was referring to the Virginia governor's race in which
Democrat Douglas Wilder won last month after a campaign emphasizing
his views in favor of abortion rights.
   Overall, the president said he was generally satisfied with a
``productive year.'' He boasted that not one of his 10 vetoes had
been overridden.
   On other topics in the wide-ranging session, the president:
   _ Denied his decision to send National Security Adviser Brent
Scowcroft and a top State Department aide on a surprise visit to
Beijing marked a move toward ``full normalization'' of relations.
He said the weekend mission, four months after last June's bloody
government crackdown, was an attempt not to further ``isolate the
Chinese people.''
   _ Insisted he would do nothing to force the issue of German
reunification. ``It's too sensitive and it's not the role for the
United States to do that,'' Bush said, suggesting the day when
either the U.S. president or the Soviet leader had a role on the
issue of European boundaries had long passed.
   _ Reiterated his desire that a drug summit can be held next
February in Colombia, despite recent violence there, saying he
wanted no part of sending a signal that Colombian President
Virgilio Barco ``cannot provide the proper security.''
   _ Said that he would give more attention next year to trade
issues, saying that, while he had no intention of ``bashing''
trading partners needlessly, ``I am not relaxed about where we
stand'' in terms of dismantling foreign barriers against U.S. goods.
   _ Said that the United States does not favor any step that would
force Israel to be ``pressured into negotiating'' with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, despite Secretary of State James
A. Baker III's efforts to help formulate a way to get Middle East
peace talks going.
   _ Said he was ``satisfied so far'' that Jennifer Casolo would
receive a fair trial in El Salvador. Casolo, 28, of Thomaston,
Conn., was arrested Nov. 26 in a police raid at her house in San
Salvador. Police say they found weapons including grenades, and
dynamite, hidden behind her house.
   On Friday, Casolo was ordered held for 90 days while
investigation continues. Bush said he had personally told
Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani ``that it's essential that a
fair trial be granted.''
   Bush also denied allegations that U.S. officials had mistreated
a Salvadoran witness who had implicated the Salvadoran Army in the
slayings of six Jesuit priests last month.
   On his relations with Congress, Bush said, ``there have been
some good moments and there've been some enormous frustrations.''
   ``I am not overly satisfied, but I think the first year has gone
pretty well,'' he said.
   He said he was particularly pleased that the United States was
ending the year with a still-growing economy.
   And, while difficult budget choices loom, Bush said he was
pleased he had been ``able to keep my pledge of `no new taxes' for
this year.''
   At the same time, Bush said that efforts to clean up the
financially troubled savings and loan industry were proceeding
haltingly. Despite the $50 billion Congress authorized for Congress
to close down defunct S&amp;Ls, Bush said ``I'm now told this might not
be enough.''
   ``All I do know is that we've got to clean it up and it's a
whale of a mess,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
