<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-China     12-11 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-China,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Say They'll Revive Legislation Opposed by Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democrats, denouncing renewed
high-level Bush administration contacts with China as
``embarrassing kowtowing,'' vowed Monday to revive legislation
protecting Chinese students here and imposing sanctions against
their government.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, told reporters
that Bush's decision to dispatch two leading foreign policy
advisers to Beijing over the weekend undermines his
administration's professed support for human rights and ``sends the
worst possible message at the worst possible time.''
   Mitchell said Bush's move makes ``a mockery of our profession of
concern for human rights'' and was ``inconsistent with our stated
ideals.''
   The majority leader noted that Bush had declared in June that
the United States could not conduct normal relations with a
government that had reacted to weeks of pro-democracy
demonstrations with a bloody crackdown.
   ``Yet that is exactly what appears to be happening,'' Mitchell
said, referring to the mission to Beijing led by National Security
Adviser Brent Scowcroft and Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger.
   Mitchell said Bush's decision raises the question of how the
administration might react if the Soviet Union intervened
militarily to crackdown on democratic movements in Eastern Europe
and within its own borders.
   ``Will the president send his emissaries to Moscow to tell tham
that we want to do business as usual?'' Mitchell asked
hypothetically. ``Or are there two standards, one for the Chinese
and another for the Russians and everyone else?''
   The majority leader also said he will lead efforts to override
Bush's Nov. 30 veto of legislation to permit any Chinese student
fearful of reprisal if forced to return home to remain in the
United States beyond his visa's expiration.
   Bush said then that he was directing Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh ``to take the steps necessary to extend administratively
to all Chinese students in the United States the same benefits''
that were in the bill he was vetoing.
   Separately, the House and Senate voted just before adjourning
for the year Nov. 21 to impose political and economic sanctions on
the Chinese government. But the approvals were to slightly
different versions of the legislation and the differences were not
resolved before adjournment.
   Both versions would have imposed as a matter of law sanctions
Bush put in place days after the June 3 crackdown. Both measures
would permit the sanctions to be lifted if the human rights
situation in China improved.
   The White House opposes that legislation, saying Bush needs
flexibility in lifting the sanctions, which include a suspension of
financing for U.S. investment in China and a ban on exports to
China of military, nuclear and satellite technology.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs Asian subcommittee, said he believes Bush's veto of the
visa-extension bill will be overridden and that Congress will act
quickly to revive the sanctions legislation when it returns next
month.
   ``I believe the Congress is not in the mood to kowtow to these
Chinese leaders,'' Solarz said.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, called Bush's move ``ill timed to say the least.''
   At a time of major breakthroughs for democracy in Eastern
Europe, Bush's action sends the message that ``we care less about
human rights in China,'' Nunn said.
   Asked about Bush's announcment that China now has promised not
to sell missiles in the Middle East, Nunn noted that an identical
promise was made several years ago to then-Secretary of Defense
Frank Carlucci.
   ``If the Chinese have now promised that a second time, the
obvious question is, what happened the first time?'' Nunn said.
   Bush himself received a similar assurance when he visited China
in February.
</TEXT>
