<FIRST>r w AM-Poland-Harvest     12-11 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Harvest,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businesses Urged to Donate Ag Equipment to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three organizations intent on helping Poland
enhance its 1990 harvest Monday urged U.S. agriculture businesses
to donate desperately needed machinery, chemicals, feed and animal
pharmaceuticals.
   The donations are necessary because of a ``gap in the U.S.
legislative package'' that provided $533 million in assistance to
Poland and Hungary, said Josiah Lee Auspitz, secretary of the Sabre
Foundation, a non-profit educational and scientific organization
that promotes free enterprise.
   The government is sending commodities and expertise to Poland,
but there was no provision in the law for the ``inputs'' _ such as
machinery, fertilizer and feed _ needed to make a modern farm
system work, Auspitz said.
   Polish banks, he said, don't have the money to loan against next
year's harvest to enable the farmers to buy those input items.
   Fertilizers, animal-care products, animal feed, pesticides,
fungicides and herbicides top the list of items Polish farmers
need. Also needed is machinery such as, planters, grain drills,
potato seeders, fertilizer spreaders, manure spreaders, plows,
sprayers, chain saws and harvesters.
   ``It is feasible financially for companies to donate (these
items) without losing a lot of money,'' Auspitz said at a day-long
seminar sponsored by his foundation, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce
and the Foundation for the Development of Polish Agriculture, a
private Polish group dedicated to strengthening that nation's
private sector farms.
   The U.S. tax code allows for a deduction of twice the cost for
donations of inventory property for the care of the ill, the needy
or minor children. Private Polish farmers qualify as needy, said
tax lawyer Stuart A. Smith, who appeared on a panel with Auspitz.
   He said companies should make donations to a tax-exempt
organization, such as Sabre, which will certify the products are
going as gifts for the needy. The donated materials may not be
given to Polish government-owned farms or the government itself to
qualify for the U.S. tax deduction.
   About 77 percent of the farms in Poland are private, but under
communism, the state cooperatives were the only ones benefitting
from technological advances, David Hopper, senior vice president of
the World Bank, said during a separate panel discussion.
   ``The private sector has been starved from modern inputs,'' he
said.
   Polish farmers need the machinery and chemicals by April 1, the
beginning of the growing season, to show progress in the 1990
harvest.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher encouraged participation,
saying in a letter that Sabre's plan follows the intent of the
agreement on private-sector cooperation between Poland and the
United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
