<DOCNO> AP891211-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1753EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     12-11 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Opposition Accuses Sandinistas of Terror Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Opposition Union on
Monday accused the governing Sandinistas of waging a campaign of
provocation and violence to intimidate opponents in the Feb. 25
elections.
   Virgilio Godoy, the opposition union's vice presidential
candidate, and other party leaders told a news conference that
Sandinistas provoked rioting Sunday in Masatepe in which one man
was killed and more than 20 people were injured.
   He said the National Opposition Union (UNO) has sent a report on
the violence to a summit of five Central American presidents
meeting in San Jose, Costa Rica.
   Godoy acknowledged that UNO supporters also took part in the
fighting, but insisted the Sandinistas started it.
   ``Violence generates violence; this is inevitable,'' he said.
``Nobody here is going to wait to have their throat slit. But the
provocations continue, and the one responsible for this is the
Sandinista Front.'' he said. He added that UNO will not pull out of
the campaign.
   Other party officials told the news conference that after the
rioting in Masatepe, 30 miles south of Managua, groups of masked
men attacked UNO supporters in many nearby villages. They said they
were asking for protection from United Nations and Organization of
American States election observers.
   Godoy said the Sandinistas' plan to hold a rally in Masatepe
``makes us think that the government has decided to escalate the
violence to try to impede normal development'' of the election
campaign.
   Witnesses in Masatepe Sunday said clashes broke out during a UNO
rally at the town park and combatants fought with machetes, rocks
and sticks. The Sandanistas' Masatepe campaign headquarters was
attacked and a car and motocycle were set afire.
   Ricardo Lopez Cerda, a member of the Sandinista campaign
committee, said he and 12 other people had taken refuge in the
party headquarters when he saw about 200 people approach, vowing to
shoot everyone inside.
   He said he and the others escaped through the back of the
building. The building was heavily damaged and the furniture
burned. A home next door also was sacked.
   Mario Casco, a UNO leader in Masatepe, said groups of hooded men
fired at a house in nearby San Bernardo with rifles and doused
another home with gasoline and threatened to burn it unless the
occupants came out.
   When two men came out of the house one was beaten with clubs and
the other was doused with fuel and threatened with incineration,
Casco said. Similar incidents occurred in other villages, he said.
``It was a night of terror.''
   Manuel Guevara Calero, 38, of La Concepcion village, was stabbed
to death. Reports in pro-government newspapers quoted his mother,
Hilda Calero, as blaming UNO militants.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said in Washington
the Sandinista government ``is at a crossroads.
   ``It can hold free and fair elections without violence and
intimidation, and begin the process of bringing peace to Nicaragua.
Or it can continue to turn the thugs loose on peaceful opposition
rallies, thereby ensuring the election results will be deemed
illegitimate and that the crisis in Central America will continue.''
   Sandinista and UNO groups have battled several times since
campaigning began in early November but the Masatepe rioting was
the worst. On Dec. 3, rival groups engaged in a stone-throwing
melee in Confradias, 12 miles east of Managua, and dozens were
injured.
   The presidents of Costa Rica, El Salvador, Nicaragua, Guatemala
and Honduras are trying to arrange truces in the civil war in El
Salvador and the fighting between Nicaraguan rebels and the
Sandinistas.
   Under an earlier agreement, Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega
advanced the general election to this February from November 1990
and promised they would be free and fair. In exchange the Central
American leaders declared they would try to demobilize the
Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, most of whom are based in
Honduran border camps, by Dec. 5.
   The Contras, with U.S. backing, defied the deadline, saying they
should remain as a fighting force to make certain the elections are
fair.
</TEXT>
