<FIRST>r a AM-PoliceShooting     12-11 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Shooting,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Talk to Black Leaders Following Shooting of Unarmed Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officials met with black
leaders Monday to discuss the apparent accidental shooting of an
unarmed black man by a white policeman during a drug search.
   ``We want to get as much information out as possible,'' said
Police Chief Joe Gerwens.
   Patrick Lavon Lee, 28, was shot in the back of the head in a
predominantly black neighborhood Sunday by Officer Robert Thomas
McCabe, 28.
   Lee was in critical condition Monday at Broward General Medical
Center, and was not expected to recover, doctors said.
   Gerwens said the timing was ``unfortunate'' because of events in
Miami.
   The shooting was the second involving a police officer and an
unarmed suspect in south Florida since a Miami jury on Thursday
convicted Officer William Lozano of manslaughter in the deaths of
two black men killed last January.
   The slayings triggered three days of rioting, and Miami had
braced for more unrest in the event Lozano was acquitted.
   Later Thursday, a Hallandale police officer shot and killed an
unarmed robbery suspect following a car chase. Both the suspect and
the officer were black.
   On Sunday, McCabe's .45-caliber automatic apprently went off
accidentally as Lee was pinned against a car, police said.
Officials said they were unsure why the officer drew his gun
because the suspect wasn't armed.
   Gerwens contacted black leaders Sunday, held a news conference,
and met with them again Monday to release more information. Black
leaders told reporters they were satisfied with the way things were
being handled.
   ``The only thing we can do now is wait for the investigation,''
said Carlton Moore, former president of the Fort Lauderdale chapter
of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
``We need to know exactly what happened and how the firearm
discharged.''
   The Broward County state attorney's office is investigating the
incident. Prosecutors said a grand jury would decide whether to
charge McCabe. The police department is also investigating.
   McCabe and his partner were looking for drug dealers in one of
the city's most violent neighborhoods in northern Fort Lauderdale
when they encountered Lee and another man.
   Witnesses said McCabe cursed Lee, then grabbed him and threw him
against a car. McCabe then put his gun at the back of Lee's head.
   ``Pat's hands were up and he started to turn around and then the
gun went off,'' said Carolyn Howard, who was standing less than 10
feet away.
   ``Then the cop said, `Oh my God, my gun went off,''' Howard said.
   No statement has been taken from McCabe, who has been with the
department since August.
   McCabe is on administrative leave with pay ``to collect
himself,'' said police spokesman Ott Cefkin.
   Lee has been arrested several times and been convicted of armed
robbery and cocaine possession with intent to deliver, police said.
He did not have any cocaine on him at the time of the shooting,
they said.
</TEXT>
