<SECOND>AM-BRF-South Yemen,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Yemen Opens Door for Multiparty System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADEN, South Yemen (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This small, staunchly Marxist Arab
state has been swept up in the political reforms surging through
the Soviet bloc, with Aden radio saying Monday that the ruling
Marxists have opened the door for a multiparty system.
   It said the decision was adopted by the Central Committee of the
Yemen Socialist Party, the country's only legal party, at a two-day
meeting that concluded Monday afternoon.
   South Yemen, on the Red Sea, has developed strong political and
military links with the Soviet Union.
   The broadcast said the ground rules for the formation of new
parties would be published by the Political Bureau.
   The move was in line with a general political and economic
liberalization program that South Yemen has been introducing.
   Last month, independents were allowed to run in municipal
elections against party candidates.
