<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Widows     12-11 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Widows,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pensions Increased for Widows of Servicemen Killed Before 1973</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 53,000 widows of British servicemen killed
in action before 1973 will receive an increase of $62 in their
weekly pension, the government announced Monday.
   Legislators of all political parties had called for a correction
in the disparity between the amounts given to widows of servicemen
killed before and after 1973.
   Widows of more than 2,000 servicemen killed in combat since 1973
get a minimum weekly pension of $196. The maximum weekly amount
given to widows of servicemen killed before 1973 was $90.
   Defense Secretary Tom King told Parliament the pension increases
will be tax free and payments will begin in April.
   He said the Conservative Party government ``recognizes the very
special place that these widows hold in the affections of this
country, and the particular debt that we all owe them.''
   Dame Vera Lynn, the singing sweetheart of World War II soldiers,
had campaigned for the pension improvements and said she was
disappointed the payments wouldn't start until April.
   ``It's a shame it's not more and it's sad they couldn't have had
it for Christmas,'' she said. ``It would have been a lovely present
for them.''
   Roland Boyes, the opposition Labor Party spokesman, called the
government's decision ``a major, though acceptable U-turn.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
