<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 2ndLd-Writethru a0652 12-11 0891</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0652,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovaks Ring Freedom Bells; Look for President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with former official accused, details; edits
to trip. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XPRA1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joyous cacophony of bells and
whistles heralded a popular victory over the Communists, and
Czechoslovaks settled down Monday to choosing a president from
among heroes the old order called villains.
   A presidential contest appeared to be developing, and the people
may get to decide.
   ``This is the end of communism!'' exulted Jana Navara, an
actress in pink mukluks, adding the sound of a brass chime to the
bells of Prague's Tyn Church on Old Town Square. Her 3-year-old
daughter made a triumphant ``V'' with two tiny fingers.
   The brief blast of noise replaced a threatened general strike,
canceled after events brought to power the first government in 41
years not dominated by Communists and drove President Gustav Husak
from office.
   Soldiers began removing barbed wire from the border with neutral
Austria and Prague radio reported plans to disband Pacem im Terris,
a state-controlled organization of Roman Catholic clergy. Priests
outside the group often were persecuted as the state tried to
impose its will.
   In the first official act against members of the old leadership,
the prosecutor charged former party ideologue Vasil Bilak for his
part in crushing the 1968 Prague spring of reform, the official
news agency CTK reported.
   ``According to some opinions, his deeds can be considered
treason,'' it said, but added that Bilak, now 72, could not be
tried because the statute of limitations had run out.
   Elsewhere in Eastern Europe:
   _ Petar Mladenov, head of the Bulgarian Communist Party, said
free elections should be held in May and a new constitution written
that does not guarantee the party a monopoly on power.
   _ The four Allies of World War II held their first meeting in 18
years Monday and stressed the need for stability at a time of rapid
change in East Germany. It was requested by the Soviet Union, which
is concerned about German reunification.
   _ More than 150,000 people held a pro-democracy rally in
Leipzig, a southern industrial city in East Germany, and many
called for German unity.
   In Prague, Parliament meets Tuesday and has two weeks to elect a
president, but the Club of Communist Deputies, similar to a
majority party caucus, said Monday it would support a referendum.
   A statement from the club said it would ``recommend to the
Federal Assembly to adopt the necessary measures for an
all-people's vote'' because ``the authority of the head of state is
so important that only the people can decide,'' CTK reported.
   Earlier, Politburo member Ondrej Saling said the Communists and
opposition had agreed the president should be a Czech with no party
affiliation.
   ``In my view, the president must be someone who enjoys broad
support and guarantees stability,'' he said.
   That seemed to suggest Vaclav Havel, the playwright who was
jailed for opposing communism and is now the driving force behind
Civic Forum, the main opposition.
   Posters reading ``Havel na Hrad'' _ ``Havel to the Castle,'' the
presidential residence _ sprouted all over Prague.
   The candicacy of Alexander Dubcek, who led the 1968 reform as
party chief until Soviet tanks arrived, threw the result into
doubt, however, and other names were being mentioned.
   In a late-evening television interview with Soviet television,
shown in Prague, Havel said he would keep his country in the Warsaw
Pact.
   While evoking an ideal of Europe ``as a peaceful community''
with no military blocs, he said ``we shall not get any closer to
this ideal by any kind of individual split from the Warsaw treaty,''
   Havel's gravelly voice rolled over a crowd of 100,000 people
Sunday in Wenceslas Square. As he listed popular victories over the
past three weeks, which the people had come to celebrate, they
chanted ``We want Havel!'' and he made a very presidential bow.
   Dubcek, 68, remains a popular symbol but evokes little emotion
among younger Czechoslovaks, who regard him as a product of the
system they intend to abolish.
   He also is a Slovak, as is Marian Calfa, the new premier. Calfa
has said a political tradition, under which one office is held by a
Slovak and the other by a Czech, would be respected.
   Czechoslovakia joins Poland in forming an administration not
dominated by Communists, but unlike Poland, its government is led
by a member of the party.
   ``We have not won yet,'' Havel told the Sunday rally, which was
televised live. But, he added, ``The years-long, deadly silence of
a humiliated people has been drowned out by a multivoiced popular
choir.''
   A rally in support of Havel was held Monday at Plzen, west of
Prague, and many Czechoslovaks ringing bells around the country
also wore the ubiquitous blue, red and white ``Havel for
President'' buttons.
   The burst of bell-ringing occurred three weeks to the day after
students rose up, angered by brutal police assaults on peaceful
demonstrators. They surged through the streets of Prague, stopping
street cars to sound their bells, then everyone joined in.
   Soon afterward, a liberty bell appeared on a hill above Prague
where a statue of Stalin once had been. In letters visible across
the Vltava River, it was labeled, ``The final bell,'' the last line
of every Czechoslovak fairy tale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
