<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0656 12-11 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0656,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arens Demands U.S. Guarantees Before Talks, 14 Arabs Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with West Bank schools ordered to remain closed.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said Monday Israel
wants guarantees from the United States that the PLO will have no
role in the peace process before he attends talks in Washington.
   No date has been set for the meeting between Arens, Secretary of
State James A. Baker III and Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmet
Abdel-Meguid. The three will discuss the composition of a
Palestinian delegation to direct talks with Israeli officials.
   In violence Monday in the occupied territories, troops shot and
wounded 14 Palestinian protesters, Arab hospital officials said.
The army said it was investigating.
   Arens cast some doubt Monday on his planned trip to Washington,
saying he is concerned about reports that Egypt is acting as a
``postman'' for the PLO.
   ``The Egyptians, who started the process as an independent
factor, have lately presented themselves as, in effect, a postman
for the PLO,'' Arens said on army radio. ``If this is what will be,
I fear that we won't get very far.''
   Last month, the Cabinet linked Israeli acceptance of Baker's
proposal for the Washington meeting to assurances that the PLO
would play no part in the peace process.
   Asked about the proposed Washington trip, Arens said, ``Firstly,
I'm not going yet. We will first conduct contacts concerning the
guarantees that our Cabinet has requested.''
   Cabinet Secretary Eliakim Rubinstein is scheduled to go to
Washington this week to discuss the assurances sought by Israel,
said Avi Pazner, a spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   The latest hitch in the talks followed weekend news reports that
Israeli, Egyptian, U.S. and Palestinian officials were holding
secret contacts to draw up a preliminary list of Palestinian
negotiators.
   The clashes Monday were sparked by the fatal shootings Sunday of
two Palestinians, apparently by Israeli civilians who opened fired
after their cars were stoned, Israeli and Arab reports said.
   The deaths raised to 631 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israelis during the two-year uprising against Israeli rule. At
least 155 other Palestinians have been killed by their fellow Arabs
who accused them of cooperating with Israeli authorities or
involvement in prostitution or drug-dealing. Forty-three Israelis
also have died.
   In Gaza City, a military court sentenced four Palestinian men to
prison terms ranging from 10 to 14 years for throwing firebombs at
military patrols in April 1989, a military spokesman said. No one
was injured in the attacks.
   In Jerusalem, police said they detained for questioning at least
21 Palestinian youths after the funeral of 17-year-old Joseph
Albert Muneir turned into a nationalist demonstration.
   Muneir's family claims he died Sunday as a result of beatings by
Israeli soldiers, but a police investigation reported he died of
natural causes.
   About 500 Arab youths marched behind Muneir's coffin, singing
the Palestinian national anthem and waving the outlawed red, white,
black and green Palestinian flag. Nearly 100 police and
paramilitary border policemen stood guard.
   Israel's military administration of the occupied territories
ordered the United Nations Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA) to keep
the 90 schools it operates for Palestinian refugees in the occupied
West Bank closed until the new academic year begins Jan. 10.
   A spokesman for the administration said all 930 schools in the
West Bank will remain closed until then.
   The schools have been closed since the school year ended Nov. 1.
   UNRWA had announced its schools would reopen Monday to give
students a chance to complete the past academic year. The students
were unable to complete the full year because many schools have
been closed frequently during the uprising.
</TEXT>
