<FIRST>r w AM-DrunkenDriving 2ndLd-Writethru a0630 12-11 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drunken Driving, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0630,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Calls Drunken Driving a `Scourge' of the Age</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf Sullivan comment after 6th graf pvs, Skinner
said</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, calling drunken driving ``one
of the most deadly scourges'' of our times, promised Monday to keep
up pressures to get intoxicated drivers off the road. His
transportation secretary suggested new restrictions on alcohol
advertising may be necessary.
   Their comments came at a briefing at the White House for 150
anti-drunken driving activists plus health and safety officials.
   Bush signed legislation declaring this National Drunk and
Drugged Driving Awareness Week and issued a proclamation saying,
``As we prepare to celebrate the holidays and rejoice in the
promise of the new year, it is fitting that we pause to remember
the perils of drinking and driving.''
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner was peppered with
questions before Bush spoke about why the government does not raise
excise taxes on alcohol to discourage drinking and does not
restrict brewers' and liquor manufacturers' ads.
   ``I'm not so sure it isn't time to revisit those issues'' of
regulating advertising, said Skinner.
   Skinner said people are ``not going to stop drinking,'' but said
they must be stopped ``from getting behind the steering wheel.''
   Health Secretary Louis Sullivan was more direct, telling the
briefing that the nation should ``consider some form of
restrictions on the advertising of alcoholic beverages.''
   Bush said the public outcry in recent years against drunken
drivers has been ``one of the most amazing success stories of the
1980s.''
   Drunken driving deaths fell 20 percent in the last six years,
although the number of miles traveled rose 25 percent, Bush said.
   Still, almost 500,000 Americans are injured in alcohol-related
accidents and half the 50,000 fatalities on America's highways each
year are alcohol-related, ``an annual toll that would nearly fill
the polished granite walls of the Vietnam Memorial,'' Bush said.
   He called drunken driving ``one of the most deadly scourges ever
to strike modern times. And it's as crippling as crack, as random
as gang violence. And it's killing more kids than both combined.''
   To those who have crusaded against drunken driving, Bush said,
``speaking not only as president, but as a father and as a
grandfather, you have my respect, my admiration and my thanks.''
   On Capitol Hill, meanwhile, a Kentucky senator urged motorists
to turn on their headlights for three hours on the last day of
December to remind other drivers not to drink and drive on New
Year's Eve.
   ``And it will be a memorial to all those victims of drunk
driving who will not be with us to celebrate the dawn of the new
decade,'' Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said at a news conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
