<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--GrainDeath     12-11 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Grain Death,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stored Corn Spills, Suffocates Worker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELKTON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grain bin filled to capacity with shelled
corn partially collapsed Monday morning, suffocating a man and
injuring two others, the Huron County Sheriff's Department said.
   Patrick W. Dufty, 34, of Caseville was pronounced dead at Huron
Memorial Hospital in Bad Axe following the 8 a.m. accident at the
Elkton branch of the Pigeon Cooperative Elevator in Michigan's
Thumb region, the department said.
   Dufty, a trucking company employee, and two other men were
inside the bin, preparing to transfer its 650,000 bushels of corn
to silos along railroad tracks 500 feet away, Deputy Elwood Smith
said.
   An inside support bracket broke loose and hundreds of bushels of
corn spilled out, burying Dufty for nearly an hour, Smith said.
   The other men were partially buried but escaped and were treated
and discharged from Huron Memorial Hospital, the deputy said.
   The sheriff's department and the state Occupational Safety and
Health Administration were investigating the incident, Smith said.
