<DOCNO> AP891211-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     12-11 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nighttime Explosions Kill Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two explosions seven minutes
apart rocked downtown Johannesburg, killing two people and damaging
the main train station, police said early Tuesday.
   The first blast at 11:30 p.m. Monday killed two men believed to
be Indians, said police spokesman Col. Hennie Heymans. He said
police suspected a limpet mine was used. The second blast was heard
throughout downtown but police could not determine the location
after searching for more than an hour.
   No one claimed responsibility and Heymans declined to speculate
on who may have been involved.
   More than 100 bombings have hit South Africa since a state of
emergency was declared in June 1986. Most were blamed on the
outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement, which is
based in Lusaka, Zambia, and is fighting to undermine white
domination.
   About 16,000 transportation workers have been on strike since
Nov. 2. Management has blamed them for arson and sabotage attacks
that have caused more than $8 million in property damage.
   Earlier, police said 16 blacks were killed Sunday and 65 homes
destroyed in factional fighting in Natal Province. About 2,000
people have died since late 1986 in battles among blacks there.
   Fire and hospital officials said four blacks were killed, eight
injured and more than 100 homes were razed on Sunday in arson
attacks related to a power struggle in the Crossroads shantytown
outside Cape Town.
   In Cape Town on Monday, Supreme Court Justice D.M. Williamson
acquitted an army officer and 12 policemen of murder in the case of
a boy shot dead in 1985 by officers hidden in crates on an unmarked
truck. It was the first murder trial held under a law allowing
private citizens to press prosecution in certain cases in which the
government declines to do so.
   Williamson said the officers did not act with premeditation in
the 1985 shooting death of Shaun Magoed, 16.
   The white officers concealed themselves in what looked like an
ordinary delivery truck that was driven into a mixed-raced township
near Cape Town during anti-apartheid unrest.
   Magoed and two other youths were killed after they threw stones
at the truck in a case that became known as the ``Trojan Horse
incident.''
   Williamson advised police to stop such operations, saying they
could endanger innocent people.
   Magoed's father pursued the case on his own after the Cape
Province attorney general declined to prosecute.
</TEXT>
