<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany 2ndLd-Writethru a0654 12-11 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0654,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rallies in Leipzig and Elsewhere Split on Reunification</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to include other rallies, detail; picks
up 8th `Calls for'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150,000 people rallied
for democracy in this southern industrial city Monday night, with
shouting matches breaking out for a fourth straight week over
whether Germany should reunite.
   ``We in Leipzig and those in Hanover (West Germany) are and will
remain Germans,'' one speaker said, to roared approval from some
and boos from others. ``What belongs together will grow together.''
   ADN, the official news agency, said 40,000 people demonstrated
at Karl-Marx-Stadt for a referendum on reunification before
elections planned in May. It said the crowd also demanded that
cells of the discredited Communist Party be disbanded by Dec. 15.
   Other rallies took place in Dresden, Neubrandenburg, Halle and
Potsdam, the agency reported. It said the Dresden crowd also
divided on the reunification issue.
   It was the fourth week German unity was a central issue of
Leipzig's regular Monday night rally.
   Dozens of West German flags waved in the crowd. Some
demonstrators carried signs saying ``No Fourth Reich'' and urging
East Germans not to let their country become a West German
``plantation.''
   ``There are two real movements now,'' said a young woman opposed
to reunification. ``It's too bad it's come to this.''
   In West Germany, ZDF television said: ``The fear of a deep
division within the opposition is huge, because of the different
goals.''
   Throughout the evening, protesters on both sides shouted at each
other.
   Reunification has become an increasingly bitter topic for East
Germany's New Forum opposition group, which sponsors the Leipzig
rallies. New Forum says reunification would mean a ``sellout'' to
West Germany.
   Calls for and against German unity were not the only demands.
Many demonstrators warned fellow East Germans against ``attacks and
taking law into their own hands.''
   As they press their beleaguered government to carry through with
promises of reforms, East Germans have increasingly been swept up
in a frenzy to root out corruption, leading to many warnings
against the use of violence.
   Monday night's protest was sponsored by the 200,000-member New
Forum, the nation's largest opposition group. The organization said
Monday it will take part as a political party in the nation's first
free election, slated for May 6, and will hope to form its own
parliamentary group.
   A national congress of New Forum to launch the group as a party
will be held in Leipzig on Jan. 6-7.
   Another opposition group, Demokratischer Aufbruch, which means
democratic ``start'' or ``awakening,'' called on the government to
pass immediate regulations allowing foreign companies to transfer
their profits out of the country and that would guarantee
protection of investments.
   Earlier Monday, the official East German news agency ADN said
new Communist Party chief Gregor Gysi spoke by telephone with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and that the two men had
agreed to meet soon.
   Gorbachev praised the party's ``rejection of attempts to damage
the sovereignty of the country,'' ADN said.
   The questions of East German sovereignty have become
increasingly important with the growing turmoil in the Communist
nation. There have been predictions the rapid changes could lead to
steps toward unification with West Germany.
   Gorbachev said the Soviet Union is watching the East German
situation with ``extraordinary attention'' and promised Moscow
would consider providing support ``within the current framework of
conditions.''
   Gysi said he is counting on Soviet backing in rebuilding the
Communist Party and enacting democratic reform, ADN said.
   ADN did not specify a date for their meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
