<FIRST>r a AM-DesegregationRuling     12-11 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Desegregation Ruling,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Desegregation Settlement, Blasts School Districts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON FOURNIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Monday approved the
$130 million settlement of the largest desegregation case in
Arkansas history, but blasted school districts for suggesting the
money be used to retire debts.
   U.S. District Judge Henry Woods, saying it was ``abundantly
clear'' the parties in the case could not be trusted with the
money, ordered it put in an escrow account monitored by a
court-appointed supervisor.
   ``The amount of money is meager enough,'' Woods wrote in his
opinion.
   The judge also scaled back NACCP attorneys' fees in the case
from $3.15 million to $850,000.
   The settlement ends seven years of litigation involving the
state, three school districts in Pulaski County, which includes
Little Rock, and black students' parents.
   The Little Rock School District, which is mostly black, sued the
state and the neighboring, mostly white North Little Rock and
Pulaski County districts, alleging the defendants caused illegal
segregation in Little Rock schools.
   The settlement was reached in March. In a special session in
July, the state Legislature agreed to spend $129.75 million over 10
years for desegregation programs.
   Woods on Monday endorsed the agreement as approved Oct. 4 by
Special Master Aubrey McCutcheon.
   Attorneys for the county and North Little Rock districts had
objected to revisions recommended by McCutcheon, saying the court
should accept the settlement intact.
   McCutcheon recommended that the court have the right to order
the construction or repair of magnet schools and that court forbid
the districts from spending settlement money to retire deficits
unrelated to desegregation.
   Woods said Monday that the districts had no right to challenge
the court's jurisdiction because they'd failed to draft a
constitutional student assignment plan.
   ``That the districts would default in their responsibilities,
then attempt to bind this court by `bargaining' with each other as
to what remedies the court-appointed expert could or could not use,
is incredible,'' he said. ``The parties have bound themselves.
There is a settlement.''
   Woods said his major objection was the North Little Rock and the
Pulaski districts' suggestion that the money could be used to pay
off debts.
   Woods, however, ruled that the Little Rock district had $5.5
million in debts attributed to desegregation that could be paid
with settlement money and that the Pulaski County district had $1.4
million in such debts.
   The judge refused to grant $2.3 million in attorneys' fees the
settlement assigned to the Legal Defense Fund of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   He said the Little Rock district shouldn't pay $2 million to the
defense fund because the district played the leading role in
pressing the lawsuit, no substantial documents or time records were
filed to support the claims, and the defense fund tried to recoup
fees going back to 1957.
   In 1957, then-Gov. Orval Faubus refused to allow nine black
students to enter Little Rock's all-white Central High School.
President Eisenhower ordered federal troops to Central High to keep
the peace and enforce court-ordered desegregation.
</TEXT>
