<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     12-11 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Croatia Joins Slovenia in Asking that Yugoslavia Go Multiparty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Croatia, the second largest state in
Yugoslavia, for the first time demanded Monday that a multiparty
political system be set up in this communist country.
   Until now, the liberal northern state of Slovenia had been the
only one of Yugoslavia's six constituent republics to openly
advocate introduction of Western-style democracy.
   The Communist leadership of Serbia, the most populous state with
42 percent of Yugoslavia's 23 million people, vigorously opposes
the change. Croatia has about 20 percent of the population.
   The State Department said in Washington on Monday that it was
worried by rising tensions in Yugoslavia and urged the people to
unite in support of the reform efforts of Prime Minister Ante
Markovic.
   Stanko Stojicevic, head of the Croatian Communist Party's ruling
presidium (Politburo), said Monday that Communists have been slow
in realizing the ``historic exhaustion of the single-party system.''
   In a keynote speech opening a regional party congress in the
Croatian capital of Zagreb, Stojicevic said, ``There can be no
democratic socialism without political pluralism based on the right
of association and competition of political (movements) and
programs.''
   The speech was carried by the state news agency Tanjug.
   About a dozen independent movements and parties have been set up
in Slovenia the past year, and the region plans to hold its first
free legislative elections next March.
   About 25,000 Croatians in several cities signed a petition
Sunday urging legalization of numerous parties that would make it
possible to hold free elections in the Croatian republic, which
borders Slovenia.
   In an apparent move to stifle growing democratic trends in
Yugoslavia, Serbia this month cut all business and official ties
with Slovenia. The action shook the foundations of Yugoslavia's
loose federal system.
   Stojicevic denounced Serbia's break with Slovenia, describing
the consequences as ``dramatic with a possibly catastrophic
outcome.''
   He said, ``Ultimatums and the severance of economic relations,
accusations and threats represent a direct attack on the
constitutional order of the country and its economic and political
integrity.''
   Slovenian President Janez Stanovnik told the region's parliament
on Monday that Serbia's move dealt a ``heavy blow to the Yugoslav
federation'' and was meant to ``eliminate all those who hold
differing opinions and to produce a change of the constitutional
order.'
   At a session devoted exclusively to the break, Stanovnik told
deputies, ``The blockade of Slovenia, therefore, represents an act
of aggression against Yugoslavia.''
   In Washington, State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher
said when when asked about ethnic problems in Yugoslavia:
   ``We are greatly concerned by the growing tensions and conflicts
among the republics and national groups that make up Yugoslavia.
Mutual respect, adherence to democratic principles, and a
commitment to avoiding violence are crucial to resolving this
situation.
   ``The U.S. supports and will continue to support a united
federal Yugoslavia in which human rights and civil rights of all
citizens are protected.
   ``The U.S. strongly supports the ongoing efforts of ... Prime
Minister Markovich to create a market-based economy and to promote
greater political pluralism. We urge all Yugoslavs to put aside
their differences and to focus their energies on this important
reform effort.''
</TEXT>
