<DOCNO> AP891211-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NavalChase     12-11 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Naval Chase,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Naval Destroyer Pursues U.S. Scalloper For Alleged Illegal
Fishing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian naval destroyer Monday fired a shot
across the bow of an American scalloper that allegedly rammed it
three times, Coast Guard officials said.
   The 366-foot destroyer Sagueny fired a 3-inch round at 6:52 p.m.
near George's Bank after chasing the 114-foot scalloper Concordia
for eight hours, said Petty Officer Ellen Harrington.
   The Concordia did not stop or attempt to make radio contact
after the warning shot was fired, said Harrington. She said the
vessel continued to steam west towards Cape Cod and its home port
of Fairhaven.
   The Sagueny followed it until 8:50 p.m., when it entered U.S.
waters.
   The scalloper was allegedly spotted fishing 2.5 miles across the
Hague fisheries line by a Canadian aircraft, said Harrington.
   The Hague line divides U.S. and Canadian waters was established
by the World Court in 1984. There have been several reports this
year of American fishing boats crossing the line to the rich
fishing area on the Canadian side.
   Lt. Doug Maybee, a Canadian Forces spokesman, said the Sagueny
began tracking the Concordia after it was spotted fishing in
Canadian waters on five occasions during the weekend.
   The smaller boat allegedly disregarded radio messages before it
``eventually turned toward Sagueny and stuck the right rear quarter
three times,'' Maybee said. No injuries or serious damage were
reported.
   ``Options are being weighed by the political masters in Ottawa
as to what the next step should be,'' he said. ``It is
all-important that a knee-jerk reaction be avoided.''
   The Coast Guard was expected to board the craft when it reached
U.S. waters, Harrington said. ``We will document the vessel's
catch, check charts and records, and varify the identities of the
master and crew,'' she said.
   Harrington said the Concordia will be allowed to proceed to its
home port after the boarding was completed, and any further action
would have to be initiated by the Canadian government.
   Maybee declined to detail what kind of punitive action could be
taken in the alleged ramming about 130 miles off Cape Cod.
   Harrington said the Coast Guard had no plans to intervene,
adding, ``Canadian ships don't usually pursue the American fishing
fleet inside American waters unless they get permission from
diplomatic channels.''
   ``The Coast Guard has been monitoring the situation, abiding its
policy of not interfering with Canadian law enforcement.''
</TEXT>
