<FIRST>u i AM-Quayle-Zionism     12-11 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Zionism,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Asks Repeal of `Odious' U.N. Resolution on Zionism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle said Monday the
United Nations should repeal its ``odious'' 1975 resolution that
equates Zionism with racism in an effort to promote the Middle East
peace process.
   He also gave Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar a check
for $65 million in partial payment of major U.S. arrears, an issue
that has stirred anti-U.S. sentiment here. U.N. officials said the
United States now owes $365 million for the regular budget and $153
million for peacekeeping.
   ``Repealing this resolution would re-establish the stature and
moral authority of the U.N.,'' Quayle told reporters after a
50-minute meeting with the U.N. chief.
   ``Now is the time to begin discussion on substituting or getting
rid of this odious resolution which equates Zionism with racism.''
   Quayle's comments came in answer to questions.
   The resolution is symbolic and not binding, but has been a sore
point with the United States and its ally, Israel. U.S. and Israeli
diplomats said that killing the resolution, or declaring it null
and void, could enhance the Middle East peace process by removing
an Israeli objection to U.N. involvement.
   The General Assembly resolution was backed by Israel's Arab
rivals, the Soviet Union and much of the movement professing
non-alignment with either superpower. Quayle said it ``should be
declared null and void.''
   Francois Giuliani, spokesman for the secretary-general, later
said the U.N. chief had no comment. ``It is up to the member states
and General Assembly to decide,'' he told reporters at a daily
briefing.
   He said no resolution has ever been rescinded or repealed, but
that the 159-nation General Assembly ``can innovate if it wishes to
do so.''
   Resolutions are part of the permanent record and cannot be
repealed or erased, U.N. diplomats said. However, substitute
resolutions can be presented and previous resolutions, by a
majority vote, can be declared void and no longer representative of
the majority's sentiments.
   Quayle said the Soviet Union and other countries ``can be very
helpful'' in the matter of repeal. The Soviet Union changed its
traditional vote this year and for the first time supported
accepting Israel's credentials in the General Assembly.
   Quayle was asked how repeal would promote Palestinian rights. He
said that renouncing the resolution would help human rights in the
occupied territories and send a positive signal about the Middle
East peace process.
   Quayle told reporters he had ``a very good and candid
discussion'' with the U.N. chief on a number of issues, including
the U.S.-Soviet summit in Malta, allegations of Cuban violations of
human rights, forthcoming Nicaraguan elections and the Central
American peace process.
   He said he briefed Perez de Cuellar on the Malta meeting. He
said he told him ``Cuba is becoming more isolated.'' He said Cuban
President Fidel Castro's criticism of perestroika, or reform, in
the Soviet Union ``is an indirect criticism of Soviet President
(Mikhail) Gorbachev.''
   The United States last week suffered a setback on Middle East
issues after it threatened to cut off all funding to the United
Nations if the world body upgraded the status of the Palestine
Liberation Organization as an observer state, instead of an
observer group.
   The issue was defused and the question was put off, but
anti-U.S. sentiment remains. The General Assembly later adopted a
package of pro-PLO, anti-Israel resolutions _ an annual event.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
