<TEXT>
   A women's basketball player who tutors
Cambodian refugees and a woman who worked in a Brazilian orphanage
were among 32 Americans to join the ranks of Rhodes Scholars.
   The 18 men and 14 women selected Sunday receive two years of
study at Oxford University in England.
   Yale and Princeton universities led with four each, Harvard had
three, and Georgetown, Kansas State University and the U.S.
Military Academy at West Point, N.Y., each had two.
   The winners were chosen from among 102 finalists interviewed
last week by the Rhodes Scholarship Trust, whose American branch is
based at Pomona College in suburban Claremont.
