<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-KennyRogers Adv12   12-11 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Kenny Rogers, Adv 12,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, Dec. 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kenny Rogers and His Son Star in Christmas Special</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1 of Dec.9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although ``Christmas in America: A Love
Story'' reflects parts of Kenny Rogers' own life it was written
before he was signed to star in the NBC special.
   The one-hour show on Wednesday tells the story of an
internationally famous photographer who reflects on his life and
uses the opportunity to heal the wounds between himself and his
son. The son felt his father had always put his career ahead of his
family.
   Rogers, although best known as a singer and actor, is also an
acclaimed photographer and recently patched up relations with his
own son, Kenny Rogers Jr., who co-stars in the special as the son.
Kate Reid and Ashley Crow are also in the show.
   ``We sent him the script to read,'' said Earl Hamner, who
co-wrote the show with Donald Sipes. ``I was delighted when I
learned he was not only a photographer but a good photographer.
Kenny felt he had neglected his own son and had an estrangement.''
   Sipes said, ``I think the feeling of the film is one of healing
and coming together, which was reflected in Kenny's own
relationship with his son.''
   When the project got under way Hamner and Sipes were asked to
come up with a story about four periods in a man's life.
   ``Don and I came up with the idea of making him a
photographer,'' said Hamner. ``That way we could use photos to
introduce each period. The first period is childhood, when he
becomes interested in photography. The next is young manhood, when
he goes off to war and falls in love. Act three is his marriage and
family and the development of his career and the conflicts it
causes in his personal life.
   ``The last act is about maturity and reconciliation. It's about
regeneration, which is so appropriate for this time of year. An
area Don and I wanted to explore is something that is common to all
of us in this society. That's the work ethic and how it can cause a
man to neglect his family.''
   Hamner said he also felt at ease with Rogers when he learned
that he's a fisherman. Hamner fished the streams of his native
Virginia for many years before discovering salmon fishing.
   ``I fish in British Columbia now,'' he said. ``I caught a
50-pound fish up there last year. That's a lifetime fish. They
canned it for me and the cans arrived just yesterday.''
   This is the first collaboration between Hamner, best known for
creating ``The Waltons'' and ``Falcon Crest,'' and Sipes, a former
entertainment executive and a published novelist.
   ``We've known each other a long time,'' said Sipes. ``We always
discussed writing because we both write. We both collect books and
when we meet for lunch we arrange it near a book store. After lunch
we'll go and browse for a while. I collect literature and Earl
collects Americana.''
   Hamner said, ``My dream is to find a rare book and buy it for
$7.50. But the book store people all know the value of these
books.''
   Their next collaboration will be ``Brewster Place,'' a half-hour
drama for ABC starring Oprah Winfrey. It will be filmed in Chicago,
where her talk show is based, and will make its debut in April.
They are also working on several cable television projects and
wrote a pilot last year for NBC.
   ``Brewster Place'' is adapted from the book ``The Women of
Brewster Place'' and the miniseries that ran on ABC. Hamner and
Sipes are making some changes in the concept because the miniseries
presented such a negative image of black men.
   ``We'll have much more positive images,'' said Sipes. ``We're
adding some new characters. Oprah will play her character in her
late 40s. She'll have to be aged and padded for the part.''
   Hamner said he feels the television audience wants the kind of
family programming represented by ``Christmas in America.''
   ``The networks want people between 18 and 49,'' he said. ``You
cut out a lot of people that way. Suppose you do a `once upon a
time' story. You can attract the 18-49 audience and everyone else,
too.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   `PINK PANTHER' _ Oscar-winning composer Henry Mancini will score
the music for the new CBS series ``The Pink Panther'' that combines
live action and animation. Mancini received an Academy Award
nomination for composing the music for the first ``Pink Panther''
movie 26 years ago. The series, from MGM-UA Television, stars
Charlie Schlatter, Lisa Waltz, Dabbs Greer, Tim Stack and Karen
Austin.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tuesday PMs, Dec. 12</NOTE>
