<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Moslems-Rushdie Adv18   12-11 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Moslems-Rushdie, Adv 18,0890</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, Dec. 18 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Britain's Moslems Split over Response to `The Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Moslem leaders in Britain agree Salman Rushdie
blasphemed their religion in his book, ``The Satanic Verses,'' but
they differ sharply on what to do about it.
   One noted Moslem figure, Hesham El-Essawy, said he wanted to go
to Iran and win a reprieve for the author, but after a Tehran
newspaper said ``the hanging rope'' awaited him, he stayed in
England.
   A prominent Moslem, Kalim Siddiqui, supports the death sentence
imposed on Rushdie by the late Iranian leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, and thinks Rushdie should be hounded perpetually until
his book, published 14 months ago, is withdrawn from bookshelves.
   Rushdie, a Bombay-born Moslem, has been in hiding under police
guard since Feb. 14. Khomeini died in Iran on June 3, but his edict
endures.
   Siddiqui, director of the Moslem Institute, says Khomeini's
edict is unchallengeable and that Rushdie got ``nothing less than
he thoroughly deserved.''
   But while favoring the death decree ``absolutely,'' he says it
is ``not for Moslems living in this country to break British law to
bring Rushdie to book.''
   El-Essawy, chairman of the Islamic Society for the Promotion of
Religious Tolerance, contends that the death sentence contradicts
the Koran's teachings.
   ``As a Moslem, I should really suppress the human response and
adopt the religious response, which is, `Don't punish him; leave
him to God to punish or forgive him as He wishes,''' El-Essawy said
in an interview.
   He planned a lecture tour of Iran, Egypt and the Persian Gulf
states in February to dispute Khomeini's edict but canceled it when
Iran declined to guarantee his safety and its semi-official
newspaper, Kehan, warned he would be hanged.
   ``The death sentence is really a slur, is something that defames
the religion of Islam,'' El-Essawy maintained.
   ``As long as the man stays in hiding, we'll stand accused of
putting him there and keeping him there. We'll be regarded as
potential killers.''
   El-Essawy said he hoped at least to remove the $5.2-million
bounty offered by Iranian clerics for Rushdie's assassination, by
designating it ``the tactics of gangsters and not worthy of the
Islamic republic.''
   El-Essawy and Siddiqui have never met. El-Essawy's group seeks
to identify and correct causes of intolerance toward Moslems.
Siddiqui's disseminates information on Moslem political thought.
   Siddiqui, came to Britain from Pakistan in 1954; El-Essawy came
from Egypt in 1970. Both are married with three children and both
are thoroughly Westernized in appearance. They share an easy humor
and a mutual contempt.
   In a book-lined study at his house in suburban London, Siddiqui,
58, dismissed El-Essawy as an apologist.
   ``Totally idiotic the man is, to put it mildly,'' he said.
   El-Essawy, 43, seated in his ornamented dentist's office in
Harley St., London's medical row, said Siddiqui's speeches verge on
``incitement to murder, but don't let me be the judge.''
   In October, at a Moslem rally in northern England, Siddiqui
called for a show of hands on whether the death sentence was just
and virtually all 250 people in the audience were reported to have
raised their hands. A BBC-TV poll published the previous night
indicated only 35 percent of Britain's 2 million Moslems were in
favor of the death penalty.
   Police are investigating whether Siddiqui was guilty of
incitement and have obtained a court order forcing the BBC to hand
over its footage of the rally.
   Siddiqui complains the British media portray him ``as a sort of
rabble rouser _ the opposite to Salman Rushdie, as it were.''
   He says Moslems have no choice but to protest and show that
``anyone who tries to go down the same road as Mr. Rushdie in the
future will be dealt with much more severely.''
   Siddiqui wants Rushdie and his publishers, Viking Penguin, to
withdraw the book and that profits from the 1.2 million copies sold
should be shared among relatives of 26 people who died in
anti-Rushdie riots in India and Pakistan.
   ``They should make amends, and then we'll call it a day,''
Siddiqui said. Otherwise, ``this is going to be an issue in 50
years from now.''
   El-Essawy said: ``There is not one single Moslem who is not
angered by the book.'' But he thinks Rushdie might defuse the furor
by affixing labels to his book making clear the contents are
fictional.
   He said he met Rushdie on a train two weeks before the author
was driven into hiding and suggested the disclaimer label, but
Rushdie rejected it as tantamount to ``an apology.''
   Rushdie is ``not showing any good will at all,'' El-Essawy
added. ``In fact, he's doing the opposite _ he's trying to promote
the campaign against him ... because he wants to sell more books.''
   Rushdie, 42, continues to write, and occasionally aims barbed
comments at his opponents.
   In a book review he wrote recently for The Times Literary
Supplement, he alluded to the public burning of his book by Moslems
with this thought: ``To burn a book is not to destroy it. One
minute of darkness will not make us blind.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday PMs, Dec. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0748EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-SouthAfrica-Schools Adv19   12-11 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Schools, Adv 19,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs, Dec. 19 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>State-run Schools Still Off-limits to South African Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DAVID CRARY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the government pursues
racial reform on several other fronts, rigid apartheid remains the
rule at state-run schools, despite a growing clamor for change.
   For millions of black children, schools are overcrowded or
unavailable. Scores of white schools have closed because of pupil
shortages. Yet the government recently rebuffed a coalition of
white parents, teachers and students who petitioned to establish
South Africa's first multiracial public school.
   ``Amid all his encouraging moves ... President de Klerk has just
failed an acid test,'' said The Star, the country's largest daily
newspaper. ``No matter how compelling the reasons to amend that
archaic policy, no matter how desperate the pleas from those
affected, apartheid remains alive and kicking in the school
system.''
   Since taking office in mid-August, President F.W. de Klerk
repeatedly has vowed to eliminate racial discrimination. Yet his
support for segregated state schools is unwavering despite official
figures indicating that the government spends nearly five times as
much to educate a white pupil as a black one.
   According to the minister in charge of white education, Piet
Clase, school segregation is essential to ensure ``cultural and
linguistic continuity'' between the home and the classroom.''
   The ``acid test'' referred to by The Star was the fate of
Johannesburg Girls High School, a 102-year-old institution the
government targeted for closure because of declining enrollment.
   A substantial majority of the teachers, students and parents
launched an unprecedented campaign to save the whites-only school
by opening it to children of the thousands of black, mixed-race and
Indian families who have moved into the inner-city neighborhood in
defiance of residential segregation laws.
   After hinting that it might allow a experimental multiracial
public school, the government decided instead on a compromise. It
would allow the high school to remain in operation, but only as a
private school.
   The state will provide a subsidy of up to 45 percent of its
operating costs, but even so, few of the current pupils are
expected to able to afford the projected monthly fees of 100 rand
($38).
   The school also is expected to lose two of its five grades
because of financial constraints and will be able to cater to no
more than 240 pupils, although the facility has a capacity of
nearly 700.
   ``The creation of a private school is no victory as far as I am
concerned,'' said Neil McGurk, a member of a provisional board of
trustees for the new school. ``The new school will have nothing to
do with the old.''
   McGurk, the principal of a multiracial Roman Catholic school,
said the government tends to lower its subsidies to private schools
with relatively high proportions of black pupils.
   ``The state has a natural temptation to mobilize as much
resources as possible for whites,'' he said.
   The government currently spends the equivalent of about $800 a
year to educate a white child, compared to less than $200 per black
child. This gap has been reduced from previous years, but the
government recently abandoned a 10-year plan to equalize the
per-capita education spending.
   In Soweto, the largest black township with an estimated 2.5
million residents, schools have been plagued by violence, severe
overcrowding, shortages of textbooks, poor performances on exams
and deteriorating facilities.
   In many Soweto schools, there are 40 to 50 pupils for each
teacher.
   The South African Institute of Race Relations reported in
November that 196 white schools have been closed in the past 10
years, and that remaining white schools have more than 250,000
vacant places. An estimated 1 million black children have no
schools to go to, the institute said.
   A handful of the closed-down white schools have been made
available to the education departments for Indians and mixed-race
people, but most have been leased to other government agencies and
42 are unused, said the institute, an independent research
organization.
   ``Given the crying need for school places for black pupils, this
is a criminal waste of a high order,'' said a recent editorial in
The Star.
   The campaign to integrate Johannesburg Girls High School has
been emulated in other cities, under the banner of a group called
All Schools for All People.
   Ahmed Moonda, a leader of the group, said that if the state does
not act, a defiance campaign will be launched next year in which
parents will take their children to the nearest school and demand
enrollment.
   ``We do not want to cause disruptions, but we may be forced
to,'' he said. ``The state is simply fostering illiteracy among our
kids.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tuesday PMs, Dec. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
