<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears ADV12   12-11 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV12,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues Dec 12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Politicians Plot Greater Safety in Numbers on Risky Votes</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a political system that is supposed to
thrive on competition, there's something odd happening. Politicians
are starting to suggest the only way to deal with really tough
issues is under a cease-fire, a truce in which they would agree to
put unpopular votes out of campaign bounds.
   One Republican leader called it a ``suicide pact,'' and said
that may be what it takes to get action to rein some politically
sacrosanct spending programs _ Social Security and veterans
benefits were two he mentioned.
   The political parties already have put one such deal into
effect, agreeing that Republicans and Democrats will speak no
campaign evil of each other for supporting the two-step pay raise
the House voted itself just before adjourning.
   House leaders of both parties insisted on that pledge before the
vote on salaries and a 1991 ban on honoraria, finding at last a way
around the political perils that have gone with raises in
congressional pay for 200 years.
   So the chairmen of the national and congressional campaign
committees agreed the pay vote ``is not an appropriate point of
criticism in the coming campaigns.'' That will be fine with House
memers who voted for the raise; dissenters and challengers who try
to make it an issue will risk losing the financial and technical
support they could otherwise expect from the national campaign
committees.
   With that deal cut, other topics may start to look inviting as
prospects for non-aggression pacts.
   That idea and some variations on the theme came up last week at
a forum on Congress in the 1990s, sponsored by the American
Enterprise Institute.
   In theory, the American political system and Congress itself
should work best with ideas, issues, candidates and officeholders
competing in contests that produce winners, force compromise and
ultimately shape consensus.
   Former President Gerald Ford argued that side of the case at the
AEI forum, saying it can work between the branches as well as
between the parties. ``A little conflict can bring out the best,''
said Ford, a former House Republican leader who went to the White
House and vetoed bills at a record pace, 67 of them in 2{ years.
``I'm not sure that confrontation between the White House and the
Congress is necessarily bad.''
   As for political competition, Ford said if he had the power to
draw congressional district lines, each of them would be as closely
divided as possible, with party registration split no more widely
than 60 percent to 40 percent for the minority.
   But Rep. Steny Hoyer of Maryland, chairman of the Democratic
conference, said congressmen from closely divided districts are the
most skittish on controversial votes. He said members with
politically safe districts may be in better shape to make the
correct but unpopular decisions that sometimes come to a member of
Congress.
   Tony Coelho, the former Democratic whip who quit the House
earlier this year, said professional, aggressive congressional
campaign committees in both parties tend to make members nervous
about becoming a target over a potentially unpopular vote.
   ``It's very organized, very controlled,'' Coelho said. ``I was
part of it, I recognize it.''
   Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming, the Senate Republican whip, said
that's why members of Congress back away from such risky positions
as limiting Social Security benefit increases in order to chip away
at the federal deficit. Republicans tried in 1982 and got creamed,
he said.
   ``Who the hell is going to do the heavy lifting?'' he said.
   All sides acknowledge it will take unpopular votes to make real
reductions in the federal deficit.
   ``Nobody gets elected saying no,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
``You get elected saying yes.''
   It was Simpson who suggested that a political truce might be a
way to get things done, by taking the sting and risk out of votes
to cut votes to cut popular spending programs. ``We ought to sit
down and do the suicide pact,'' he said, agreeing members in both
parties will ``go over the cliff together'' and won't try to punish
each other later.
   ``It doesn't take courage if we all do it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tues Dec 12 and Thereafter</NOTE>
