<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, Dec. 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, December 21, the 355th day of 1989. There are
ten days left in the year. Winter arrives at 4:22 p.m. Eastern
Standard Time.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On December 21, 1914, 75 years ago, the first feature-length
silent film comedy, ``Tillie's Punctured Romance,'' was released.
The movie starred Marie Dressler, Mabel Normand, Charlie Chaplin
and Mack Swain, and was directed by Mack Sennett.
   On this date:
   In 1620, the Pilgrims aboard the Mayflower went ashore for the
first time at what is now Plymouth, Mass.
   In 1898, scientists Pierre and Marie Curie discovered radium.
   In 1913, the first crossword puzzle was published, in the Sunday
supplement of the New York World.
   In 1940, author F. Scott Fitzgerald died in Hollywood at the age
of 44.
   In 1945, Gen. George S. Patton died of injuries he suffered in a
car accident in Heidelberg, Germany.
   In 1948, the state of Eire (formerly the Irish Free State)
declared its independence.
   In 1958, Charles De Gaulle was elected to a seven-year term as
the first president of the Fifth Republic of France.
   In 1968, Apollo 8 was launched from Cape Kennedy on its way to
humankind's first orbit of the moon.
   In 1969, 20 years ago, Vince Lombardi coached his last football
game as his team, the Washington Redskins, lost to the Dallas
Cowboys, 20-10.
   In 1971, the U.N. Security Council chose Kurt Waldheim as
secretary-general, succeeding U Thant.
   In 1976, the Liberian-registered tanker Argo Merchant ran
aground near Nantucket Island, spilling millions of gallons of oil
into the North Atlantic.
   In 1978, police in Des Plaines, Ill., arrested John W. Gacy
Junior and began unearthing the remains of 33 men and boys that
Gacy was later convicted of murdering.
   Ten years ago: Black Rhodesian leaders signed a peace agreement
aimed at ending seven years of guerrilla warfare and paving the way
to the creation of the independent state of Zimbabwe.
   Five years ago: Soviet Deputy Premier Ivan V. Arkhipov arrived
in Beijing, becoming the highest-ranking representative of his
government to visit China in 15 years.
   One year ago: 270 people were killed when a bomb exploded aboard
a Pam Am Boeing 747 over Lockerbie, Scotland, sending wreckage
crashing to the ground.
   Today's Birthdays: Former undersecretary of state George W. Ball
is 80. The president of Austria, Kurt Waldheim, is 71.
Ventriloquist Paul Winchell is 67. Actor Ed Nelson is 61. Talk show
host Phil Donahue is 54. Actress Jane Fonda is 52. Rock
composer-singer Frank Zappa is 49. Tennis star Chris Evert is 35.
Olympic gold medalist Florence Griffith Joyner is 30.
   Thought for Today: ``I don't want to live _ I want to love
first, and live incidentally.'' _ Zelda Sayre Fitzgerald, American
author (1900-1948).
</TEXT>
