<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Japan-IslandAirport Adv18   12-11 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Island Airport, Adv 18,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Dec. 18, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Airport on Island Not Seen as Solution to Travelers' Woes in Japan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSAKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While foreign businessmen complain of
obstacles to Japanese markets, travelers complain that crowded
airports are the most frustrating barriers to getting into the
country.
   In hopes of easing the bottleneck for air travelers, the
Japanese are building an island in Osaka Bay and plan to put an
airport on it. But few industry insiders think it will be the
answer.
   The project is moving smoothly along, nevertheless, in contrast
to Tokyo's Narita airport, where riot police recently battled
radicals who used firebombs to defend land on which a runway was to
have been completed 15 years ago.
   At Narita, eight farmers still grow vegetables on and around the
planned second runway, refusing to sell their land. Though police
have begun to dismantle buildings erected by radicals supporting
the farmers, industry sources are doubtful the second runway will
be completed by the end its new deadline, two years from now.
   For more than 20 years, protests against Narita have left six
people dead. The airport is surrounded by barbed wire and riot
police. It is not connected to key rail lines to Tokyo, 40 miles
away.
   The $7 billion Kansai Airport at Osaka, however, will be out in
the bay and not likely to generate any fights with the city's
residents.
   The airport is one of the world's biggest civil engineering
projects of the 1990s, but it has its critics.
   Japan is famous for its bullet trains and sparkling subways, but
its links to the outside world _ international airports _ are
widely considered unworthy of a great economic power.
   The main link, Tokyo's Narita airport, ``is becoming a symbol of
Japan's closed nature,'' says Yasuo Sakakibara, an economics
professor.
   New Tokyo International Airport, as Narita is officially called,
greets passengers after long trans-Pacific flights with crowds and
confusion. After picking up their luggage, passengers get a choice
between a $200, 40-mile taxi ride to Tokyo or a wait of an hour or
more for a bus.
   Narita handled 4 million more passengers last year than it was
planned for, all squeezing through the same number of immigration
counters as when the airport opened in 1978.
   With just one runway, Narita handles 17 million passengers a
year. New York's John F. Kennedy airport, with five runways,
handles 10 million.
   ``The congestion is terrible,'' says Richard Jurek, director of
Pacific operations for Northwest Airlines. ``The day (Narita)
opened it had already reached its comfortable capacity.''
   The new Kansai airport, an hour's flight west of Tokyo, is
supposed to relieve the problem when it opens in 1993.
   But industry sources say the runway is too short, the distance
to Osaka too far, and its link highways too narrow. An airport
serving a metropolitan region that produces 2 percent of the
world's economic output needs at least three runways, they say, not
just one. Three were originally planned, and the Ministry of
Transport is still hoping for them, but the Ministry of Finance
says the country can afford only one.
   Industry sources predict Kansai airport will be full within a
year or two of its opening. They expect growth in Japan's
international passengers in the next few years to nearly match the
more than 20 percent annual growth since 1987.
   Today, boats cruise in Osaka Bay where 747s will take off.
Machines disgorge enough sand to fill scores of Houston Astrodomes
into a box 2.7 miles long that will be the airport's supposedly
earthquake-proof base. It is one of the deepest of man-made
islands, standing in 60 feet of water.
   On it will rise an ultra-modern terminal with people movers and
indoor landscaping. A two-level bridge will carry trains and cars
across 2.3 miles of water to Osaka's shore.
   Japan squeezes 122 million people _ half the population of the
United States _ into a habitable area about the size of
Pennsylvania; few of them want an airport in their backyard. That
keeps airports small and inconvenient to city centers. The island
airport will be an hour's bus ride from downtown Osaka.
   The sand used for the island is costing more than it should
because of price-fixing among contractors, who were stiffly fined
by Japan's antitrust agency. The United States has charged that
collusive business practices like the sand cartel keep out foreign
businesses; Washington has made access to the airport's
construction by U.S. companies a major trade issue with the
Japanese.
   After long negotiations, the airport opened bidding on
construction and supplies to foreign firms, and an Italian
architect won a design contest for the terminal building.
   Despite the prospect of problems ahead, foreign airlines are
lining up for flight slots at the new airport. For many airlines,
the Pacific and Japan are the fastest growing and most profitable
markets in the world.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Dec. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--LastInnocentXmas Adv24-1stAdd   12-11 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Last Innocent Xmas, Adv 24-1st Add,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: super cruisers.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One of the groups, composed of the cruiser Exeter with 8-inch
guns and the cruisers Ajax and Achilles with 6-inchers, found the
Graf Spee in the South Atlantic near Montevideo, Uruguay, where the
River Plate vents to the sea. Each of the hunter groups was
configured to deal with a pocket battleship, but this group lacked
another 8-inch cruiser, the Cumberland, which was refitting in the
Falklands.
   The Graf Spee had 11-inch guns with greater range and hitting
power than the British ships. Even with the Exeter steaming toward
her, the Spee had three minutes of unimpeded barrages before she
came into Exeter's range. The lighter cruisers were under even a
greater disadvantage.
   The Spee sought to stay at maximum range under the cover of
smoke, but it soon found itself beset from three directions. The
Exeter was hit and out of control when the light cruisers finally
came into play.
   The Graf Spee made for the River Plate under cover of smoke. The
Exeter, her bridge and forward guns gone, was being steered from
the emergency controls aft. The Ajax had lost its after turrets.
The entire engagement had taken an hour and 20 minutes. The British
ships pursued the Spee to Montevideo and lay to outside. They were
joined by the Cumberland two days after the initial action, evening
the odds.
   Capt. Langsdorff of the Graf Spee notified the German admiralty
of his plight and asked instructions. On the evening of Dec. 17, he
headed his ship out of the harbor and toward the waiting British
ships. Some two hours later she blew herself up. Two days later
Langsdorff shot himself.
   Churchill wrote: ``The effects of the action off the Plate gave
intense joy to the British nation and enhanced our prestige
throughout the world. The spectacle of the three smaller British
ships unhesitatingly attacking and putting to flight their far more
heavily gunned and armoured antagonist was everywhere admired.''
   Not everywhere. The Soviet naval publication, Red Fleet, called
it a demonstration of the impotence of the British.
   Meanwhile, the Soviets invaded Finland 25 days before Christmas,
but the Finns would not lie down and play dead. American moviegoers
that Christmas would see white-clad Finnish ski troops on their
newsreels.
   In London, Churchill pleaded for a softening of the blackout
regulations, which he saw as hurting the war effort and morale of
the populace.
   Military objectives, he said, could best be attacked by daylight
or moonlight. London could be found easily by simple directional
navigation. He suggested modified lighting that was employed in
Paris that allowed enough light to see 600 yards ahead and a margin
of safety for motorists.
   ``There is no need to have the `rosy glow' as a guide, and it
would not be a guide if it were extinguished before the raiders
leave the sea. But there is not much in it anyway ...
   ``The penalty we pay for the present methods is very heavy.
First, the loss of life. Secondly, as the secretary of state for
air has protested, the impediment to munitions output; and also
work at the ports ... Thirdly, the irritating and depressing effect
on the people, which is a drag upon their war-making capacity ...
Fourthly, the anxieties of women and young girls in the darkened
streets at night or on blacked-out trains. Fifthly, the effect on
shopping and entertainments.''
   He cited newspaper reports of a man who was prosecuted for
smoking a cigarette too brightly, and another of a mother who was
fined for turning on a light to care for her crying baby.
   Modifying to a dimout, he said, might help Britain make it
through the mist and fog of the three winter months with better
morale and greater safety.
   ``We can always revert to the existing practice if the war
flares up, or if we do anything to provoke reprisals.''
   The war would flare up.
   Before another war-free Christmas Day would dawn, some 50
million people would violently vanish from the face of the Earth.
</TEXT>
