<DOCNO> AP891211-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Reindeer Adv24-1stAdd   12-11 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Reindeer, Adv 24-1st Add,0879</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>STOCKHOLM: sometimes silver.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Like the sled driver in that poem, they do have ``cheeks like
roses'' and ``a nose like a cherry.'' You'd glow like that, too, if
you dashed out of a night 50 below into a sauna 220 above zero.
   Lapps or Laplanders, these rugged people are still widely called
in Sweden, but in Norway and Finland their official name is Sami.
They have their own language, of remote Hungarian and Finnish
origin, with 120 words for snow and 400 for reindeer.
   Why not? We reindeer are their whole life, culture and history.
Carbon tests on petrified slats found in tundra bogs show they have
been chasing us on cross-country skis since at least 2500 B.C.
   We are their horse, sheep, cow and general store, available in
one portable compact model.
   Tents, blankets, boots, parkas, leggings, sleeping bags are
taken out of our hide. The meat, strong and flavorful, can be
jerked, smoked, boiled or barbecued. Reindeer blood pancakes are an
acquired taste. Our milk is four times richer than a cow's, great
for butter and cheese.
   Bowls, spoons and fish hooks are fashioned from our antlers. Our
sinews contribute harnesses, boot laces, lassos and thread spun on
looms fashioned from our bones, which also provide knife handles,
pack racks and the baby's kemse or cradle, all held together with
glue from our hoofs.
   There really are reindeer games like you hear about in that
Rudolph song. With dice and markers made from our toe bones, the
herder's family gathers in the glow of the tent stove for a board
game called wolf tablo, a variant of chess in which the wolf
gobbles up some reindeer pawns until he finally is cornered.
   Reindeer aren't driven like cattle in the American West. We call
the tune. Instinct dictates where and when we'll mosey off to
richer pastures. The herder and his family just follow along,
listening for the jingle bells around our necks and the hollow
clicking noise the herd makes on the move. Tendons stretching
across our toe bones make a sound like of a bunch of schoolboys
cracking their knuckles.
   Before Norway established border controls in 1912, reindeer used
to roam from the top of the Gulf of Bothania, where Finland and
Sweden meet, all the way to the Atlantic.
   Herding has changed dramatically in recent years. Logging
operations in Finland, NATO bases in Norway and Sweden's
unquenchable appetite for hydroelectric power have shrunk our
traditional grazing ground.
   Many herders have forsaken the old nomadic ways. They use
planes, helicopters and walkie-talkie radios to follow our
migrations.
   In Rovaniemi, up on the Arctic Circle, a Finnish firm called
Rova Elektro is marketing ``reindeer radar'' to replace the bells
around our necks. Some herd handlers these days ride the frozen
range on snowmobiles. ``Tinplate geldings,'' the Sami call them.
   This brings up a delicate subject. A few weeks ago a militant
feminist on a TV talk show called Santa a male chauvinist because
only a token doe, Vixen, made his starting lineup on Christmas Eve.
   The awful truth is that all sled-pulling reindeer are ``harkar''
_ geldings. Castration is performed at the fall roundup, when the
huge herds that summered in the mountains are sorted out by family
ownership for breeding, slaughter or sled training.
   The other big reindeer roundup comes early in spring when the
young calves still following their mothers are literally earmarked
for owner identification.
   I'll never forget the last day of my childhood. A lasso was
thrown over my antlers, and I was bulldogged to the ground like a
calf at a rodeo. The next thing you know the herder's plump wife
was sitting on my flanks and carving a decorative slice out of my
ear with a hunting knife.
   This snippet, along with others, was hung from the tent pole
with care in the time-honored method of reindeer bookkeeping.
Swedish Lapland alone has more than 10,000 legally registered
reindeer earmarks, all different.
   Rudolph the Red-nosed Reindeer has become what Tin Pan Alley
calls a Golden Oldie. Among us, he's strictly for laughs. What
Rudolph really needed to lead the pack was a glowing taillight. On
our frequent travels through frozen mist and fog, we follow the
wagging white tail of the reindeer just ahead.
   Although St. Andrew's Day, the last Sunday in November, is the
big feast in the North Country, Christmas is a fun time for
reindeer. The air is clean and bracing, fragrant with the scent of
the stunted pines. We come gaily galloping with steam rising from
our muzzles when the herder clangs his ice axe into the frozen snow
to dig us out some tasty holiday tidbits.
   The sun at noon is just an embarrassed blush on the horizon, but
in the diamond-studded long winter night the Northern Lights blaze
purple and red and gold, more dazzling than the Rockefeller Center
tree.
   It makes a reindeer want to sing out like Santa _ or at least
bark, which is what we do: `Happy Christmas to all, and to all a
good night.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
