<DOCNO> AP891211-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   12-11 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Let Love Rule'' (Virgin) _ Lenny Kravitz
   
   Quick now _ the cover of Lenny Kravitz's ``Let Love Rule'' album
pictures a black man in dreadlocks with a ring through his nose.
What type of music does the cover protect?
   Your first guess was probably not a singer-songwriter album that
owes much to the 1970s work of such artists as Paul McCartney and
Stevie Wonder.
   But confounding expectations is Kravitz's game. His debut album
is encouraging in several respects. First, it's nice to see an
artist _ any artist _ break past stereotypes at a time when racial
tension is high and too many people have closed-minded views about
what's ``black music'' or ``white music.''
   Second, it's encouraging that any company in the conservative
record business will allow a brand new artist to produce, write and
perform an album virtually by himself. Many established artists
don't get the same trust.
   Of course, the clear danger in these ``homemade'' projects is
too much self-indulgence. Yes, ``Let Love Rule'' suffers from this.
But what it lacks in slickness it frequently makes up for in charm
and intimacy.
   With its overly polite, workmanlike drumming, ``Let Love Rule''
sounds much like McCartney's first solo album. Kravitz also shows a
fondness for the hippie era in his lyrics for such songs as ``I
Build This Garden for Us.''
   The soaring title track is one of this rookie's best moments, as
is ``Mr. Cab Driver.'' In the latter, Kravitz accompanies himself
on fuzztone guitar while telling of a cab driver passing him up for
a ride because of his dreads and skin color. He ends with an
expletive.
   ``My Precious Love,'' a gospel number with guest organist Henry
Hirsch, is another high point. ``Be'' sounds strikingly like
Plastic Ono Band-era John Lennon.
   Be forewarned, though: ``Let Love Rule'' begins to get ponderous
toward the end, with many arrangements crawling.
   Kravitz may not be the genius that this self-produced effort
seems to herald. But simply dismissing him as Mr. Lisa Bonet (his
TV-star wife) is a mistake. He's got enough talent and strength of
convictions to merit watching.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Variations on a Theme by Hindemith, Symphony No. 2, by William
Walton (EMI) _ the Bournemouth Symphony Orchestra, conducted by
Vernon Handley
   
   Here is a regional European orchestra that performs difficult
music at the highest level. Handley elicits crackling yet
controlled performances. The Bournemouth musicians play with the
clarity and solidity typical of many British orchestras; the winds,
particularly in the symphony's Andante movement, play real chamber
music.
   Walton's idiom, though at times reminiscent of Nielsen and
Bartok, is highly original and produces an abundance of orchestral
sounds. His music is worth getting to know.
   _ By Daniel J. Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
