<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Winner Adv22-24   12-11 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Winner, Adv 22-24,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 22-24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS
</TEXT>
<HEAD>From `Death Wish' to a New Wish: Winner's Return to Comedy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-WKD--Bullseye, b0856</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thinking back on his career, Michael Winner finds
something very odd.
   And that is, he said, that ``a very sophisticated British chap
who lives in a stately home in London has made more films probably
than most Americans in the worst slums of America.''
   Winner is a Cambridge University-educated sort of chap who puffs
cigars and is best known for directing the ``Death Wish'' series of
movies about vigilante warfare against the punks, rapists and
muggers of America.
   Now he has gone back to trying to make people laugh.
   ``I sort of slipped into this bath of blood and made all those
pictures, and I decided I had to do something myself to get back,''
Winner said during a break on the set of ``Bullseye,'' his comedy
caper starring Roger Moore and Michael Caine.
   Due for summer release and budgeted at $15 million, ``Bullseye''
pairs Caine and Moore for the first time on-screen, playing dual
roles as con men and atom scientists.
   On one recent day, Winner was shooting at the west London
location of Syon House, home since 1594 to the Dukes of
Northumberland and substantially redesigned two centuries later by
architect Robert Adam and master landscape-gardener Capability
Brown.
   It's a long way from Winner's urban nightmares starring Charles
Bronson, and the director acknowledged he was more in his element
here.
   ``I'm more at home as we talk here in a wonderful 18th century
palazzo, which is the sort of place I live in,'' said Winner, who
lives in a London mansion in the Bayswater district with British
actress Jenny Seagrove.
   ``It's quite nice to be back in a more sophisticated area.''
   Winner makes no apologies for the violence that has often
defined his films, from ``The Mechanic'' in 1972 to the three
``Death Wish'' movies.
   ``I think they were good thrillers,'' said Winner, whose films
have been accused of irresponsibly encouraging viewers to take the
law into their own hands.
   ``I have many friends who are muggers in the Bronx and Harlem
and East New York. They are fascinating people, underused people,
who have to make do when society rejects them. I love the people
there,'' he said.
   Winner started out as a critic and journalist. His early movies
were comedies, among them a caper film ``The Jokers,'' with Oliver
Reed and Michael Crawford. But his comedies on the whole have not
done well, critically or financially.
   His 1975 ``Won Ton Ton the Dog Who Saved Hollywood'' flopped,
despite a starry supporting cast including Henny Youngman, Joan
Blondell, Milton Berle and Edgar Bergen.
   He has just come out with ``A Chorus of Disapproval,'' his film
of Alan Ayckbourn's acclaimed play, to a lukewarm critical
reception.
   The ``Bullseye'' casting coup was his idea, based, he says, on
having watched Caine and Moore at dinner parties and seeing ``how
wonderfully they work together as a comedy act socially.
   ``We've always said we must find something ...and it just
happened merely by chance: I found this script that needed a lot of
work but was basically a wonderful piece for them, so here we are.''
   Winner said the stars' off-screen rapport was evident on screen.
   ``They will often carry on a scene with ad libs of their own,''
he said. ``There's a shorthand both during the shooting and during
the lunch break and all the time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 22-24</NOTE>
</DOC>
