<DOCNO> AP891211-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Gabriel Adv22-24   12-11 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Gabriel, Adv 22-24,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 22-24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: World Music for Peter Gabriel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years ago, Peter Gabriel bought his first
drum machine. All he needed were rhythms to program.
   Bored with rock 'n' roll, the former star of Genesis looked to
Africa, Asia, the Middle East and elsewhere.
   He couldn't believe what he was hearing, the freshest grooves,
the richest harmonies: spirituals from Pakistan; African jazz from
Tabu Ley of Zaire; Cuba's Orquesta Reve, perfomers of ``son,'' the
root of modern salsa.
   His music was never the same. Gabriel began experimenting with
rhythms on his 1982 album, ``Security'' (on one track, ``Rhythm of
the Heat,'' he used a Ghanian drum section), and the same year
helped form the WOMAD (World of Music Arts and Dance) festival,
gathering bands from more than 60 countries.
   Like the Rolling Stones, who went out of their way to praise the
blues musicians who influenced their records, Gabriel wanted to
find a large audience for these exciting sounds.
   ``Grooves for me are physical things,'' explained the
39-year-old Gabriel, in New York recently to promote the release of
four records on the new RealWorld label. ``They make me feel good.
A bad disco groove, of which there's an awful lot, doesn't make me
want to dance.
   ``Some of the grooves we now take as commonplace rock have come
from Africa and Latin America. They travel across the seas and
become slightly different. I think quite often, white artists don't
quite get it right, and we end up coming out with a form which is
new.''
   The records just issued are ``Passion Sources,'' music from the
Middle East and Africa that Gabriel heard while putting together
the soundtrack for ``The Last Temptation of Christ'';
``Shahen-Shah'' by Pakistan's Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan, one of the
foremost singers of the devotional music called ``Qawwali''; ``La
Explosion Del Memento'' by Orquestra Reve; and Tabu Ley's ``Babeti
Soukous.''
   ``We've tried to look for performers who have a lot of soul,''
Gabriel said. ``I think they have strong traditions in their own
countries, it's sometime unfortunate that it gets all out under a
`World Music' label. You talk to the musicians themselves, and they
say, `What the hell is this world music?' I play my music, whatever
it is.'''
   Gabriel is part world musician, part traveling salesman. He
knows record buyers might never even look at the selections from
the Middle East or Africa without an old friend pointing the way.
So if you happen to think of Peter Gabriel while listening to the
infectious grooves of Tabu Ley, well, at least that's a start.
   ``It's not me I'm selling, but someone else,'' he said. ``It's
saying to people who are interested in my music that if you like my
stuff, there's a chance you would like some of the things that
really turn me on.
   ``But it's not Peter Gabriel's label. It's a label in which I
participate. We have a rule where everyone on our committee has to
like everything that goes out.''
   Lyrics are not included, forcing the listener to turn his or her
attention away from the songs' literal meaning and concentrate
instead on the emotions of the performance. In Qawwali, for
instance, words are chanted over and over to a simple rhythm,
giving them a hypnotic, mantra-like effect.
   ``There are ways which you get into a framework where everything
you hear is music, which is probably a nice place to be,'' he said.
``You can really hear the emotion and humanity. So many
intrumentalists are desperately trying to speak with their
instruments, are trying to run the gamut of human emotions. ``You
try to listen to their soul and the feeling that comes out of it.
Some of these wonderful singers from all around the world are just
capable of getting the hairs up in the back of my neck: That's what
I look for.''
   Gabriel, of course, has one advantage over the average listener:
He's actually met the people on the records. Not all the local
musicians, however, were impressed by the presence of a world
famous rock star.
   ``Half knew who I was, half had no idea. One of the Qawwali
groups assumed I was a guy who worked around the studio and didn't
know I was a musician. When they found out I could play, they were
a little bit curious.''
   For Gabriel this music suits his political ideals as well.
Regional tensions, he discovered, can crumble under the power of a
universal language.
   One of the best evenings he had was when he was improvising with
a Pakistani singer and sitar player Ravi Shankar, who's from India.
Shankar played double violin. ``India and Pakistan don't normally
work together and probably wouldn't have in other situations, but
they really got turned on,'' said Gabriel.
   ``I was contributing, but in a subsidiary role. Now I'm going to
do an album with the two of them. They started out not hostile, but
suspicious of each other. By the end of it, they were in love, all
in the space of 40 minutes.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 22-24</NOTE>
</DOC>
