<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--ActiveMinds Adv14   12-11 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Active Minds, Adv 14,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Dec. 14, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Active Minds Are Healthy Minds, Retirees Find</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY PEMBERTON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only thing wrong with retirement,
Gerald Giles says, is he can't get a day off.
   Giles, 68, of West Des Moines, retired as a chemical engineer
seven years ago. As a volunteer for the Service Corps of Retired
Executives, he spends 10 hours a week advising small businesses on
marketing and sales techniques. He also is a speaker for Gideons
International, which distributes Bibles.
   Wes Kitchell, who retired as an insurance consultant in 1981,
coordinates monthly business seminars for SCORE. He has been a
trustee for the Masons for three years and visits once a week with
patients at Mercy Hospital's Heritage Program for Seniors.
   ``Some people think I'm driven, but I just get a big kick out of
life,'' said Kitchell, 74, of Des Moines.
   Kitchell and Giles may be getting more than just a kick out of
life.
   ``We think differently as we get older, in a slower manner, and
there is some memory loss which is a perfectly normal finding,''
said Dr. Robert Bender, of the Mercy Hospital Geriatric Clinic.
``But there is some evidence that staying mentally active may
actually help preserve brain function.''
   Mental lethargy and its effects on good health can be seen most
easily in nursing home patients, said Dr. Roy Overton, another
gerontologist at Mercy.
   ``In nursing home patients, we see these pseudo dementias that
aren't real dementias at all. You walk into a room and see a
patient staring at the ceiling or the floor. And you think they've
lost their minds but they haven't. They're truly depressed,'' said
Overton.
   Bender tells his patients to write down their talents and use
them. ``Using one's talents is the epitome of mental activity which
may prevent or slow down the changes in the aging brain.
   ``Albert Einstein did active research until the week before he
died in his 70s. That shows you that we always have the capacity to
learn more.''
   Gwen Rusk, 79, of Des Moines, worked as an insurance secretary
for 14 years until retirement in 1980. ``Now, I stay home as a last
resort,'' said Rusk, who volunteers 15 to 20 hours a week at the
Retired Senior Volunteer Program. Her rule is not to spend more
time playing bridge than doing volunteer work.
   RSVP, a United Way program begun in 1972, matches volunteers
with jobs in the community. Program director Barb Wacker said its
1,100 volunteers donated 162,000 hours in fiscal 1988-89.
   Rusk and other retirees at a senior housing building make
teaching aids for children in the Head Start program. They fashion
balls out of fabric scraps and nylon stockings and put together
jump ropes by connecting red plastic loops.
   ``It isn't that I don't like my own company, but actually it can
get very stale if you're not out in the world to see what's
happening. That's how you make friends to ensure you have friends
when you become an old lady,'' Rusk said.
   Miriam Cline, 68, a member of the Urbandale City Council, is on
an RSVP committee that gives advice on planning for retirement. She
was co-coordinator of the Iowa Peace Ribbon Project in 1984 and
visited Nicaragua in 1986 for the International Women's Day and to
learn about problems facing women there.
   Cline said she has retired at least six times, but can't make it
stick. She stays involved ``to feel like I'm worth something, have
something to offer and have a place in this world.''
   Virginia Yaeger, 65, of Des Moines, raised two children after
her divorce by working as a dental assistant. At age 60, she was
forced out of her job when her boss retired. ``I tried to find work
with another dentist but they all wanted to hire younger dental
assistants,'' Yaeger said.
   She called the Retired Iowans Employment Program at the state
Department of Elder Affairs, which placed 2,000 senior citizens in
paying jobs last year. It helped her get a job as a receptionist at
Crossroads, a seniors program.
   ``I learned to use one of these fancy memory typewriters. I
learned how to get around that pretty well,'' she said. ``If you
stay home you become a couch potato with your soap operas and you
just don't think like you did before.
   ``I'll work as long as my health holds out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 14</NOTE>
