<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Serape Adv14   12-11 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Serape, Adv 14,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Dec. 14, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Anthology Publishes Work by Older Writers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN GOESSL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ah, the stories they can tell. About a
man obsessed with the education of his children. Or a love story
with Venice as a backdrop. Or building a homestead in the early
1900s.
   ``A lot of us do memory pieces and if they're not entirely
memory we might write fiction based on things we've known,'' said
writer Garnet Garoni, 71, of Las Cruces. ``There isn't a very big
market for that type of story, but it's really fun to write.''
   Not a big market, maybe, but Mrs. Garoni and other older New
Mexicans have found an outlet in Serape, an annual anthology of
poetry and short stories by senior citizens. Published by Nightjar
Press at New Mexico State University, Serape first appeared on New
Mexico bookshelves in 1983, the result of a creative writing class
at a Las Cruces senior center.
   Kevin McIlvoy, an associate professor of English at New Mexico
State, isn't proud that he was surprised at the caliber of writing
he found among students at Munson Senior Citizen's Center. But his
thinking took a quick, sharp turn.
   ``I thought, `Gee, this is powerful writing,''' says McIlvoy,
who still teaches the weekly class. ``It's so strong, so powerful
and so informed by those years of experience that I really wanted
it to be brought to readers.''
   Serape's early issues contained work by class members, but more
recent editions have been open to older writers throughout the
state. Some 30 pieces of work by 15 authors _ all of them 55 or
older _ appear in the sixth edition of ``Serape,'' scheduled for
release this month.
   It will be the fourth time Mrs. Garoni's work has been published
in ``Serape.'' ``Miracles Do Happen,'' a short, fictional story
about a girl who leaves a Wisconsin town for the bright lights of
Chicago.
   ``Really one of my own thoughts about Serape is what we're doing
is giving exposure to people whose names are not already
recognizable, but who are certainly doing important work,'' McIlvoy
said.
   He and editors Kathryn Byrd and Bill Pearson, retirees whose
work has appeared in Serape, waded through 64 manuscripts of about
25 pages each before making the wrenching final selections for the
1989 edition.
   ``We get quite a massive pile of material,'' McIlvoy said. The
pile could become even more massive if he is able to expand the
anthology to include older writers from throughout the Southwest.
McIlvoy proposed the idea to New Mexico State officials while also
telling them the expansion would require higher production
standards and more pages _ and therefore more funding.
   Serape, which sells for $6 and can be purchased at bookstores
around the state or from New Mexico State, now is funded mainly
through sales and by the university, with 10 percent coming from
donors and patrons.
   ``Teaching at the Munson Center, as I have done for the last six
years, and editing this anthology are for me the most important,
stimulating things that I do,'' McIlvoy said. ``I work with
extremely talented young writers here at the university, but the
old cliche applies _ there's no replacing experience.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 14</NOTE>
