<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     12-11 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0852</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment climbed to a 10-month high of 5.4
percent in November and manufacturing payrolls shrank for the
eighth consecutive month, the government said.
   The increase in the civilian jobless rate from 5.3 percent came
despite the addition of 210,000 non-farm jobs last month.
   The new non-farm jobs reported Friday by the Labor Department
was in itself a moderately strong number, but the government also
sharply cut its job growth figures for October from 233,000 to
93,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is considering
significant relaxation of a U.S. ban on high technology exports to
Eastern Europe, Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher says.
   Mosbacher indicated Hungary and Poland could be two of the main
beneficiaries of such a change. He said in a television interview
the two countries were discussing with U.S. officials how to
prevent the transfer of militarily strategic items to neighboring
Communist-bloc countries.
   A change in U.S. restrictions would be designed to encourage the
political liberalization in Eastern Europe and to deal with heavy
pressure from U.S. allies seeking an easing of export controls to
the Soviet bloc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil giant Chevron Corp. said it had moved
to thwart buyout threats raised by Pennzoil Co.'s purchase of an
8.8 percent stake, suing to force the sale of the stock and beefing
up its takeover defenses.
   Chevron, in a U.S. District Court suit filed late Thursday,
scoffed at Pennzoil's claim that it was not interested in a
takeover and accused the much smaller company of plotting to force
a restructuring that would benefit Pennzoil.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government incorrectly cut off cash
benefits to some of the most vulnerable of America's poor _ the
elderly, blind and disabled _ in more than half the cases reviewed
in a study, the Social Security Administration said.
   The findings suggest more than 10,000 recipients of Supplemental
Security Income may have their benefits suspended each year
``despite being unable to act or unlikely to understand'' what they
must do to continue receiving benefits, an agency report released
Friday said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the 12-nation European
Community, closing ranks amid upheaval in Eastern Europe, agreed to
press ahead with an economic and monetary union despite British
opposition.
   The decision Friday, on the opening day of a two-day summit,
means the EC will convene a special conference in December 1990 to
start negotiations for the adoption of a single currency and to set
up a system of central banks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. officials announced they are forming a
division to develop a new widebody plane that could become the 777.
The new jet will be larger than an existing 767 but smaller than
the familiar 747 model.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton said Friday
the company is going ahead and developing the plane and making
first offers to airlines. But Thornton said no airlines have yet
offered to buy the plane and Boeing is far from committed to
actually building it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department is considering new
40-year bonds as part of its government financing operations.
   A Fed official made the announcement Friday. Thirty-year bonds
currently are the longest-term debt instruments sold by the
Treasury to finance the government. It also periodically auctions
shorter-term bonds, notes and bills to raise money.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilton International, a chain of 140 hotels
worldwide, plans to link up with a separate company, Hilton Hotels
Corp., in marketing resorts and airport hotels.
   The program will include joint marketing of resort hotels and
hotels at major airports worldwide, Hilton International Chairman
John Jarvis said Friday. Hilton International also is launching a
$17 million advertising campaign and a corporate identity program.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loral Corp. pleaded guilty to charges it
tried to improperly influence the award of two defense contracts by
obtaining confidential data from key Pentagon officials.
   New York-based Loral, which agreed to pay $5.77 million in
fines, penalties and reimbursement for the cost of the
investigation, pleaded guilty Friday to conspiracy, conversion of
government property and filing a false statement.
   The New York-based defense contractor admitted charging the
Pentagon $578,000 it paid under bogus consulting arrangements to a
defense consultant who actually was hired to influence the award of
contracts for a radar detection device and a Navy blimp.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market chalked up a moderate gain Friday, aided by
falling interest rates and new signs of sluggish economic growth.
The Dow Jones industrials average rose 10.66 to 2,731.44, winding
up the week with a net loss of 16.21 points.
   The dollar ended marginally weaker.
   Bond prices rose.
   Pork belly futures prices plunged; livestock futures were lower;
cotton continued to lose ground; grain and soybeans were mixed;
precious metals gained and energy futures were mostly higher.
</TEXT>
