<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingHelicopters     12-11 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Helicopters,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Helicopters, Union Reach Agreement on New Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Helicopters and 3,000 union members
have reached agreement on a three-year contract that parallels one
that ended a 48-day strike by Machinists at parent Boeing Co.
   The agreement is retroactive to Oct. 5, when the old contract
would have expired without a day-to-day extension.
   A Boeing Helicopters announcement did not provide results of the
ratification vote Sunday. United Aerospace Workers' Local 1069
officials could not be reached for comment.
   The new Boeing Helicopters contract parallels the package
accepted three weeks ago by the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
   The contract includes a three-year series of wage increases,
lump sum payments and quarterly cost-of-living adjustments, the
company said.
   The wage increases of 4 percent, 3 percent and 3 percent are
retroactive to Oct. 5. Three lump sum payments of 10 percent, 5
percent and 4 percent are to be paid on Dec. 15 of 1989, 1990 and
1991.
   Boeing Helicopters, based in Ridley Township outside
Philadelphia, produces military rotocraft, including the tilt-rotor
V-22 Osprey transport.
   Earlier this month, Defense Department Secretary Dick Cheney
canceled the V-22 production contracts with Boeing Helicopters and
Bell Helicopter-Textron of Fort Worth, Texas.
   The Marines want to use the V-22 to shuttle troops from ship to
shore in amphibious operations. The canceled contract applies only
to production money appropriated for the fiscal year 1989, which
ended in September.
   Boeing and Bell are building six V-22 prototypes, and research
and development contracts will continue, Boeing said.
</TEXT>
