<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-11 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell today against all major foreign
currencies, except the Japanese yen and the Canadian dollar in
light overseas trading.
   Gold prices rose in quiet trading.
   Traders said fundamentals have changed little from last week
with the West German mark still strong against all currencies.
   Trading will remain uneventful, dealers predicted, as the market
winds down before the Christmas holiday season.
   ``I don't think much will happen any more before Christmas,
although the trend line shows it (the dollar) could move a little
bit lower,'' said a trader at a large Frankfurt bank.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose even though traders said the Bank of
Japan sold dollars to check the American currency's rise. The Bank
of Japan, the nation's central bank, does not comment on its market
activities.
   The dollar rose 0.38 yen in Tokyo to a closing 144.65 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 144.57 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.7695 West German marks, down from 1.7720;
1.5965 Swiss francs, down from 1.5985; 6.0455 French francs, down
from 6.0565; 1.9962 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0000; 1,305.50
Italian lire, down from 1,306.50; and 1.1615 Canadian dollars,
unchanged.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5835 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5793 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $412.90 a troy ounce, up
from $411.55 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $414.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $413.90, up from $409.25 bid late
Friday.
   Gold in Hong Kong rose 11 cents to close at a bid $412.26.
   Silver rose in London to a bid price of $5.66 a troy ounce, up
from Friday's $5.64.
