<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0746EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-11 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Rise Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen for
the seventh consecutive trading day today and prices on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange also rose slightly.
   The dollar closed at 144.65, up 0.38 yen from its 144.27 yen
close on Friday. It opened at 144.50 yen and ranged between 144.45
yen and 144.73 yen. The U.S. currency now has climbed 1.75 yen in
seven trading days.
   Its higher opening resulted from its surge last week in New
York, where it closed at 144.25 on Friday, and from tightened
demand for a large number of export contracts usually due for
settlement on Mondays, dealers said.
   But the Bank of Japan was believed to have stepped into the
market several times, selling dollars to keep the U.S. currency
within a narrow range, said Kaneo Ogino of Goldman Sachs in Tokyo.
The central bank does not comment on its exchange market activities.
   Ogino said market activity was likely to trail off toward the
end of the month, with dealers unwilling to take large positions
before the new year.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues gained 28.61 points, or 0.08 percent, closing at
37,752.67. On Friday, the Nikkei fell 134.05 points after closing
at record highs on 11 of the preceding 12 trading days.
   Trading started slowly today as investors waited to see the
market's performance after its strong advances last week, traders
said.
   After opening lower, the Nikkei rebounded toward the end of the
morning session on renewed buying of resource-related and
incentive-backed issues, dealers said.
   The large amount of funds flowing into the market from
institutional and corporate investors prevented a major decline
from profit-taking, they said.
   Investors are watching currency markets carefully out of concern
that a renewed surge of the dollar against the yen could provoke an
interest rate hike, said Julian Jones of W.I. Carr's equity sales.
   Volume was estimated at 700 million shares, down from an
estimated 1 billion shares Friday.
</TEXT>
