<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Wyse-Taiwan     12-11 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wyse-Taiwan,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Group to Acquire Wyse Technology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group of government and
local enterprises has agreed to acquire the California-based
computer products company Wyse Technology Inc. in a cash deal
valued at $268 million, both groups announced today.
   The buyout would be the largest ever of a foreign firm by Taiwan.
   Under the agreement, the Taiwan group, known as the Channel
International Corp., would buy all Wyse's shares for $10 each, said
Koo Cheng-fu, chairman of China Investment and Trust Co., the
largest investor in the buyout.
   ``The acquisition is an important step for Taiwan's electronics
and computer industries to enter the world market,'' Koo told a
news conference.
   Koo said his group would use Wyse's sales channels and
technology personnel to promote Taiwan's high-technology products.
   Koo's company will offer 29 percent of the capital for the
investment.
   The acquisition also was supported by Taiwan's Cabinet, which
offered 20 percent of the total investment from a development fund.
Other investors include Mitac Computers, a local computer
manufacturer, and two petrochemical companies.
   The acquisition, which was approved by Wyse's board of
directors, is expected to be completed next week.
   Wyse, based in San Jose, Calif., holds about a 50 percent market
share for general-purpose terminals in the United States. It also
produces monitors and IBM-compatible personal computers.
   Wyse officials began a search for buyers earlier this year after
the 8-year-old company suffered a loss of $21 million in the 1989
fiscal year ended March 31, compared with a $28 million profit the
previous year.
   Wyse Chairman Bernard K. Tse said the acquisition ``provides
shareholders an opportunity to maximize the value of their shares
at this time.''
   Daniel Wu, president of Channel International, said the group's
main objective will be to improve business. He said he was
confident demand for computer terminals would remain strong.
   Taiwanese businessmen have shown growing interest in acqusition
of foreign firms, which they believe could help boost their
business in the world market.
   Last month, Samuel Hsieh, governor of the Central Bank, proposed
to use Taiwan's foreign reserves of about $73 billion for loans to
local enterprises for overseas acquisitions.
   In August, Continental Engineering Corp., Taiwan's leading
construction company, acquired American Bridge Co. of Pittsburgh,
for an estimated $70 million to $100 million.
</TEXT>
