<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 0923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-WaterPrivatization     12-11 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Water Privatization,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government's Latest Sale is 5.7 Times Oversubscribed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's $8.3 billion sale of its water
industry was 5.7 times oversubscribed, attracting the second
highest number of applicants for a British privatization, officials
said Monday.
   Demand for shares of the 10 water authorities of England and
Wales was strong enough to trigger ``clawback'' provisions that
will give small investors nearly half the stock instead of the
previously planned 27 percent.
   Most investors will get far fewer shares than they asked for in
the sale, which totals 5.24 billion pounds.
   ``It is a great success,'' Environment Minister Michael Howard
said. ``We have proved our critics wrong.''
   Some 2.7 million people made applications, the second highest
response ever for a government privatization after the 4.5 million
applicants in British Gas PLC sale.
   There had been concern that the sale would be unsuccessful
because the stock market has been in the doldrums and the
privatization has faced stiff opposition from critics who believed
such a vital utility should remain government-owned.
   Trading in the shares officially begins Tuesday on London's
Stock Exchange. In the ``gray,'' or unofficial, market the shares
were trading at 126 pence, or $1.99, at midday Monday.
   The government is selling 2.183 million shares at 240 pence, or
$3.79, each but investors only put 100 pence down and pay the rest
off in installments.
   Under the ``clawback'' provisions in the water sale,
institutional investors now will get 39 percent of the shares, and
foreign investors the remainder. Each investor everyone will get at
least 100 shares.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government has
sold off billions of pounds worth of state-owned companies in the
past decade to promote capitalism in Britain.
</TEXT>
