<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-NationalSemiconductor     12-11 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-National Semiconductor,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Semiconductor Reports $2.4 Million Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp.
announced Monday it earned $2.4 million in the second quarter
compared with a loss of $25.2 million for the same period last year.
   The company, citing progress in addressing inventory, capacity
and other cost issues, said it had met its goal to return to
profitability during the period, which ended Nov. 26.
   Earnings per common share, after payment of preferred dividends,
were zero in the latest quarter in contrast to a loss of 27 cents a
share a year earlier. National Semiconductor said its net sales for
the second three months of fiscal 1990 rose to $416.8 million from
$404.6 million.
   Sales for the first half of fiscal 1990 were $814.4 million,
with a net loss of $19.5 million, or 24 cents a share. Sales during
the first half of last year were $849.5 million, with a net loss of
$55.7 million, or 58 cents a share.
   The chipmaker in February announced plans to close its Danbury,
Conn., plant. In May, the company said it would close a plant in
Seoul, South Korea, and consolidate two Singapore factories in an
attempt to reduce duplication created by the acquisition of
Fairchild Semiconductor.
</TEXT>
