<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Climb On Soviet Trade News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose modestly in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid hopes of
increased grain sales to the Soviet Union.
   Analysts cited as a major factor the Agriculture Department's
announcement on Friday that it had increased by 4 million metric
tons to 20 million metric tons the amount of U.S. grain the Soviet
Union would be allowed to purchase during the current marketing
year.
   Some of this morning's buying also was linked to President
Bush's statement Friday that he would push for granting
most-favored-nation trade status to the Soviet Union. The
designation would allow for freer trade between the superpowers.
   Forecasts for cold, dry weather this week in the Great Plains
and the Midwest also lent support to the grain markets.
   In early trading, wheat futures were } cent to 1{ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.11{ a bushel; corn
futures were { cent to 1 cent higher with December at $2.37\ a
bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1\ cents higher with December at $1.45
a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 2} cents higher with January at
$5.80{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures gained while pork futures fell in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Frozen pork bellies were down
the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit in early trading after limit losses
in the two previous sessions.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .62 cent higher with December at
76.17 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to .33 cent higher
with January at 83 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent to .70
cent lower with December at 50.67 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent to 2 cents lower with February at 50.45 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Friday.
</TEXT>
