<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Test of Your 1980s Business IQ</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are 20 questions asking everything you ought to know about
the business '80s:
   1. Who described the Reagan economic plan in 1980 as ``voodoo
economics''?
   2. Who said, ``Welcome to the world of being a sleaze''?
   3. What is the significance of the number 508?
   4. Who was the decade's youngest billionaire?
   5. Who warned of a market ``meltdown'' more than six months
before the Crash of 1987?
   6. Why was trading in the stock of Bache &amp; Co. halted on the
afternoon of March 27, 1980?
   7. What was the Predators' Ball?
   8. After what video game was a defensive tactic against
takeovers named?
   9. What ``discontinued'' item of transportation equipment was
revived in the 1980s?
   10. Who asked, ``Where's the beef?''
   11. When fictional tycoon Gordon Gekko said ``greed is good'' in
the movie ``Wall Street,'' what real person was he echoing and what
was the actual quote?
   12. What British company bought the Pillsbury Dough Boy?
   13. Who quit her job at Bendix Corp. when rumors surfaced of a
romance with the boss?
   14. What was the name of the broker who used reporter R. Foster
Winans' tips to trade stocks in advance of Winans columns in The
Wall Street Journal?
   15. What did Saul Steinberg get from Walt Disney Co.?
   16. What was Michael Jackson endorsing when his hair caught fire
during a commercial filming?
   17. What was the term used to describe the program trading
technique that some believe contributed to the stock market crash
of 1987?
   18. Who was handcuffed and frisked by authorities in front of
his co-workers at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. in a dramatic insider
trading arrest?
   19. What banking product was first made available to the public
on Dec. 14, 1982?
   20. Who was accused of hunting Ivan Boesky with a loaded assault
rifle?
   ANSWERS
   1. George Bush.
   2. Bruce Lee Newberg, a former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
trader indicted along with Michael Milken.
   3. The number of points the Dow Jones industrial average fell on
Black Monday.
   4. Bill Gates of Microsoft Corp.
   5. John Phelan, chairman of the New York Stock Exchange.
   6. The Hunt Brothers of Texas, who did much of their business
with Bache, had run into trouble trying to corner the silver
market, precipitating a crisis in the financial markets.
   7. An annual gathering of junk-bond customers of Drexel Burnham
Lambert.
   8. Pac Man.
   9. The convertible.
   10. Clara Peller (and Walter Mondale)
   11. Ivan Boesky, who told students at Berkeley in 1985, ``greed
is healthy.''
   12. Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   13. Mary Cunningham.
   14. Peter Brant.
   15. Greenmail.
   16. Pepsi.
   17. Portfolio insurance.
   18. Richard Wigton, a Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. trader.
   19. The money market deposit account, to compete with money
market mutual funds.
   20. John A. Mulheren.
</TEXT>
