<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Timeline for the Business '80s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the notable events of the 1980s in business and
the economy.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1980:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 3: Carter embargoes grain sales to Soviet Union.
   March 14: Carter responds to high inflation by imposing first
peacetime credit controls in modern times.
   April 21: Dow Jones industrial average hits decade low of 759.13.
   Dec. 19: Prime lending rate rises to 21.5 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1981:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 24: Reagan lifts Soviet grain embargo.
   May 1: Japan agrees to ``voluntary'' restraints on exports of
passenger cars to the United States.
   Aug. 3: Air traffic controllers begin illegal strike and are
fired.
   Aug. 13: Reagan signs tax-cutting legislation; top rate drops to
50 percent from 70 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1982:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 7: U.S. Steel buys Marathon Oil Co. for $6.3 billion.
   Jan. 8: AT&amp;T agrees to give up 22 local telephone companies,
representing $80 billion in assets. It is freed to enter computer
business.
   October: Unemployment hits 10.8 percent, highest in 42 years.
   November: Economy hits bottom and expansion begins.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1983:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 5: Crude oil settles at record $32.15 a barrel on New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   Aug. 20: Reagan lifts curbs on export of pipeline-laying
equipment to the Soviet Union.
   Oct. 1: National debt tops $1 trillion.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1984:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 1: Breakup of AT&amp;T takes effect.
   Feb. 13: Texaco Inc. outbids Pennzoil Co. and buys Getty Oil Co.
for $10 billion, a deal that comes back to haunt Texaco.
   April 26: Chevron Corp. buys Gulf Oil Co. for $13.2 billion in
record takeover.
   Sept. 26: Continental Illinois Bank of Chicago gets record
federal bailout.
   Dec. 3: Gas leak from Union Carbide plant in Bhopal, India,
kills at least 1,700 people and injures 200,000.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1985:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 5: General Motors Corp. buys Hughes Aircraft Co., founded
by Howard Hughes.
   July 10: Coca-Cola Co. brings back original-formula Coke after
consumer protest.
   Dec. 11: General Electric Co. agrees to buys RCA Corp.
   Dec. 23: Reagan signs farm bill cutting price and income
supports and bailing out Farm Credit System.
   United States becomes net debtor nation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1986:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 31: Crude oil falls to decade-low close of $10.42 a barrel
on New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Oct. 22: Reagan signs tax-reform bill, lowering top rates,
eliminating tax shelters, limiting IRA deductions and ending
capital gains tax break.
   Nov. 14: Stock speculator Ivan Boesky pays $100 million in fines
and restitution; agrees to plead guilty to a single felony count.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 12: Texaco files for bankruptcy while appealing $11
billion award to Pennzoil.
   April 17: Reagan slaps high tariffs on certain Japanese products
over alleged barriers to U.S.-made computer chips.
   June 2: Reagan announces Paul Volcker will step down as chairman
of the Federal Reserve, to be replaced by Alan Greenspan.
   Oct. 19: Stock market suffers biggest single-day drop in history
as Dow Jones industrial average falls 508 points.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 2: Reagan and Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney sign
agreement to create largest free-trade area in the world.
   April 7: Texaco emerges from Chapter 11.
   Aug. 17: Reagan signs trade bill providing for new means to deal
with unfair foreign competition.
   Nov. 29: RJR Nabisco Inc. agrees to $25 billion buyout, biggest
in history.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1989:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 4: Machinists strike Eastern Airlines; pilots and flight
attendants walk out in sympathy.
   March 29: Federal grand jury indicts Michael Milken and two
others on allegations of insider trading.
   April 19: Congress approves $159 billion plan to bail out
savings and loans.
   Aug. 24: Stock market recovers and Dow Jones industrial average
surpasses the previous peak reached in August 1987.
   November: Longest peacetime economic expansion in U.S. history
reaches seventh anniversary.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
