<DOCNO> AP891211-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Airlines Adv00   12-11 0893</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Airlines, Adv 00,0922</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>After Decade of Deregulation, Airlines Facing Challenges</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest airline company is a
conglomeration of big and small carriers flying under the regional
banner of Texas Air Corp.
   Almost every other major carrier has been a target for takeover
or restructuring.
   Airports are clogged, fares are inscrutable, and the commercial
fleet is showing its age with frightening regularity.
   That is probably not the future the architects of deregulation
imagined in 1978 when the airline industry was freed from
government control over fares and routes.
   But that future is now, after little more than a decade of
freewheeling competition.
   For business students of the 1980s, there was no more compelling
case study of the impact of Reagan-era deregulation. No industry
underwent more wrenching changes. None moved from controls to
competition to consolidation as quickly.
   In October 1988, the airlines celebrated their first decade of
freedom. Less than a year later, the industry was engulfed by a
wave of takeover fever, its second since deregulation began.
   ``I'm uneasy about the wave of buyouts,'' said Alfred Kahn, a
former chairman of the Civil Aeronautics Board who is widely
considered the father of airline deregulation. ``The critical thing
is, how does it affect competition?''
   In the space of a week last August, United Airlines, the
nation's second-largest carrier, was put into play by a $5.4
billion buyout bid for parent UAL Corp. from oilman Marvin Davis;
an investor group completed its $3.65 billion buyout of NWA Inc.,
parent of Northwest Airlines; frequently rumored takeover target
USAir Group Inc. completed its merger with Piedmont Aviation and
separately sold a major stake to ``white knight'' investor Warren
Buffett; and a manufacturing company said it might consider a
takeover of Midway Airlines.
   While the fierce competition sparked by deregulation turned many
airlines into hot properties, it put others in desperate straits.
In 1989, three carriers filed for bankruptcy protection under
Chapter 11: Texas Air's Eastern Airlines, hit by a crippling strike
in early March; Braniff Inc., which filed for the second time in
seven years; and Presidential Airways, a feeder carrier for United.
   As some companies faltered, the takeover frenzy continued to
build, culminating in developer Donald Trump's $7.5 billion buyout
proposal in October for AMR Corp., parent of industry leader
American Airlines.
   When UAL failed to assemble financing for its $6.75 billion
pilot-management buyout _ an announcement that caused a sudden
190-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average on Oct. 13 _ the
mania subsided temporarily.
   But UAL talks revived, and experts said the reshaping of the
industry will continue in the '90s.
   Airlines in Western Europe are positioning themselves to exploit
the Common Market deregulation set to begin in 1992, and some are
swooping down to buy pieces of U.S. carriers.
   The prospect of foreign ownership and the heavy debts associated
with takeovers have prompted warnings from officials in Washington,
including Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner.
   Under U.S. law, foreign airlines aren't allowed to own more than
25 percent of the voting stock of domestic carriers. In October,
Skinner used his authority to force KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, the
foreign partner in the NWA deal, to cut its $400 million investment
by $225 million.
   For travelers, the fallout from deregulation has been even more
worrisome.
   The number of passengers on U.S. airlines jumped to around 455
million in 1988 from 275 million in 1978, according to the Air
Transport Association. By the year 2000, traffic is projected to be
800 million or 900 million people.
   There's nowhere near enough capacity in the system _ runways,
airport space and air traffic control _ to handle the onslaught.
   The nation's commercial fleet, meanwhile, has been aging
rapidly, from an average 8.5 years old in 1978 to 12.5 a decade
later. Aging aircraft have been blamed for some terrifying
accidents in recent years and have compelled thriving big airlines
to buy new jets.
   To upgrade their fleets, major U.S. carriers spent a record $67
billion in the first 11 months of 1989 on 1,600 new planes. Boeing
Co., the largest commercial aircraft maker, cannot keep pace. Its
backlog, swollen further by the Machinists union strike that ended
Nov. 20, is now worth $85 billion.
   The problems, and the concern about safety they have prompted,
have intensified pressure on the federal government to re-regulate
the industry, Kahn and others warn. Proposals to re-regulate the
airlines emerged in Congress in early November.
   The industry hopes it will be allowed to work out the problems.
As for the lack of capacity, ``There's a lot of immediate things
that can be done,'' Eastern President Phil Bakes said in an
interview. Bakes, a former attorney for the CAB, was influential in
drawing up the 1978 deregulation law.
   As a sign of progress, he pointed to the first meeting in
mid-October of the Aviation System Capacity Task Force _ a group
that includes representatives of the major airlines, airport
operators and the Federal Aviation Administration.
   Skinner's department is developing a new U.S. transportation
policy to take the country into the 21st century, and the FAA's new
System Capacity Office will help expedite the rebuilding of the
infrastructure.
   If those efforts fail, Skinner warned, ``We will lose the
benefits of deregulation.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Airlines-Deregulation Adv00   12-11 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Airlines-Deregulation, Adv 00,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Airline Deregulation: Pros and Cons</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Decade-Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since the nation's airline industry was
deregulated in October 1978, a debate has raged on the benefits and
problems created by the move.
   Among the main benefits, according to supporters and industry
experts:
   _A ``democratization'' of air travel, formerly the domain of
relatively few Americans. The number of passengers on U.S. airlines
jumped to around 455 million last year from 275 million in 1978. By
the year 2000, that traffic is widely projected to surge to 800
million or 900 million people.
   _With nine out of 10 air travelers flying on some sort of
discount fare, the average price of a plane ticket dropped 21
percent from 1978 to 1988 with inflation taken into account,
according to the Air Transport Association.
   _A planeload of passengers takes off from an airport somewhere
in the country on an average of every 4.8 seconds.
   _Several studies of airline deregulation contend that travelers
and the economy as a whole have benefited.
   The downside:
   _Growing complaints about the concentration of the industry
around a few ``mega-carriers'' and about the dominance they wield
in and out of some cities, and through links with commuter airlines
to entire regions of the country.
   _Unprecedented congestion at busy airports and in the skies
surrounding them, with some airport planners resorting to high
landing fees to keep out smaller aircraft.
   _Concerns about aviation safety. Critics both in and out of the
industry complain that the government is unable to keep up with
traffic growth and industry fluctuations to assure a continuing
high level of safety.
   _Predictions of catastrophe and re-regulation of the industry
unless airports are expanded, new airports are built and the air
traffic control system is modernized.
   _Complaints that airline service continues to deteriorate,
especially in rural areas, while prices are allowed to soar
unfairly high in some markets, especially between busy ``hub''
airports dominated by one or two airlines.
   _A realization that the days of aviation entrepreneurs starting
an airline from scratch and taking on the competition have long
passed, the victim of the same ``mega-carriers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
