<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Fortune500 Adv00   12-11 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Fortune 500, Adv 00,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Buyouts, Shift from Industrial Pursuits Changed Face of Fortune 500</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Levi Strauss disappeared from industrial
America's best-known roster, sold in a management buyout.
   Lone Star Industries became too small to qualify.
   International Telephone &amp; Telegraph was reclassified and appears
on a separate service company list.
   For a variety of reasons, upwards of one-third of the companies
included at the end of the 1970s on the Fortune 500 ranking of the
nation's biggest industrial concerns were missing from the same
list a decade later.
   The buyout wave of the 1980s was a major factor in the sweeping
changes in the Fortune 500 list. Combined sales rose 66 percent to
more than $2 trillion.
   Levi Strauss, which was No. 177 on the list published in 1979,
last appeared among the Fortune 500 in 1985 after which it was sold
to management.
   Continental Oil, which ranked a lofty 18th on the 1979 list,
changed its name that year to Conoco, then vanished from the list
after DuPont Co. acquired it in 1981.
   The flip side of the buyout wave has been that buyers generally
moved up the list. DuPont was ranked ninth in 1989, up from No. 16
a decade earlier.
   Making an even bigger move was Philip Morris Companies Inc., the
cigarette manufacturer ranked 10th in 1989 and 46th in 1979. It
bought General Foods, which was 41st in 1979, and Kraft, which was
39th, during the 1980s.
   Some companies dropped off the list, meanwhile, because they
sold assets or failed to grow fast enough.
   Lone Star Industries, which sold assets over the decade, was No.
248 in 1979 and last appeared in 1987.
   Another big factor in the changes was an increasing emphasis on
service businesses. Companies must derive at least 50 percent of
their sales from manufacturing or mining to qualify for the
magazine's industrial rankings; otherwise they are eligible for
Fortune's Service 500.
   That caused companies like ITT, ranked 11th on the 1979
industrial list, to be moved to the list of diversified service
companies in 1988.
   Other prominent companies reclassified as service concerns
during the 1980s included Gulf &amp; Western Industries, ranked 58th on
the industrial list in 1979 and now known as Paramount Pictures
Inc., and American Can, which was 66th in 1979 and is now called
Primerica.
   The top of the Fortune 500 industrial listing has been fairly
stable despite the exodus of companies lower down.
   Eight of the Top 10 in 1979 were still there in 1989.
   The dropouts are Standard Oil of California, now known as
Chevron, and Gulf Oil, which was acquired by Chevron in 1984.
Standard Oil had been No. 6 in 1979 and Gulf Oil was ninth. Chevron
ranks 11th on the 1989 list.
   They were replaced by the acquisitive DuPont and Philip Morris.
   General Motors led the 1979 list with $63.2 billion in sales and
remained at the top in 1989 with nearly twice as much _ $121.1
billion.
   The 500th company in 1979 moved halfway up the ladder,
reflecting computer industry growth in the Money Decade.
   Data General was 500th in 1979 with sales of $379.9 million and
No. 272 in 1989 with sales of $1.36 billion.
</TEXT>
