<DOCNO> AP891211-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Autos Adv00   12-11 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Autos, Adv 00,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Firmly Rooted U.S. Automakers Bent Far Eastward in '80s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tracker is one of those vehicles that could
have existed only in the 1980s: designed in Japan, built in Canada
by a U.S.-Japanese partnership and sold in the United States.
   Did that make it Japanese, Canadian, or maybe American, since it
was sold in Chevrolet showrooms? Its producers avoided the issue by
calling it a Geo, from the Greek word for Earth.
   For the U.S. auto industry, it was a confusing, sometimes
difficult and above all blurry decade.
   Blurriest were the definitions of what was an imported car.
Scenes of angry men battering a Toyota with sledgehammers faded
into scenes of happy Japanese and American autoworkers toiling
together on assembly plant teams.
   People weren't even sure what it was the companies were making.
The Nissan Pathfinder was classified as a car by the Treasury
Department and a truck by the Transportation Department.
   As for attitudes toward the Japanese, just ask Bob McCurry,
executive vice president of Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A. Inc.
   ``Most of the prejudices have gone away,'' he said, ``but I
still have some relatives where they haven't.''
   The auto industry was touched, like many others, by
acquisitions, joint ventures and takeovers. As in other industries,
the Japanese influence shifted into high gear.
   Proud American automakers, industrial pillars of the West,
struggled to halt their loss of market share to competitors from
across the Pacific by forming joint ventures with Japanese
companies and imitating Japan's manufacturing and labor management.
   The Tracker typifies the partnership trend. The small
sport-utility vehicle was designed by Suzuki Motor Co. Ltd. of
Japan. It's built in Canada at a factory owned by Suzuki and
General Motors Corp. It's sold through U.S. Chevrolet dealers and
carries the Geo nameplate.
   For another example, a Mazda Motor Corp. plant in Flat Rock,
Mich., produces cars for Ford Motor Co.
   ``The Japanese certainly have provided a goad and it has been a
chance for us to learn some very good things that we have learned
to apply,'' Ford Chairman Donald Petersen said in a recent
interview.
   Each of the Big Three battled back to profitability during the
decade through new products, cost-cutting, union concessions and
government protection from imports.
   Chrysler's case was the most widely publicized. In 1980, the
federal government guaranteed loans to refloat the sinking
automaker. The corporation paid off the loans seven years early.
   ``We began the decade of the '80s by taking one risk that ran
against some of the most deeply ingrained economic ideals we hold
in this country and it was a huge success,'' Chrysler Chairman Lee
Iacocca said in a recent speech.
   Ford lost $1.54 billion in 1980 but it turned into the most
profitable automaker in history just eight years later when it
reported a $5.3 billion profit. GM began an ``Action Plan'' that
has a target of trimming $13 billion from its costs.
   Instead of reinvesting all their profits, the Big Three hedged
their bets by going into other businesses.
   General Motors Corp. acquired Electronic Data Systems Inc. in
October 1984 and Hughes Electronics Inc. in June 1985.
   Ford got into the banking business in December 1985 when it
acquired San Francisco-based First Nationwide Bank, which has
become the nation's second-largest savings and loan institution.
   Chrysler Corp. bought Gulfstream Aerospace in August 1985, two
years before it purchased American Motors Corp.
   Chrysler, for one, later decided it was spreading itself too
thin. Late in 1989, it announced plans to sell Gulfstream Aerospace
and its military electronics business to ``concentrate resources on
core car and truck operations.''
   Another ploy of the automakers had an unintended side effect.
The Big Three managed to obtain ``voluntary'' restraints on
Japanese imports, but that only drove the Japanese into building
plants in the United States. Those plants made cars even more
cheaply than the ones in Japan.
   Honda Motor Co. Ltd. spearheaded the Japanese manufacturing
assault on American soil when it began making Civics in Marysville,
Ohio, in November 1982. Since then, Nissan, Toyota, Mazda,
Mitsubishi, Subaru, Isuzu and Hyundai have set up assembly plants
either independently or in a joint venture with one of the Big
Three automakers.
   Those plants are adding to big problems for the industry as the
1990s get under way _ overcapacity and the potential for layoffs.
   The overcapacity that emerged in the 1980s seems certain to
worsen in the 1990s. The plants forced to close most likely won't
be the new Japanese-owned ones in white-dominated,
``right-to-work'' places like rural Tennessee and Kentucky. They'll
be the aging Big Three plants, mostly located in union strongholds
and employing a disproportionate share of minority workers.
   Under pressure from Japan, membership in the United Auto Workers
union dropped during the decade from about 1.5 million to just
under 1 million.
   While many things got blurry in the 1980s, the outlook for
old-line autoworkers became starkly clear.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
