<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Markets Adv00   12-11 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Markets, Adv 00,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wall Street Sent Pointed Messages in the '80s</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Money Decade of the 1980s brought both heady
success and egregious excess to Wall Street.
   The securities markets returned the favor by taking a hand in
setting the economic and political course of the decade for
American society.
   Stock traders celebrated the ascendance of deregulation,
technology and global investing with a historic bull market that
began in the summer of 1982 and reached new highs as late as the
autumn of 1989.
   ``It has been a very unusual bull market _ the longest we have
ever had in peacetime,'' said Raymond F. DeVoe Jr., a veteran
analyst at the firm of Legg Mason Wood Walker Inc.
   It outlasted several prominent participants, who by the end of
the decade were serving prison terms or banished from the business
for their parts in a series of scandals.
   In the ultimate test of its staying power, the bull market
survived the worst market drop in more than half a century _ the
crash of 1987 that culminated in Black Monday on Oct. 19 of that
year.
   Wall Street in the '80s was unfailingly controversial as well.
While the bull market signaled a seven-year period of economic
expansion that was welcomed by many business managers and
consumers, it was assailed by social critics as the emblem of an
age of materialism.
   Many Wall Streeters themselves decried the new computerized
trading techniques it helped spawn _ strategies like index
arbitrage and portfolio insurance that collectively came under the
label ``program trading.''
   Worst of all, said some, the boom on Wall Street was financed in
large part by a mountain of debt that might someday collapse with
devastating consequences.
   Still, with all their blemishes, the 1980s lived up to their
billing on the Street as ``the decade of financial assets.''
   Gone were the bouts of rapid inflation and rapidly rising
interest rates that depressed paper investments in the 1970s,
elevating in their place tangible assets such as gold and
collectibles.
   Stocks and bonds were back in favor as a way to participate in
the growth and resilience of the American economy.
   As they recovered their strength, the stock and bond markets
flexed their muscles, playing a newly prominent role in the shaping
of government policies affecting the economy.
   At the beginning of the 1980s, it was the bond market's turn to
play ``vigilante,'' acting as a kind of self-appointed surrogate
for the Federal Reserve by increasing interest rates each time its
traders sensed a new stirring of inflation.
   By the time of the 1987 crash, the stock market also had emerged
as a vigilante force, impelling central bankers to ease up on
credit conditions whenever it felt the threat of recession.
   The new breed of financial vigilante was quick to strike,
sending the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials down a record 508
points on Black Monday in 1987, and administering another 190-point
beating nearly two years later, on Oct. 13, 1989.
   Despite those rude interruptions, the net results for the decade
showed emphatic advances. The Dow Jones industrials, which started
the 1980s at 838.74, hovered near 2,700 in the waning weeks of the
decade.
   That kind of performance won't be easy to match in the 1990s.
For the average to triple again, it would have to climb past 8,000.
   Some observers see reason to hope for more good news. The
nation's labor force is likely to grow more slowly in the 1990s,
putting pressure on business to invest in greater amounts of
productivity-enhancing equipment, says Richard Peterson, chief
economist at Chicago's Continental Bank.
   ``The net effect of increasing investment in business equipment
will be a pattern of steady economic expansion through the 1990s,''
Peterson asserts.
   Nevertheless, many analysts wonder whether more unpleasant
shocks await a generation that grew up with the image of Wall
Street as inexhaustible horn of plenty.
   As DeVoe put it: ``An awful lot of people are being seduced to
the idea that we're never going to have another bear market again.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Computers Adv00   12-11 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Computers, Adv 00,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Personal Computers Went Hand-in-Hand With Capitalism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Diebold was in Paris in the late 1950s
talking about computers when a Russian stood up in the back of the
room and said computers were exactly what his country needed.
   Large computers would finally enable Soviet leaders to control
their economy according to plan, the Russian said.
   Don't be so sure, Diebold told the man. Computers can do a lot,
but they can't run an entire economy. Nothing can. Things are too
complex.
   That meeting in Paris more than 30 years ago foreshadowed two of
the most powerful developments of the 1980s: the rise of the
personal computer and the decline of centrally planned economies.
   Western democracies prospered in the '80s because power was in
the hands of the people. Personal computers helped by breaking the
tyranny of the corporate data center, where men in white coats had
doled out information to supplicants.
   Moscow's commissars feared personal computers as much as
printing presses. Their central computers were busy churning out
five-year plans. It didn't work for producing steel, and it worked
even less for producing ideas, the currency of the knowledge
economy that emerged in the '80s.
   ``They always thought that if they just got one more level of
sophistication in their equations, and in their models, that would
make the whole thing work. It didn't,'' said Diebold, a New
York-based consultant.
   Apple Computer Inc. recognized the personal computer's
revolutionary potential in a January 1984 commercial of a female
athlete throwing a mallet through an image of Big Brother.
   In the flash of the exploding screen, Apple announced the
Macintosh and promised, ``You'll see why 1984 won't be like
`1984.'''
   The personal computer was a phenomenon of the 1980s.
   While the pple II appeared in 1977, PCs didn't become a force in
the business world until IBM rolled out its first model in 1981.
After that, things happened quickly.
   In 1982, Lotus Development Corp. introduced 1-2-3, the
electronic spreadsheet that gave many people a reason to buy their
first computer. Compaq Computer Corp. introduced its first IBM
clone that year, and rose to the Fortune 500 faster than any
company in history.
   1984 was the year of the Macintosh as well as the first personal
computers from newly split-up AT&amp;T. In 1985, co-founder Steve Jobs
resigned from Apple. In 1987, IBM tried to distance itself from the
clone-makers with its Personal System-2 line. In 1989, Jobs
introduced a black magnesium cube of a workstation that he called
the ``Next.''
   PCs were the great levelers in the '80s. They let little guys
compete for business with big guys. Owners of PCs could dig facts
out of databases, analyze them and assemble them into
professional-looking documents _ all from a storefront office or a
corner of the bedroom.
   The leveling happened within the computer industry itself.
   For IBM, PCs threatened the fat profit margins it made on
minicomputers and mainframes.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. found that all the resources
of Bell Laboratories could not guarantee it success in the
fast-moving PC industry. In 1989, it ran ads portraying itself as a
David to the Goliath of Compaq _ a company not even founded a
decade earlier.
   The United States invented personal computers and used them in
the '80s more than any other nation, perhaps a reflection of the
go-it-alone spirit of Americans.
   Americans dominated production of PCs as well, but that may not
last for long. Japan gained control of most chips, screens and
other components and attained a solid position in laptop computers,
the fastest-growing portion of the market.
   Whether or not Japan takes over the PC industry in the '90s, the
critical issue will be which company, and which nation, uses
computers most intelligently.
   The wrong way is mindless number-crunching, which was all too
common in the '80s.
   ``You got a lot of people showing very elegant sets of figures
all worked out in great plans, but with the same sorts of lack of
judgment you would have had without the computer,'' said Diebold.
   To change that, personal computers in the '90s must be machines
for ideas, argues Marsh Fisher, an entrepreneur in Irvine, Calif.
   Society must learn to raise ideas as methodically as it raises
wheat, Fisher argues. He has sold Walt Disney Co. and others on a
program called IdeaFisher that prods people into making odd but
fruitful mental associations.
   ``The computer's been crunching numbers and word-processing very
neatly for a lot of years,'' Fisher said. ``Now we've got to move
it into expanding our mind.''
   That agenda is a natural for the American-born personal
computer. It is definitely not what the Russian in Paris had in
mind.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Products Adv00   12-11 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Products, Adv 00,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Products of '80s Stressed Convenience, Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Product makers in the 1980s let people have what
they wanted, even if it meant admitting a mistake.
   The revival of old Coke by popular demand told the story of the
decade. Consumers were masters of the economic universe and they
got exactly what they desired, from fax machines to oat bran.
   Convenience and specialization were hallmarks of '80s products.
   Microwave ovens had been available before the decade started,
but their popularity zoomed in the '80s as lower prices and more
compact construction helped make them indispensable fixtures in
American kitchens.
   Judith Langer, who heads her own New York-based market research
firm, said the machine eased the guilt some homemakers felt about
pursuing interests outside the home. The kids could easily fix
their own hot meals.
   Coca-Cola Co. upset some customers by changing the formula for
its flagship drink in 1985. The company said it listened to
consumer complaints and brought back the original as Coca-Cola
Classic three months later. The old standby soon regained status as
the best-selling soft drink, leaving analysts to wonder whether it
was all a publicity stunt.
   While the microwave oven made it easier to leave home, the 1980s
offered other products for those who didn't necessarily want to go
to the office.
   From the Timex Sinclair 1000 personal computer that debuted in
the early part of the decade through generations of IBM and Apple
models and the Compaq laptop, people had the tools to keep up and
figure things out for themselves at home.
   The trend toward self-sufficiency was accelerated with the
proliferation of cellular telephones and personal facsimile
machines.
   Well over half of American homes installed videocassette
recorders, giving people the freedom to do what they wanted and
still catch their favorite movies or programs on their terms.
Forget to set the timer? You can tune in the portable Sony Watchman
TV.
   Gannett Co. Inc. launched its national newspaper, USA Today, in
the 1980s and its colorful graphics and concise writing style
influenced other papers.
   In television, the mass media came under assault as cable
networks emerged and others went after narrow audiences. Rock music
fans got their MTV and the Financial News Network was launched.
Home shopping channels also debuted, peddling jewelry, porcelain
dolls and gadgets around the clock.
   Dozens of new financial products appeared in the 1980s,
including zero-coupon bonds, securities backed by payments on car
loans, bank money market accounts and futures trading based on
stock indexes.
   On the highways, Chrysler Corp. introduced minivans, cars like
Chevy Camaro and Pontiac Firebird livened up the dowdy state of
auto design and convertibles made a comback. But the gull-winged
DeLorean failed to fly (except in the movies), and the Yugo from
Eastern Europe quickly ran out of gas.
   California Coolers started a rush to concocting alcoholic
beverages for the adults who grew up on fizzy drinks, but the rage
soon went flat. Anheuser-Busch Cos. introduced LA, a low-alcohol
beer that has lagged despite the trend toward moderation and health.
   The health craze created the environment for $100 sneakers from
Nike and Reebok and a revival of demand for oatmeal with its
reputed cholesterol-lowering abilities.
   If the 1980s left you stressed, you could take some consolation
from another product of the decade _ the pain reliever ibuprofen
was approved for sale without prescription.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-People Adv00-2Takes   12-11 0940</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-People, Adv 00-2 Takes,0978</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eight Who Shaped the Business '80s</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES M. KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan, Volcker, Milken, Pickens, Lorenzo, Iacocca, Morita and
Jobs.
   Of the scores who played leading roles in business and finance
during the decade, these are eight who shaped the '80s.
   When asked to name the great business leaders of the decade,
Associated Press business writers produced a list of more than 30,
including some inanimate objects like the junk bond and one obvious
group, the Japanese.
   But some individuals stood out, their contributions so familiar
that the mere mention of their last names nearly tells their
stories.
   These are eight who set the tone. Eight who personify the most
important themes of the last 10 years _ free markets, corporate
restructuring, economic transformation and global competitiveness.
   Two of the eight, former President Reagan and ex-Federal Reserve
Chairman Paul Volcker, orchestrated events at the macroeconomic
level, molding an economy of steady growth and low inflation.
   Michael Milken, T. Boone Pickens and Frank Lorenzo exploited the
times, blazing trails and building fortunes in Reagan's unfettered
marketplace.
   Lee Iacocca and Akio Morita performed business miracles on
opposite ends of the earth and emerged as national as well as
corporate standard-bearers.
   Steve Jobs, as a singular sensation, proved a reassuring
reminder that no matter how much change the 1980s wrought,
individual creativity was still the most valuable commodity for
sale in America.
   Below are brief reflections on the marks these eight left behind:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Reagan and Volcker: Two Most Powerful</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reagan was dubbed the great communicator, but he was an even
greater deregulator and free enterpriser, who dedicated his
two-term presidency to restoring America's capitalist fervor.
   He will be remembered for his good fortune _ he got a recession
out of the way at the beginning of his tenure _ and for maximizing
his opportunities. In the midst of the downturn, he won approval
for big tax cuts that launched the longest peacetime expansion in
U.S. history.
   He held two economic tenets dear: Taxes should be cut and the
federal bureaucracy should be trimmed. Because he proved a better
tax cutter than program pruner, the Reagan boom created a
burgeoning federal budget deficit that kept interest rates
inordinately high even as the economy expanded.
   Plugging the holes in Reaganomics fell to Volcker, who
controlled the money supply _ and thus interest rates _ with the
perspective of a tortoise to Reagan's hare.
   Where all the president's men saw growth, the apostate Volcker
smelled inflation and resolved to keep a grip on monetary policy
even as Reaganites jawboned for easier credit.
   For his steadfastness, the Fed chairman earned the unofficial
title of ``second most powerful man in America.'' Oddly, Volcker
was never seen as a political threat to the president, perhaps
because his tight-money policies kept the worst excesses of the
Reagan revolution in check.
   Reagan's appeal was founded in his bold pursuit of ideals at the
expense of opposing interests. Executives admired his guts when he
fired the striking air controllers in 1981; labor leaders never
forgave him.
   Volcker, too, was somewhat of an idealist, but he had bitter
medicine for all to swallow, consumers and fat cats alike.
   Volcker put restrictions on business in the form of tight
credit. Reagan dismantled government regulation at every turn.
   Reagan invited all businesses to the party; Volcker and his
inflation-fighting successor, Alan Greenspan, were the designated
drivers.
   Putting an ironic twist on an old Donald Regan saw: Reagan could
not have been Reagan, if Volcker hadn't been Volcker. The
expansion, still intact after seven years, would not have been as
powerful or as enduring without the countervailing forces of
Reagan's whip and Volcker's tug on the reins.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Milken, Pickens, Lorenzo: The New Capitalists</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   By reviving laissez faire as a guiding principle of government,
Reagan set the stage for a new brand of capitalist in 1980s.
Government scrutiny was out; wheeling and dealing was in.
   Milken, Pickens and Lorenzo became giants, not by inheritance or
formal succession to the chief executive's office, but by taking
full advantage of the market's new freedoms.
   They didn't develop any new products; they employed old tools to
new ends.
   Milken, a bond trader, took high-risk corporate bonds off the
junk heap and created a $200 billion market for debt financing.
   Pickens, an oilman, showed how to hit gushers in the stock
market by snapping up the shares of companies undervalued in
comparison to their assets.
   Lorenzo, a Harvard MBA with a fascination for flying, assembled
the nation's biggest airline empire under the banner of Texas Air
by buying up deregulated carriers and busting unions.
   Sympathetic biographers would label all three self-made me, but
they were not the sort of cuddly entrepreneurs Americans
instinctively embrace. Indeed their greatest successes prompted
more cocked eyebrows than applause.
   Milken was indicted for securities fraud. Pickens was branded a
``raider.'' Lorenzo, after flying two airlines into bankruptcy and
putting hundreds of union employees out of work, became known as
one of America's toughest bosses.
   As three of the greatest risk-takers of the age, each was
stalked as much as he hunted his own prey. But they were
characteristically unbowed by challenge or criticism.
   Lorenzo, a recent magazine profile noted, survived on the
conviction of his own rightness. So, Milken in the face of his 1990
trial. So, Pickens in his raids, most recently on a Japanese
company.
   Lorenzo's comment when he bought Eastern Airlines in 1986 was
typical of the threesome's sober acceptance of controversy.
   ``There ain't no Santa Claus,'' he told a news conference.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
