<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-People Adv00-1stAdd   12-11 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-People, Adv 00-1st Add,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ... news conference.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iacocca and Morita: National Symbols</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Iacocca and Morita were tough guys with a better press. They
attracted enemies, but managed their images with aplomb. As a
result, they became instant national symbols.
   The Chrysler Corp. chairman got a billion-dollar bailout from
the federal government as the decade opened, but paid the debt in
1983, seven years ahead of schedule. To flaunt the extraordinary
payback, he held a lavish press conference where he stood before a
mammoth blowup of a check for $800 million, the company's final
payment.
   His success at Chrysler, after being fired from Ford Motor Co.
in 1978, was as much a personal victory as a corporate one. He
personally sold Congress on the bailout and became the company's
main pitchman for K-cars and minivans in national television
commercials.
   Exposure was his magic wand. When he was fired from the Statue
of Liberty restoration committee in a political snit in 1986, he
wrapped himself in the flag and called the ouster ``un-American.''
Most Iacocca fans agreed.
   Morita, the Sony Corp. chairman, became the Japanese answer to
Iacocca, but with an even tougher PR challenge. Besides selling
himself and his company, he had to sell a whole nation of
aggressive capitalists to skeptical Americans.
   A natural salesman and communicator in the Iacocca mold, Morita
seemed to sense what was needed to salve old postwar sores.
   After Sony bought CBS Records in 1987, he hugged recording star
Cyndi Lauper for a magazine cover photo, symbolically embracing the
culture. When Sony bought Columbia Pictures this fall, he paid
millions to get the services of a pair of American producers, Peter
Guber and Jon Peters, creators of hits ``Batman'' and ``Rain Man.''
   And, of course, Sony kept churning out gizmos for American
consumers. Who could hate a guy bringing a Video Walkman to market
just in time for Christmas?
   Morita was no softy: He frequently criticized short-term
thinking in the United States and co-wrote a book discussing the
``decline of America.'' But when the book provoked a backlash in
Congress, he apologized for promoting nationalistic views.
   The secret to the success of stars like Morita and Iacocca was
their political sensitivity and their mastery of the media. Few
business leaders of the age stood as tall outside the boardroom or
the plant.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Jobs: Thirtysomething Entrepreneur</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One man combined popular allure with real genius: Steve Jobs. He
was the American dream updated to the '80s. The garage inventor who
struck it rich. A thirtysomething Horatio Alger.
   In a sense Jobs was the consummate business leader of the
decade. He was young. He invented computers, the machine of the
age. He walked away from a very successful company just to start
another one.
   He built the Apple Computer Inc. empire only to leave it in 1985
after introducing one of the hottest computer boxes of the decade,
the Macintosh. Jobs left the company in a dispute with John
Sculley, a veteran businessman whom Jobs himself had recruited to
help run his growing firm.
   What mattered most to Jobs was not running a company, but
creating hot boxes. His subsequent creation, the product of a few
wizards' work, was appropriately labeled ``Next.''
   His trademark long hair sometimes gave way to a yuppie trim, and
he seemed to enjoy the panache of bow ties and designer suits as
much as his faded blue jeans. But there was no mistaking what he
represented.
   As the rebellious youth beating the old capitalist establishment
at its own game, Jobs provided a fitting symbol for a decade that
followed the '70s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
