<SECOND>BC-Decade-Success Story, Adv 00,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Success Story for the '80s: Dayton Hudson's Lauderback</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been 10 years since Brenda Lauderback
hurdled society's gender and racial barriers to win her first
corporate management job with the nation's fifth-largest retailing
company.
   From a retail training program at a Gimbles department store in
Pittsburgh, she arrived at Dayton Hudson Department Store Co. in
Minneapolis in 1975 as a merchandise buyer.
   Five years later, she emerged as the division head for intimate
apparel and has since risen into company officer ranks as the
general manager for shoes, cosmetics, accessories and intimate
apparel _ the first black woman to hold such a post at the $1.7
billion subsidiary of Dayton Hudson Corp.
   ``It showed me that your dreams can become reality and I knew it
was just the beginning,'' Lauderback said of her big promotion in
1980.
   In a decade noted for the pursuit of money, Lauderback is among
the hard-chargers who poured productive energy into the longest
peacetime economic expansion in U.S. history. Her career also
stands out among the thousands of women who entered the work force
and moved up the corporate ladder in the '80s.
   Since 1982 Lauderback has consistently met or surpassed sales
goals for her $440 million division, and earlier this year she was
invited to join the Committee of 200 _ an elite national group of
women executives.
   Lauderback and her husband, Dr. Boyd Wright, a St. Paul dentist,
are fixtures in the Twin Cities establishment. They have a
``status'' house in the exclusive suburb of Edina, an investment
professional to help manage their income, a live-in caretaker with
a master's degree in education to nurture their 4-year-old
daughter, Phallon, and plenty of money to vacation.
   If only they had more time.
   Lauderback said she's on the road up to 40 percent of the year,
including trips to Europe and the Orient. Her work week can easily
mount to 60 hours.
   Hence the decision 2{ years ago to hire Lauderback's college
friend, Nancy Bryant, to help care for Phallon.
   ``It was when the pressures were getting real tight,''
Lauderback said. ``She came to help us in managing our family and
our future.''
   Lauderback said the frenzy of meshing her career with motherhood
has prompted some to put her in the category of superwoman. But she
detests the label for the expectations it carries.
   ``I don't want that superwoman cape,'' she said. ``I'm like
every other woman. I do the best I can.''
   Stephen E. Watson, chairman of Dayton Hudson Department Store
Co., summed up Lauderback's reputation in two words: ``High
energy.''
   Raised in the Pittsburgh suburb of Penn Hills by a mother who
worked as a beautician and a father who drove a truck, Lauderback
said she was warned not to give up on her goals in the face of
racism or other adversity. Her father's tombstone reads: ``I may
give out, but I'll never give up.''
   ``I've had to succeed in a white world,'' Lauderback said. ``But
there has never been a doubt to anyone of who I am.''
   Despite lofty job offers from the outside, Lauderback said she
is content for now to stay with the 37-store Dayton Hudson chain.
   Harking back to her promotion at the start of the '80s, she said
she has the best of several worlds: A job, paycheck and family she
loves.
   ``I felt like I was on a cloud then and I have stayed on that
cloud for quite a while.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
