<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-TroubledFarmer Adv00   12-11 0895</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Troubled Farmer, Adv 00,0925</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Victims of the '80s: The Farming Kilcoins</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADAIR, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Kilcoin, a victim of the farm
depression of the 1980s, says losing his farm and seeing someone
else work the land was ``like watching someone else live with your
wife.''
   It was Oct. 19, 1987 _ a day known as ``Black Monday'' on Wall
Street half a continent away _ that Kilcoin signed the deed of his
farm over to the Federal Land Bank. Some of that land had been in
his family for three generations.
   The 440-acre corn, cattle and hog operation in the rolling hills
of west central Iowa, not far from the spot where Jesse James is
reputed to have staged the first train robbery in the West, became
another statistic in a faltering agricultural economy.
   ``The land is kind of attached to you. It's kind of like losing
your arm,'' said Kilcoin.
   His wife, Jackie, interrupted, saying, ``No, it's more like
losing your heart.''
   Kilcoin and his wife say that after 20 straight years of making
payments, they failed to meet a $35,000 annual mortgage installment
in 1985 because new management at a local bank refused to continue
a long-standing operating loan arrangement.
   ``We thought we had the operating money for the year put
together. A couple of weeks before we needed it, we found we didn't
have it,' he said.
   Kilcoin says it was a shift in inflation policy and resulting
high interest rates that did him in.
   In the 1970s, ``It was a common belief that inflation always
would be with us,'' said Neil Harl, an Iowa State University
professor and expert on agricultural economics.
   Inflationary expectations drove farmland values sky high, which
boosted the borrowing power of farmers, who used that asset as
collateral for loans.
   But the Federal Reserve's move to fight inflation with tighter
credit in 1979 drove interest rates to record heights and sent land
values tumbling. At the same time, a rising dollar made U.S. grain
and meat more expensive in foreign markets, cutting into farmers'
traditional export earnings.
   Drought hit in 1983, and Kilcoin says he never did catch up.
   Net cash farm income in Iowa, the difference between cash
earnings and cash expenses and a gauge of the money available to
repay debts or invest in operations or savings, sank from about
$2.7 billion in 1981 to around $1.6 billion in 1984.
   Farmland values in Iowa plummeted 71 percent from 1980 to 1987
after adjusting for inflation, according to the Federal Reserve
Bank of Chicago, a plunge even steeper than the 61 percent
inflation-adjusted slump of 1916-1942. The slide eroded the
security backing up loans held by the Kilcoins and others.
   ``We had a profit but interest rates ate up all profits and we
had to borrow money just to pay the interest rates,'' Kilcoin said
in a discussion at the table in a kitchen that has a 20-year-old
stove, a used refrigerator and a dishwasher bought for $6 in a
garage sale in the 1970s. ``It wasn't that we weren't making money;
we weren't making enough money.''
   Now 51, Kilcoin has learned a new trade, making engine bearings.
He has become a commuter who has time for his children only on
weekends and goes to community college one day a week.
   ``I still walk though the door (at work) and the door shuts
behind me and I think, `Is this really me?'''
   He's far from alone in his plight, despite the rebound in the
agricultural economy as the decade ended, with Iowa net cash farm
income shooting up to nearly $3.9 billion in 1987 and then settling
to $3.4 billion last year.
   ``The people I work with are the same people _ either they are
my age, farmed and lost or young people who wished they could farm
but can't,'' Kilcoin said.
   His wife, 49, works at home assembling small parts for car and
truck chassis for the Illinois Tool Works, earning about $200 a
week _ enough to meet payments on a used minivan and buy the
groceries.
   But before those jobs materialized, it was touch and go for the
family with three married daughters and a 13-year-old girl and
6-year-old boy at home.
   For two years the couple did not know if they would keep their
home, and Larry says he told his wife he was ready to leave the
United States if he lost the house.
   But the Kilcoins negotiated to buy back the home and 13{ acres
that surround it.
   They refused to declare bankruptcy and Jackie Kilcoin says, ``we
will be paying the rest of our lives on our debt.''
   Butnow, things are more settled.
   ``I don't have to worry about the phone ringing any more. I
don't have to be afraid of going to the mailbox,'' Mrs. Kilcoin
said.
   The couple still keeps a hand in farming, too. They fatten about
600 hogs for market under contract for a Chicago feedlot. They also
own 18 head of cattle.
   Kilcoin still has worries, including fears for his country,
which he sees overburdened by debt _ just as farmers were at the
start of the decade.
   ``That puts them in the position I was,'' he said. ``Who shuts
down the government?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
