<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-BusinessBooks Adv00   12-11 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Business Books, Adv 00,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Biz Books Boomed in '80s, But Was There Wisdom in Volumes of Advice?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They wrote the book on business in the 1980s
_ over and over and over, until it seemed there were fewer
executives than authors telling them how to succeed.
   Choose your approach: Management by walking around. The flat
organization. Quality circles (actually a holdover from the 1970s).
Zero defects. How ``soft'' management skills create ``hard''
business results.
   ``How to Give Good Phone'' was an offering from Lisa Collier
Cool, ``Ed McMahon's Superselling'' a tome by the Carson sidekick
and Alpo pitchman.
   The scene for all this was set in 1982 by Thomas J. Peters' and
Robert H. Waterman Jr.'s ``In Search of Excellence,'' which proved
that critically well-received management books can also be
money-makers.
   Then came ``Iacocca,'' followed by a string of best-sellers in
the mid-'80s _ ``Megatrends,'' ``The One Minute Manager,'' ``What
They Don't Teach You at the Harvard Business School.''
   ``Those three books sold between 500,000 and 1.5 million copies
each, which was unheard of,'' said business book editor Harriet
Rubin.
   The floodgates opened.
   ``Publishing is definitely a follow-the-leader business, and
when something works they jump on the bandwagon,'' said Jim Miliot,
editor of the B.P. Report, a publishing newsletter in White Plains,
N.Y.
   ``Intrapreneuring.'' ``Thriving on Chaos.'' ``You Are the
Message.'' ``Corporate Cultures.'' ``Leadership Secrets of Attila
the Hun.''
   Miliot said the books fit right in during the '80s, with
``Reagan, the business-is-great attitude and free enterprise at its
best.''
   But were they worth reading?
   ``Most of these books are shallow, insipid and stupid,'' said
Peter F. Drucker, the longtime business consultant and writer
called the ``Dr. Spock for generations of American business
managers'' by Business Week.
   ``Everyone was trying to emulate Tom Peters,'' Drucker, 80, the
author of 24 books, said in a telephone interview from his home in
Claremont, Calif.
   Ms. Rubin, the book editor, agrees most of the books are ``dull
and they're badly written.''
   ``People were buying them, but they sort of used them as
intellectual wallpaper, or on the desk as a placebo,'' she said.
   But unlike Drucker, she thinks there's a market for yet more
business books in the 1990s.
   In fact, Doubleday has hired her as executive editor of a whole
new line, Doubleday-Currency books advertised as being dedicated to
business ``thinkers, not just doers,'' who ``rebel against the
status quo.''
   ``Who today can start a fire in our minds?'' Ms. Rubin writes in
publicity material for the books.
   ``The Iacoccas succeeded in the old world of hierarchy,
authority, and control, which has less relevance today.''
   According to Ms. Rubin, ``The new hot button is no longer
`entrepreneur' or `executive' but `change agent.' That
revolutionary is our ideal reader.''
   ``Business people would buy `In Search of Excellence,' `Thriving
on Chaos' and `Leadership Secrets of Attila the Hun,''' Ms. Rubin
said in a telephone interview from New York.
   ``But the books they would actually read ... were in the
sciences, philosophy, pop culture,'' she said. ``They were trying
to make sense of complex lives.''
   The flagship publication of the new line is ``Leadership Is an
Art'' by Max DePree, chief executive of the Herman Miller Co.
furniture makers, out this fall and already in its fifth printing
with 65,000 copies in print.
   ``It's the opposite of `Confessions of an S.O.B.,' or
`Leadership Secrets of Attila the Hun,''' said Doubleday
spokeswoman Jacqueline Deval.
   ``His leadership principles are based on a concern for the
health and welfare of the people working for you,'' Ms. Deval said.
``And not just for the sake of being kinder or gentler, but for
overall profitability as well, the bottom line.''
   Drucker, the dean of the management gurus, likes DePree's book
but hopes the business-book fad as a whole gets laid to rest.
   ``The boom is over _ I hope,'' Drucker said glumly. ``But I've
been saying that for two years now and I've been wrong so far.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-MBAs Adv00   12-11 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-MBAs, Adv 00,0878</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the '80s, Reaching for the Brass Ring Required a MBA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To those who received MBAs in 1981, Wall Street
beckoned like a siren's song.
   Although a recession gripped the nation, the securities industry
and investment banks were on their way to reshaping American
businesses _ and they were hiring legions of fresh MBAs to do the
job.
   Takeovers, restructurings and stock and bond offerings became
fortune-making vehicles for an army of young people. Tales of
23-year-olds with $300,000 salaries plus bonuses abounded and lured
flocks of people to the nation's business schools.
   But what a difference a decade makes.
   These days, New York's financial district is quiet and
depressed. Tens of thousands of people were let go following the
Oct. 19, 1987, market collapse. The stock market's unsettling
volatility this fall has hurt new hiring plans.
   ``No new people are coming into the securities industry,'' said
Susan Perkins, an '81 New York University MBA grad and vice
president at the investment research boutique of Gerard Klauer
Mattison &amp; Co.
   Lucrative fees from megadeals withered this year as the dollar
volume of takeovers slumped 28 percent from 1988's heady pace,
according to Securities Data Corp. Investment houses have scaled
back commissions and shut entire departments to save money. Some
estimate bonuses will be trimmed by as much as 30 percent this year.
   The big salaries that deal people commanded during '80s ``were
clearly out of line _ and they still are,'' said Randall Rochman, a
vice president at Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. in Chicago and 1981 MBA
graduate of Northwestern University's Kellogg School.
   Starting salaries for MBAs doubled over the course of the
decade. NYU's Stern School said the average salary for grads
entering all facets of business was $26,936 in 1981; the average
broke the $50,000 mark this year.
   (The cost of getting the degree has nearly tripled at some
schools. Harvard University is charging $30,700 for the two-year
MBA course that cost $9,600 in 1981.)
   A recent NYU survey shows male 1979 MBA grads are averaging
$122,600 a year while their female classmates are making $87,200 on
average. And the respondents _ 143 of out of 665 alumni polled _
have averaged three promotions since leaving NYU.
   But for those hitting the pavement in 1991, the degree that once
opened doors could become an impediment at some job interviews.
Some speculate that with scrutiny of the bottom line, employers may
not readily embrace the high-priced grad clutching a master's of
business administration degree.
   ``People think the MBA is a ticket to a higher life,'' said
Scott Corwin, 31, chief operating officer at the Princeton, N.J.,
consulting firm Caliper Management Inc.
   ``Sure, they are averaging higher salaries, but in the end it
comes down to what an individual makes of an opportunity,'' said
Corwin, an '81 NYU grad.
   As Wall Street loses its allure, more grads are seeking to work
for America's corporations, and companies are carving out a greater
presence on campuses recruiting students.
   Kim Avison, 24, expects to put in 60-hour weeks in sales or
marketing for a major consumer products corporation when she
graduates in 1991 from Dartmouth University's Amos Tuck School of
Business.
   At Columbia University, MBA candidate Tim Newman, 25, said he
wouldn't be surprised if the nation slips into a recession shortly
after he graduates, but he says those who develop highly specific
skills will fare well.
   Newman hopes to become involved in investment management for a
university or charity endowment when he graduates in 1991, a far
cry from investment banking.
   If the business climate sours in the coming decade, as many
believe it will, the class of '91 ``may not have been taught, as we
weren't, how to deal with it,'' Caliper's Corwin said.
   He credits the hard economic times of the early '80s for
teaching him more about running a business than business school
ever did. ``It's much easier to manage when there's growth,'' said
Corwin, who noted that his consulting firm lost a third of its
business between 1981 and 1982.
   Current students say money is not their primary concern. ``If
you work hard, the money will come,'' Avison said.
   But one recent Ivy League grad countered that ``making money is
an essential consideration, particularly for those attending
expensive private schools.''
   Still, financial rewards come at a high price. Long hours,
broken marriages and a distorted sense of values typified business
of the '80s.
   ``I have seen what is probably a higher incidence of divorce in
our industry, I suspect because people are trying to reach for the
brass ring,'' Rochman said.
   ``The spirit of Reagan's presidency was one of hands-off,
unfettered pursuit of wealth, even greed,'' said Richard Fisher,
37, a vice president at CS First Boston, though he believes the
nation is begining to focus on more social concerns.
   If there is one axiom that holds true, it is, in Perkins' words,
that ``the business world was tough, and it still is.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
