<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Europe Adv00   12-11 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Europe, Adv 00,0892</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet's Dramatic Push for Western-Style Economy Marks Decade</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was almost unimaginable. The West's
most prominent banker jetting to Moscow to advise the archenemy of
capitalism.
   But Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan recently made such a
trip, a sign of the extraordinary changes that marked the '80s
overseas.
   It was a decade marked by the pursuit of a formula for economic
success, a drive that brought about wrenching changes. The big
winners were the most modern, complex and open economies. Far down
on the list were those dependent on natural resources and those
with closed, controlled systems.
   In Eastern Europe, some countries took their first, halting
steps toward Western-style economies and integration into the world
economy.
   In Western Europe, the European Community finally took seriously
its decision to fashion a single market of the dozen nations by
1992.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries went on a
roller-coaster ride that carried oil prices to wild levels before
crashing and finally recovering.
   Africa was caught up in the foreign debt crisis that swept the
world's developing nations in the early 1980s, sapping their
economic strength and impoverishing their growing populations even
more.
   In Europe, the events that captured the imagination, that seemed
least likely at the start of the decade, stemmed from the Soviets'
tacit acknowledgement that their economic system had failed.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, who came to power in March
1985, pressed his perestroika program to restructure the backward
economy, trying to wrench it from centrally planned ways to a more
market-oriented system.
   There was talk of price reform and private enterprise, more
consumer goods and fewer government subsidies.
   ``There can be no return to the old style of economic
management,'' asserted Vladimir Shemiatenkov, Moscow's envoy to the
European Community.
   But Gorbachev's task remains staggering. Inflation is high and
so is the government's budget deficit. Millions have been thrown
out of work by the modernization efforts. Workers strike and
consumers grumble.
   ``They don't have a decent economic reform program yet,'' said
Jan Vanous of PlanEcon, a Washington forecasting firm.
   Despite the daunting challenge, reform fever is spreading in
Eastern Europe, particularly Hungary, long a leader of economic
reform in the communist bloc, and Poland, where the new Solidarity
leadership plans to move swiftly to a market economy.
   East Germany, once one of the most conservative members of the
Soviet bloc, joined the rush. West Germany offered massive
financial aid in return for stepped-up economic and political
reforms.
   The European Community quickly negotiated broad trade and
economic cooperation agreements with Poland and Hungary and a
smaller pact with Czechoslovakia. Deals also were pursued with the
Kremlin and East Germany.
   Among the Western powers, a wealth of proposals were offered for
reaching their goal of a European-wide market by 1992. In contrast
to the new freedoms symbolized by the crumbling Berlin wall, the
1992 preparations were characterized by heated disagreements over
ways to dismantle the barriers separating the Common Market allies.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher clashed with others in
their vision of Europe's future. She fought proposals to create a
common currency and central bank system, fearing a loss of
sovereignty.
   ``Britain's destiny lies in Europe,'' argued Nigel Lawson, whose
October resignation as Britain's top treasury official rocked the
government. He urged Mrs. Thatcher to relent and link the pound to
Europe's other major currencies.
   The linkage system, the exchange rate mechanism of the European
Monetary System, has brought the economies more in line, analysts
say.
   With the opening of borders between the Germanys, concern was
raised that the Bonn government would forsake the West for the
East. Government officials hastily insisted they were with the
European Community.
   The United States aggressively monitored the community's 1992
campaign, complaining of any moves to keep its products out of the
new marketplace. The term ``Fortress Europe'' was coined. Europeans
denied protectionism was afoot.
   For OPEC, the decade was trying.
   The 1979 revolution in Iran, a major oil-producing nation, was
marked by a sharp drop in crude production. World oil prices soared
above $40 a barrel, shocking the economies of the United States and
other industrialized nations.
   In late 1985, the cartel shifted strategy to defend its ``fair
share'' of the world oil market. A production free-for-all sent
prices crashing. Futures prices for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark American crude, plunged to near $10 a barrel in March
1986.
   Toward the decade's end, OPEC pulled itself together. Key
members Iran and Iraq, at war most of the decade, resolved some
differences, and the cartel as a whole became less confrontational
with consuming nations. Demand for the cartel's oil grew, and
prices rebounded to around $20 per barrel.
   In Africa, the '80s were years of unrelieved misery.
   ``Sub-Saharan Africa as a whole has now witnessed almost a
decade of falling per-capita incomes, increasing hunger and
accelerating ecological degradation,'' according to a World Bank
report.
   Problems afflicting the region of 450 million people include low
foreign investment, weak export sales, growing populations,
increasing debt and poor agricultural and industrial performance.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
