<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Asia Adv00   12-11 0976</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Asia, Adv 00,1004</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Japan Excels Economically; ``Four Tigers'' in Pursuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a decade of Asian economic success, Japan piled
up No. 1 labels, four other countries gained the nickname
``tigers,'' and the star performers amassed more money to fuel
their advance into the 1990s.
   The standouts lack abundant natural resources, but have
governments that encourage private business. They share a Confucian
ethic stressing education, hard work and thrift. High savings rates
have helped pay for new and better production facilities.
   Dependence on exports forced factories to hone efficiencies
needed to compete in the international marketplace. Government
steps to hold down inflation promoted confidence and stability.
   Success in the frontrunners _ including ``tigers'' South Korea,
Taiwan, Hong Kong and Singapore _ helped pull up some of the
followers, like Thailand and Malaysia, both by example and by
expanding trade and investment.
   Asia's giant, China, also tried stressing a diligence-thrift
ethic to make its 1 billion people more productive and less poor,
but lacked the incentives of its neighbors' free-market economies
and their managerial skills and education levels. Amid scarcities,
spending on construction and efforts to live better ended up
overheating the economy.
   War impoverished Vietnam and Cambodia, although Vietnam ended
the decade by withdrawing what it said were its last troops in
Cambodia and trying to free its economy from some of the strictures
of central planning.
   The Philippines, amid a intensifying political crisis, struggled
with a legacy of foreign debt from the rule of the late President
Ferdinand Marcos, whose businessmen associates came to rely more on
favors than initiative.
   Japan struggled with problems of the rich as its high exports
and high-profile acquisitions abroad aroused resentment. It became
the world's largest creditor in 1985 and the rise of the yen
inflated its international financial power.
   In 1987, the economic newspaper Nihon Keizai Shimbun calculated
that Japan had become the world's richest nation on paper, with
$43.7 trillion in total assets such as land, factories and stock,
compared with U.S. assets of $36.2 trillion.
   The inflated wealth, plus Japan's high savings rate and its
industries' new ability to finance their own investments, gave
Japanese banks the funds to become major players in world finance.
Japanese purchases of corporations and property in the United
States became a sensitive issue, although Americans continued
seeking Japanese investment.
   The abundance of funds in Japan's stock markets also has given
its corporations access to low-cost financing that U.S. companies
cannot match.
   American corporations with access to such funds likely would be
tempted to try to buy out a competitor, said Eric Rasmussen, an
economist at Jardine Fleming Securities in Tokyo, while Japanese
firms tend to focus on productive capacity.
   ``Come 1991 or 1992, life could get very exciting for U.S.
companies. They are going to emerge from a period of sluggish
growth and long recuperation ... confronted with a flood of
high-quality Japanese exports,'' he said.
   This will be a result of Japanese companies' strong balance
sheets rather than an overall national strategy, he said.
   In Taiwan, too, ``companies used to rely on banks as their main
source of funds. Now they can raise more money from the stock
market and don't have to worry about banks withdrawing loans in
case of an economic slowdown,'' said Yeh Chih-yung, vice president
of Capital Securities Co.
   Officials said many of the 170 listed companies have used such
funds to automate equipment and make more sophisticated products to
overcome the impact of the rising Taiwan dollar.
   In Japan, the yen's rise since 1985 forced a major change in
mid-decade, from reliance on exports to depending on the home
market to fuel economic growth.
   But despite their country's image, most Japanese don't feel
rich, says Isamu Miyazaki, chairman of the Daiwa Institute of
Research.
   He cited workdays exceeding those in the West by perhaps 600
hours a year; cramped housing and long commutes through congested
traffic; and prices that, while stable, exceed other industrialized
nations' by 20 percent to 30 percent. These result from government
protection of agriculture and an inefficient distribution system,
he said.
   In South Korea, Kim Yong, director of the Economic Planning
Board, said curbs on government budgets and wage raises kept annual
inflation between 2.3 percent and 7.1 percent, down from more than
15 percent in the previous decade. The government also encouraged
competition to sharpen efficiency, and stressed technical
renovation. Labor unrest has erupted in Korea over the last year,
however.
   In China, rural production improved as the government ended
factory-style commune farming and gave families a chance to do some
of their own marketing and use spare time for sideline business.
   But in the state-run factories, efforts to boost productivity
faced the ``iron rice bowl,'' a system of lifetime employment in
which workers are paid the same regardless of labor performed.
   After cracking down on the democracy movement in June, the
Communist Party promoted leaders favoring order and central
planning over giving wider play to market forces.
   The next two largest Asian nations _ India and Indonesia _ also
lag in education, with Indonesia's literacy rate at 26 percent and
India's at 36 percent.
   The World Bank has given Indonesia high marks in recent years
for boosting growth by encouraging the private sector with improved
incentives and deregulation, and moving to shift the economy away
from heavy reliance on oil exports.
   India's government has favored state planning in efforts to
reduce income inequalities and promote rapid industrialization, but
analysts say this inward-looking policy has hurt efficiency and
growth.
   Australia, which looks toward Asia in its economic activity,
shares its more successful neighbors' free-market economy and high
education level, but its economic performance depends more than
theirs on prices for commodities. Its major exports include coal
and farm products.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
