<DOCNO> AP891211-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Analysis Adv00   12-11 1146</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Analysis, Adv 00,1173</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rewards of the Money Decade Weren't Equally Shared</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a common theme throughout the '80s, at
the dinner table, in academic papers, White House discussions,
political controversies, international debates. The subject was
money, and it was on everyone's mind.
   Money was the biggest economic puzzle of the decade, for those
who made an awful lot of it, for those who fell far behind in their
material well being, and for those who simply struggled to keep
pace.
   If wealth wasn't discussed, it was poverty; if not inflation,
then the threat of it; if not immediate monthly bills, then the
prospect that Social Security and private insurance plans wouldn't
take care of one's old age.
   Uncle Sam worried about a huge and growing federal deficit and a
trade imbalance that threatened America's global economic
leadership.
   Banks worried. The nation's big commercial institutions had made
billions of dollars in loans to the Third World, and it had become
apparent those loans might never be repaid. Late in the decade, the
banks began writing them off, or setting aside reserves for that
possibility.
   Business worried. A new definition of debt took hold. It meant
that enormous amounts of money borrowed at extremely high interest
rates was now an accepted method of financing corporations. Company
after company was threatened with takeover by raiders armed with
billions of dollars in such credit.
   Investors worried about the stock market. The Dow Jones
industrial average pierced new levels, poking above the 2,700 mark
in 1987 and again in 1989, but the market suffered its worst
collapse in half a century on Black Monday.
   In spite of the huge runup, those 2,700 points didn't represent
a new high in real terms. Adjusted for inflation the Dow hit its
all-time high way back in January 1966. To match that high, the
1989 Dow would have had to reach 3,900 points.
   Buyers, sellers and owners of housing worried, too, as variable
rate mortgages rose into the double digits and then descended
toward single numbers late in the decade. Real estate taxes
generally rose as well. A big income tax cut was passed to roaring
acclaim early in the decade, but almost every dollar saved as a
result of it was nibbled away by piecemeal increases that followed.
   Ordinary Americans never were relieved of money worries. While
all those big billions were talked about, average hourly earnings
of many Americans grew little in the 1980s. Aspirations didn't _
they kept rising _ and as a result consumer debt did also.
Unsolicited bank-card credit became available in the thousands of
dollars to millions of Americans who, just a decade earlier,
wouldn't have qualified for personal loans at a fraction of the
amounts.
   The unevenness persisted throughout the decade, beginning in one
of the worst recessions of the century, accompanied by what
President Carter referred to as a malaise of the American spirit.
   A new president helped lift spirits, talking a free-enterprise
language based in faith that what the country needed was a release
of the pent-up energies of Americans _ their innovativeness, their
willingness to work hard, their desire to participate and
contribute and be proud.
   President Reagan promised to remove bureaucratic shackles that
inhibited business, to deregulate industries, to take a more
relaxed view of antitrust enforcement, to lower taxes.
   What resulted, and who should be blamed or credited, will be
debated until the end of the century.
   Business did indeed pick up, and before the decade was over,
American goods were becoming competitive at home and abroad. The
gross national product, $2.63 trillion as the decade began, reached
more than $5 trillion in 1989. Trade deficits continued, however,
and some Americans were astonished to realize that it was the money
from their purchases of foreign goods that helped finance foreign
takeovers of U.S. companies and real estate, and pay for foreign
purchases of U.S. securities.
   Big as they were, the gains in gross national product worried
many people because the numbers were swollen by inflation. In
constant, or ``real'' dollars _ using the same 1982 buying power to
measure GNP in both 1980 and 1989 _ the figures were $3.2 trillion
for 1980 and about $4.1 trillion for 1989.
   Real corporate profits soared. New-business formations rose.
More than 20 million jobs were created. Women went to work in
growing numbers, and many of the elderly came out of retirement to
join teen-agers in part-time positions at grocery stores and retail
outlets.
   The spirit of free enterprise was contagious, but the rewards
weren't equally shared. While the new sense of freedom displayed
America's strengths, it also showed weaknesses. Economic laissez
faire made for an erratic, even chaotic economic course, one that
sometimes moved in questionable directions.
   Stock market manipulations became almost commonplace; corporate
takeover artists ``blackmailed'' companies with unfriendly
takeovers if they didn't pay their way out of it; the stock market
became more volatile, made so by trading schemes whose goals were
instant profits; debt rose precipitously; financial scandals eroded
faith in both industry and certain government officials. The
economy operated at a high level, but it wasn't well balanced. To
some, it was a high-wire act uncomfortable to watch because of the
constant fear of a slip. Many were left out; it was claimed by some
economists that the number of people below the poverty line rose.
When inflation was subtracted from hourly wages they were barely
higher as the decade ended. Thousands of farmers went broke. The
stock market was shunned by many individual investors. And a large
number of young households found buying a house an unaffordable
challenge.
   After seven years of expansion, the spread of economic benefits
was inconsistent by any measure. At one point in 1986, economic
strength was so geographically warped that the entire mid-section
of the country was strained by simultaneous weakness in farming,
heavy manufacturing, mining and oil. At the same time, the East and
West Coasts and parts of the Southeast enjoyed boom conditions,
based on strength in such sectors as recreation, finance and
computer-related industries.
   Such inconsistencies led to questions rather than conclusions.
Was something substantial created in the 1980s, or was it sleight
of hand? Did America strengthen itself, or merely create the
superficial impression by living off debt, by passing on a huge
burden for younger generations to pay?
   America improved in many ways, most people would agree, but even
those most convinced of progress wondered also if the economic
substructure had been weakened in subtle ways, particularly by
debts and deficits.
   Uncertainty was the nature of the decade, one of extreme pluses
and minuses. As the '90s approach, most people are still taking an
accounting, and probably will be for years to come.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
