down 8.32 points after gaining 10.66 points on Friday.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by about 7 to 6 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 794 issues down, 527 up and 511
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 66.15 million shares.
   Analysts said weakness in high-technology stocks was helping
drag the market lower after two major investment firms lowered the
ratings of Apple and Compaq computer companies.
   ``The market has been punishing these stocks,'' said Ralph
Bloch, chief market analyst for Raymond, James &amp; Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla.
   Profit-taking following Friday's rally also was helping depress
stock prices, said Brad Weeks, head of equity trading for
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   Weeks said stock prices could decline further before the market
begins a year-end uptick as participants await fresh news on the
economy later this week.
   ``We will probably get more profit-taking today and tomorrow
before we go into some sort of rally,'' Weeks said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.62 to 192.30.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
0.20 to 375.25.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Federal National
Mortgage was down } to 33~, Compaq Computer was off 3~ to 82, IBM
was down ~ to 96 and Philip Morris was off \ to 41~.
   Apple Computer, the most active stock on the over-the-counter
list, was down 3 to 38}.
   Varity, meanwhile, was up [ to 2{ on the NYSE, Global Marine was
unchanged at 3| and WYSE Technology was up { to 9|.
