<HEAD>London Stocks End Lower in Lackluster Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices closed lower in lackluster trading on
London's Stock Exchange Monday, as the market shadowed Wall
Street's narrow movements.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index fell 12.1
points, or 0.5 percent, to 2,351.4 points.
   Volume amounted to a light 349.5 million shares, down from 480.1
million shares Friday.
   Dealers estimated that about 6 points of the 100-share index's
decline reflected the fact that several companies went
``ex-dividend'' Monday, including Allied-Lyons PLC, British Telecom
PLC, and Hanson PLC.
   That means the deadline for buying shares to qualify for the
companies' next dividend has passed.
   A stronger pound and news that British retail sales fell 0.8
percent in November from the previous month had little effect on
the market, dealers said.
</TEXT>
