<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Jumps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell Monday against all major
currencies except the Canadian dollar in calm European trading.
Gold soared more than $5 an ounce.
   Currency dealers said the dollar was suffering from a period of
listlessness in the foreign exchange markets and might move lower
in the closing weeks of the year.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.38 Japanese yen to a closing 144.65 yen.
Later, in London, it fell back to 144.47 yen.
   Other late dollar rates compared with Friday: 1.7660 West German
marks, down from 1.7720; 1.5970 Swiss francs, down from 1.5985;
6.0370 French francs, down from 6.0565; 1.9950 Dutch guilders, down
from 2.0000; 1,304.25 Italian lire, down from 1,306.50; and 1.1632
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1615.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5895 from $1.5793 late
Friday.
   Gold recovered strongly in light European trading.
   In London, gold bullion rose to a late bid of $416.75 a troy
ounce from $411.55 Friday. In Zurich, it jumped to $415.75 an ounce
from $409.25.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 11 cents to close at $412.26 an
ounce.
   Silver bullion rose sharply in London to a late bid of $5.74 a
troy ounce, up from $5.64 Friday.
</TEXT>
