<FIRST>r f BC-CoalProduction 1stLd-Writethru   12-11 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coal Production, 1st Ld-Writethru,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Reports Weekly Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Wyoming production to 3.31 million sted 3.26 million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic coal production totaled 20
million tons during the week ending Dec. 2, up 24 percent from the
16.1 million tons produced in the previous week which included the
Thanksgiving holiday, the Department of Energy reported Monday.
   The U.S. coal industry produced 19.3 million tons in the same
week last year, according to the department's Energy Information
Administration.
   Wyoming ranked first among the 27 coal-producing states with
3.31 million tons produced. Kentucky was second at 3.26 million
tons and West Virginia was third at 3.24 million tons, the agency
said.
   Domestic coal production so far this year is 898.1 million tons,
5.6 percent above last year's production at this time, the agency
said.
   The week's production accounts for bituminous and lignite coal.
</TEXT>
