<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-11 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed; Wheat Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices rose moderately Monday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting hope for new sales of the
grain to the Soviet Union. Other grain and soybean futures finished
narrowly mixed.
   The wheat market was supported all day by the Agriculture
Department's announcement on Friday that it had increased by 4
million metric tons to 20 million metric tons the maximum amount of
U.S. grain the Soviet Union may purchase during the current
marketing year.
   Further support for wheat stemmed from President Bush's
statement Friday that he would push for granting
most-favored-nation trade status to the Soviet Union. The
designation would allow for freer trade between the superpowers.
   Forecasts for extremely cold weather this week in the Great
Plains prompted fears of damage to the winter wheat crop, which
already is under stress due to a lack of sufficient moisture.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1\ cents to 4\ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.13{ a bushel; corn
futures were 1 cent lower to 1} cents higher with December at
$2.35\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to } cent higher with December
at $1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were } cent lower to 2 cents higher
with January at $5.78{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
