<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     12-11 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0284</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell in listless trading today,
reflecting ongoing investor caution about the outlook for the
economy and interest rates.
   Stock prices were mixed at the opening, sagged to session lows
just after midday then floundered for much of the session. A late
rally erased some of the day's losses.
   Wall Street analysts said continued economic uncertainty sent
many investors to the sidelines to await fresh economic data due
out later this week.
   Reports on retail, housing and auto sales as well as producer
prices and industrial production are expected to provide further
evidence of a slowing economy, analysts said.
   Analysts said that investors hope more data suggesting a
slowdown in economic growth will prompt the Federal Reserve to take
steps to lower interest rates to stimulate the economy, and thus
help improve corporate profits.
   High-technology stocks, which have taken a hit in recent days
due to an industry-wide slowdown, helped drag the market lower for
another day.
   ``The focus is on the stocks getting hit, particularly the
narrow high-tech area, and that negative sentiment has thrown a
shroud over the rest of the market,'' said Jack Solomon, equities
analyst for Bear Stearns &amp; Co.
   Analysts said profit-taking following Friday's rally and
squaring of tax positions before year's end also helped depress
stock prices.
   Nevertheless, most analysts remain optimistic that the market
will enter the new year on an upbeat note.
   ``We will probably get more profit-taking today and tomorrow
before we go into some sort of rally,'' said Brad Weeks, head of
equity trading for Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
</TEXT>
