<DOCNO> AP891211-0307 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1746EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Wyse-Taiwan     12-11 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wyse-Taiwan,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wyse Technology Bought By Taiwan Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Foreign Investment Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyse Technology Inc., the world's second
largest maker of computer terminals, agreed Monday to a $268
million buyout by a Taiwan group in a deal that could boost the
company's flagging business.
   Wyse, which is based in San Jose but does all manufacturing in
Taiwan and elsewhere overseas, began a search for buyers after
losing $21 million in the 1989 fiscal year ended March 31.
   The $10-per-share buyout by Channel International Corp., an
investment group of government and local enterprises, is the
largest ever of a foreign firm by Taiwan.
   ``A lot of U.S. companies looked at Wyse but figured it wasn't
worth more than $4 or $5 a share,'' said Michael Murphy, editor of
California Technology Stockletter. ``Wyse got the best price it
could from Taiwan.''
   ``The acquisition is an important step for Taiwan's electronics
and computer industries to enter the world market,'' Koo Cheng-fu,
chairman of China Investment and Trust Co., the largest investor in
the buyout, said in a news conference in Taiwan.
   Koo said his group would use Wyse's sales channels and
technology personnel to promote Taiwan's high-technology products.
   Wyse, an 8-year-old company that earned $28 million in fiscal
1988 before slumping, holds more than a 50 percent market share for
general-purpose terminals in the United States. Worldwide, Wyse
trails only International Business Machines Corp. as a supplier of
terminals, said Greg Blatnik, an industry analyst for Dataquest
Inc. in San Jose.
   Terminals, which can be hooked to mainframes, minicomputers or
personal computers, accounted for 47 percent of Wyse's $452 million
in sales in fiscal 1989. Personal computers accounted for 39
percent, and screen monitors accounted for 14 percent of sales.
   Wyse is expected to sell 800,000 terminals worldwide by the end
of 1989, nearly all to businesses, compared with just over 1
million by IBM, Blatnik said.
   In the first six months of fiscal 1990, ending Sept. 29, Wyse
had $231 million in revenue and net losses of $7.7 million.
   Wyse has been less successful in selling IBM-compatible personal
computers, and Blatnik said that is the area that should get the
most attention from the new Taiwanese owners.
   ``The whole concept of the deal has to be looked at as a
positive step for Wyse,'' Blatnik said. ``It gives them financial
stability, and over the long term provides them with a better focus
on the PC side of their business.''
   Although Wyse has a reputation for making low-priced,
high-quality terminals and personal computers, its strategy in the
PC market has hurt the company's growth, said Murphy.
   ``Wyse has a strategy of not producing the most advanced
computers,'' he said. ``They wait to see how the latest technology
shakes out and then try to move in with lower prices. That hasn't
worked out for them. They need to be more innovative.''
   Wyse Chairman Bernard K. Tse will remain with the company as
vice chairman.
   Morris Chang, former senior vice president Texas Instruments and
former president of General Instrument Corp., will become chairman
and chief executive officer of Wyse.
   Chang has been serving as chairman of the Industrial Technology
Research Institute, a non-profit research and development
organization established in 1973 to accelerate the development of
advanced technology in Taiwan.
   He said he doesn't plan significant near-term changes in Wyse's
product lines or its approach to business, and intends to maintain
its headquarters, marketing and related operations in San Jose.
   Taiwanese businessmen have shown growing interest in acquiring
foreign firms, which they believe could boost their business in the
world market.
   Last month, Samuel Hsieh, governor of the Central Bank, proposed
using Taiwan's foreign reserves of about $73 billion for loans to
local enterprises for overseas acquisitions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
