<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-11 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Prices Surge, Approach New 1989 High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices surged to within a few dollars of new 1989
highs Monday on New York's Commodity Exchange as the market
extended for a fifth day its recovery from a steep
post-Thanksgiving decline.
   On other commodity markets, orange juice futures rose sharply on
Florida freeze fears; cotton futures rebounded; energy futures
gained; pork futures fell; cattle futures rose; and grains and
soybeans were mixed.
   Gold futures settled $4.90 to $5.50 higher with the contract for
delivery in December up $5 at $416.80 a troy ounce.
   The December contract reached an intra-day high of $418 an
ounce, just $1.70 below the 1989 high of $419.70 reached on Nov. 24.
   Silver futures finished 4.5 cents to 4.9 cents higher with
December at $5.692 a troy ounce.
   Analysts said that after climbing back steadily from about $401
in the past week, gold looked strong enough to break through $420
an ounce, an event that would likely trigger new waves of buying.
   Explanations for the recovery abounded but four market analysts
queried by The Associated Press agreed the political changes
occurring in Eastern Europe were in some way linked to gold's
strength.
   ``The market reads this as one of the watershed geopolitical
events of the 20th century,'' said Richard Levine of Elders Futures
Inc.
   Levine noted a strong correlation between the gold market and
the West German mark, which he interpreted as evidence that
investors expect West Germany to benefit economically from Eastern
Europe's movement away from communism.
   James E. Sinclair, a director and chief economist of Diversified
Investors Corp., saw signs that the Soviet Union is preparing to
issue gold-backed bonds and halt all sales of gold on the open
market.
   Gold traders also responded to Monday's higher energy prices,
typically a buy-signal for inflation-sensitive gold, said Peter
Cardillo, commodity trading adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New
York.
   Orange juice futures rose sharply on the New York Cotton
Exchange amid forecasts for a hard freeze in Florida by the end of
the week.
   Frozen concentrated orange juice settled 2.45 cents to 3.75
cents higher with January at $1.313 cents a pound.
   Cotton futures also climbed sharply in a move that analysts
viewed as a technical correction after several sessions in which
prices fell.
   Cotton settled .60 cent to 1.73 cent higher with March at 67.91
cents a pound.
   Heating oil continued to lead energy prices higher on the New
York Mercantile Exchange as extremely cold temperatures in Europe
spurred demand for fuel oil on the world market.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 15 cents to 23 cents
higher with January at $20.70 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent
lower to .58 cent higher with January at 66.95 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .11 cent to .40 cent lower with January at
52.40 cents a gallon.
   Frozen pork bellies dropped the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit for
the third straight day on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, partly
reflecting disappointment over the government's slow pace in buying
bellies to donate to Poland.
   Cattle futures advanced in line with strong cash markets. Hog
futures were mixed.
   Live cattle settled .45 cent to 1.17 cents higher with December
at 76.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .47
cent higher with January at 83.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .28
cent lower to .35 cent higher with December at 51.15 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were 1 cent to 2 cents lower with February at
50.45 cents a pound.
   Wheat futures prices rose moderately on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid hopes for new sales of the grain to the Soviet Union.
Other grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed.
   Wheat futures settled 1{ cents to 3} cents higher with December
at $4.13{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower to 1} cents higher with
December at $2.35 a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to \ cent higher
with December at $1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 2
cents higher with January at $5.79 a bushel.
</TEXT>
