<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-11 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Futures End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale home heating oil prices rose Monday as
wintry weather boosted demand. Crude oil futures also closed higher
but gasoline futures finished lower.
   The contract for No.2 heating oil for January delivery rose 0.58
cent to 66.95 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
adding to Friday's gain of 0.90 cent. Contracts for delivery during
February and March ended with much smaller increases while the
April contract fell slightly.
   Low temperatures in parts of the United States and Europe
spurred buying, analysts said.
   Buyers in the crude oil pit took a cue from heating oil traders
and bid prices higher. The January contract for West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 22 cents
to $20.70 per 42-gallon barrel after losing 3 cents on Friday. The
February through April contracts ended with similar gains.
   Among other refined products traded on the New York Merc,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery, which sank 0.16
cent on Friday, dropped another 0.25 cent to 52.40 cents a gallon.
Other contracts closed lower also.
   Gasoline prices typically soften in the winter when driving
tapers off due to bad weather.
   Energy analyst Linda Simard at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. said
buying enthusiasm in London spilled over into U.S. markets. In
Europe, prices of gasoil _ the equivalent of U.S. heating oil _
have firmed because of shortages and a seasonal pickup in demand.
   She said there were reports Monday that a drought in parts of
Europe, which has caused low water levels on the Rhine River, has
reduced production of hydroelectric power.
   The result has been extra demand for alternative energy sources.
France now is importing more energy than it is exporting while
normally the country is a net energy exporter, Simard said, citing
reports circulating in the futures markets.
</TEXT>
