<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   12-11 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Sag In Dull Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing prices, minor editing throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell in listless trading Monday
amid investor uncertainty about the economy and interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 3.20 points to
2,728.24 after gaining 10.66 points in Friday's session.
   Declining issues outpaced advances by a 5 to 4 margin in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
844 issues down, 669 up and 477 unchanged. Traders said
high-technology stocks led the losers after two brokerages lowered
the investment ratings of Compaq and Apple computer companies.
   Wall Street analysts attributed the market's overall weakness to
investor uncertainty about the prospects for the economy and to
profit-taking after Friday's modest rally.
   ``The word is apprehension, particularly given the sad state of
profits and no apparent reason to believe that will change,'' said
Hugh Johnson, senior vice president of First Albany Corp.
   Johnson said based on last Friday's report on November
employment, many economists have revised downward their
fourth-quarter economic forecasts. The report showed the jobless
rate rose to 5.4 percent from 5.3 percent in October. In addition,
despite a gain of 210,000 jobs in November, October's pace of jobs
growth was revised downward.
   ``The consensus before the report was for a growth rate of about
1.5 percent, now it's closer to 1 percent,'' Johnson said.
   Analysts said many investors were noncommital ahead of a slew of
new government reports due out this week which could provide a
better clue about the economy's direction, among them November
retail sales, producer prices, industrial production and capacity
utilization.
   Investors hope further evidence of an economic slowdown will
persuade the Federal Reserve to take steps to lower interest rates
and thus help boost sagging corporate profits, analysts said.
   Analysts said some investors also took the opportunity to do
year-end housecleaning in the absence of fresh economic news to
stir the market.
   ``It was a continuation of year-end tax selling, some for
profits some reflecting negativism about former favorites with the
focal point being high-tech stocks on the sell side,'' said Jack
Solomon, equities analyst for Bear Stearns &amp; Co.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 147.13 million
shares, up from 144.91 million in Friday's session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 177.28 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market fell $6.221 billion, or 0.18
percent, in value from Friday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped 0.09 to 192.83.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Pinacle West, the most
active stock, fell | to 10], Compaq Computer dropped 4\ to 81|
after First Boston Corp. downgraded the stock's investment rating,
IBM lost } to 96[, and Pfizer tumbled 1{ to 67|.
   Apple Computer, the most active stock on the over-the-counter
list, dropped 2{ to 39\ after Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. lowered its
investment rating and earnings estimate for the company.
   On the plus side, Federal National Mortgage rose } to 35],
Philip Morris gained \ to 42] and WYSE Technology advanced | to 9}.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index lost 0.31 to 398.91, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index edged down 0.13 to 348.56.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
tumbled 3.80 to 452.42. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 375.04, down 0.41.
</TEXT>
