<FIRST>u f AM-SEC-Netherlands     12-11 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Netherlands,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-Dutch Securities Agreement Reached</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Wim Kok in 5th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United States and Netherlands securities
regulators have signed a pact to assist each other in conducting
investigations and enforcing their respective securities laws, the
Securities and Exchange Commission announced Monday.
   Officials hailed the administrative assistance agreement, signed
Monday at The Hague, as the most comprehensive formal securities
enforcement accord yet between the United States and a European
country.
   ``Each of our nations has a common interest in protecting
investors at home, and in foreign markets, from fraud, manipulation
and similar abusive practices,'' SEC Chairman Richard C. Breeden
said in written remarks prepared for the signing at The Hague.
   ``The agreement signed today strengthens our ability and detect
these types of unlawful activities conducted across national
borders,'' Breeden stated.
   The agreement also was signed by Dutch Minister of Finance Wim
Kok.
   U.S. investors' transactions in Dutch corporate stock increased
from $1.9 billion to $4 billion between 1985 and 1988. During the
the same period, Dutch transactions in U.S. corporate stock
increased from $4 billion to $5.8 billion.
   Under the agreement, the SEC and Dutch finance ministry will
assist each other in enforcing their respective securities laws,
including obtaining information and documents, taking statements
and conducting compliance examinations or inspections of securities
businesses.
   The agreement applies only to territory of the Kingdom of the
Netherlands in Europe and not in the Caribbean.
   Mutual cooperation in criminal matters, however, will continue
to governed by a 1981 mutual assistance treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
