<HEAD>Group Headed by Texas Billionaire Increases Stake in Lockheed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group headed by Texas
billionaire Harold C. Simmons disclosed Monday that it has
increased a stake in Lockheed Corp. to 16.9 percent.
   The group stated in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission that it had acquired 3.83 million shares of the defense
contractor's shares since Nov. 22.
   All the shares were purchased at prices ranging between $36.75
and $39.25 per share on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The group still indicated that the stock purchase for investment
purposes only.
   A spokesman for Lockheed at its Calabasas, Calif. headquarters,
Robert Slayman, said the company would have no comment on the SEC
filing. Lockheed, maker of the stealth bomber and other defense
weapons, has declined to comment on Simmons' previous stock
purchases.
   Earlier this year, Simmons revealed he had a 5.3 percent stake
in Lockheed, prompting Lockheed to create an employee stock
ownership plan (ESOP) to block any takeover attempt.
   Simmons, who has holdings in the chemical, timber and sugar
industries, at first reduced his holdings in Lockheed and has since
increased it several times to 6.25 percent, then 9.46 percent and
10.43 percent.
