<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BankofBoston     12-11 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank of Boston,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Of Boston to Sell Credit Card Portfolio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of Boston announced plans Monday to sell its
$590 million credit card portfolio because of difficulties in
competing with companies that operate multibillion dollar credit
card operations.
   Bank of Boston spokesman Wayne Taylor said that since the 1970s,
the credit card business had grown to the point where just a few
companies had amassed a large chunk of the market.
   Taylor said although Bank of Boston was the 15th largest bank in
the United States, it ranked only 33rd among credit card suppliers.
   The bank has 675,000 Mastercard and VISA cardholders, located
mostly in New England, for revenues of $590 million. By comparison,
Taylor said, giant Citicorp has credit card revenues of more than
$21 billion annually.
   ``We'd have to spend a lot of money to continue to compete in
this field,'' Taylor said. ``We came to the point where we decided
to put our resources elsewhere.''
   Taylor said the bank would concentrate on expanding its branch
network throughout New England and on broadening its range of
consumer finance products, such as home equity, residential
mortgages and student loans.
   He did not identify any possible buyers for the credit card
business.
</TEXT>
