<FIRST>u f AM-IMF-Peru     12-11 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF-Peru,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Pact with International Monetary Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After four years of disagreements, the
International Monetary Fund announced on Monday that it has reached
an accord with Peru, raising the prospect of financial aid if
Peruvian policies meet its approval.
   An official of the fund, who spoke on condition he not be named,
said Peru had made a payment of $42.3 million on the $800 million
it owes the fund. The payment covers only the arrears since
September of this year.
   The agreement was reached last week between Peru's negotiator,
Abel Salinas, and Michal Camdessus, the fund's French managing
director, the official said.
   Owned by 152 governments, the fund negotiates at length with
governments in financial trouble. It gives its help only when the
borrowing government agrees on a set of policies it approves.
Usually these include cuts in government spending, especially on
official payrolls and subsidies, and often a devaluation of the
country's currency.
   Peru has been in trouble with the financial world since
President Alan Garcia was elected in 1985 and announced that he
would make only partial payments of interest on the country's
debts. At that time Peru owed $14 billion abroad. Now the figure is
closer to $20 billion.
   Its financial troubles have been worsened by the continuing
rebellion of a leftist guerrilla group, the Shining Path, and a
thriving traffic in drugs.
   Peru is one of 10 countries with a total arrears of $3.5 billion
to the fund, and so ineligible for more finanical aid from it _ or
much from anyone else. This year the fund started a series of what
it called ``shadow programs,'' under which governments promised new
policies but got no immediate money. Vietnam, Zambia, Somalia and
now Peru have started such programs.
   If the fund finds they are doing well after a year or so, they
will start getting its financial help.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0315 </DOCNO>
