<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   12-11 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Department Orders Eastern Compliance on Health Benefits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department on Monday said it has obtained
an order requiring Eastern Airlines to help striking and laid-off
employees obtain continued health benefits.
   ``Employers must know that the Labor Department is serious about
protecting the right of working Americans to continued health
coverage in cases like Eastern,'' Elizabeth Dole, Secretary of
Labor, said in a statement released in Washington concerning
Eastern and the Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act.
   The consent order, which requires Eastern to report on its
compliance quarterly for five years, followed an investigation by
Labor officials into complaints by Eastern COBRA participants who
said insurance carriers told them they were no longer covered, even
though the employees had paid insurance premiums. The federal law
says employers must give terminated employees the chance to obtain
continued health benefits at group rates.
   ``As a result (officials) began a large-scale investigation into
possible violations of notification and insurance claims processing
provisions under COBRA,'' said David George Ball, assistant Labor
Secretary.
   Wally Haber, senior general chairman of the Machinists union
that's been on strike since March 4, said employees were
inappropriately rejected on claims or faced backlogs of up to six
months.
   ``We've been having a running battle with Eastern on the COBRA
violations,'' Haber said.
   Haber said just before the strike began, Eastern laid off most
of its workers in the insurance department, which contributed to
the backlog. Haber said employees have had better results recently.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said claims were taking an
average of four weeks to process. He said the consent order would
have no financial impact on Eastern.
   ``We're up-to-date now,'' he said.
   Matell blamed initial problems on a combination of hostile
union-management relations, the complications of the Chapter 11
bankruptcy reorganization Eastern filed for March 9, and the
massive number of employees suddenly on strike o laid off. Also, he
said, Eastern had computer problems that exacerbated the delays.
   ``We feel that we really reacted admirably in the unusual
circumstances,'' Matell said. ``The COBRA law never contemplated
such wide-ranging and massive problems.''
   Eastern has been operating as a much smaller airline because of
the strike and bankruptcy reorganization. It reportedly is close to
selling Latin American routes to AMR Corp., parent of American
Airlines, for $300 million to $400 million.
   Neither Fort Worth-based AMR nor Eastern would discuss the deal,
reported in several newspapers. But there was speculation a deal
could be announced by Wednesday, when Eastern is scheduled to meet
with a committee of creditors.
   The negotiations with AMR on the Latin American routes are the
second round since Eastern sought Chapter 11 protection. Earlier
attempts to sell the routes to AMR foundered over disagreements
involving a lawsuit filed against American by Continental Airlines,
the other main Texas Air subsidiary.
   During the strike American, the nation's largest airline, has
been expanding aggressively in the Caribbean _ a key area for
Eastern.
  
</TEXT>
