<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Heinz     12-11 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Heinz,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.J. Heinz Co. reported a 14.1 percent
increase in second-quarter earnings Monday, helped by stronger
sales and higher prices for its food products.
   Earnings for the Pittsburgh-based food manufacturer totaled $125
million in the period ending Nov. 1, or 47 cents per share, vs.
$109.9 million, or 42 cents per share a year earlier. The per-share
figures reflect a 2-for-1 stock split in September.
   Sales during the second quarter amounted to $1.5 billion, up 7.5
percent from $1.4 billion in 1988. The gain resulted from higher
volume of tuna, frozen potatoes and Weight Watchers frozen meals,
as well as price increases.
   For the first six months of 1989, net income was $251.9 million
or 95 cents a share, up 14.5 percent from last year's $219.9
million or 84 cents a share a year earlier.
   Sales for the first half of 1989 increased to $2.9 billion, up
6.4 percent from last year's $2.8 billion.
