<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ColaFlap     12-11 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cola Flap,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Royal Crown Asks FTC for Sanctions Against Pepsi, Coke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Royal Crown Cola Co. has asked the Federal Trade
Commission to invoke sanctions against bigger rivals Pepsico and
Coca-Cola Co. for what it called ``predatory pricing'' by their
company-owned bottling plants.
   Al Burke, president and chief operating officer of Royal Crown,
said Monday that the company has asked the FTC for sanctions
against the two. Royal Crown has requested that Pepsi and Coke be
prohibited from acquiring additional holdings in their franchise
systems, Burke disclosed at a beverage industry gathering in New
York.
   In addition, he said, the FTC should order the two companies to
divest their interests in company-owned bottling plants and the
brands other than Coke and Pepsi produced by those operations.
   Under the request, Royal Crown has asked the FTC to require that
the two companies each reduce their holdings in company-owned
plants to 25 percent within two years _ at which time they would be
sold.
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola declined comment, saying it was unaware
of any FTC investigation of the issue, said spokesman Randy
Donaldson.
   Pepsico, based in Purchase, said it hasn't been contacted on the
matter by the federal agency or Royal Crown.
   ``There's really nothing new here and certainly nothing the
industry hasn't heard before,'' said Tod MacKenzie, a spokesman for
the company's Pepsi Cola operations.
   Royal Crown's appeal to the FTC is the second time in three
years the company has filed complaints with the agency against Coke
and Pepsi. In 1986, Royal Crown asked the FTC to block Pepsi's
proposed acquisition of Seven-Up Co. and Coke's planned buyout of
Dr Pepper, claiming the purchases would violate federal antitrust
laws.
   The FTC later blocked the acquisitions on antitrust grounds.
   Royal Crown, based in Miami, is a subsidiary of Chesapeake
Financial Corp., which is in turn controlled by industrialist
Victor Posner.
   In his talk, Burke called predatory pricing the most serious
problem facing the U.S. soft drink industry.
   Predatory pricing consists of pricing products below cost to
beat competitors, then quickly hiking them back up after the action
has succeeded.
   Burke charged, for example, that it costs bottlers about 80
cents to put a two-liter bottle in a supermarket, but Coke and
Pepsi both sold the bottles for 69 cents each last Labor Day
weekend in Dallas.
   Coke has 41.1 percent of the U.S. soft drink market, followed by
Pepsi with 31.1 percent. Royal Crown has only 2.8 percent,
according to Beverage Digest, an industry publication.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
