<FIRST>r f AM-ColumbiaSavings     12-11 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Columbia Savings,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Junk Bond Proponent Resigns as Columbia Savings Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The troubled junk bond market
claimed the job of one of its biggest supporters Monday when Thomas
Spiegel said he would quit as chairman of Columbia Savings &amp; Loan
Association at the end of the year.
   Under the leadership of Spiegel, a former Wall Street trader,
Columbia invested more heavily than any other thrift in high-yield,
high-risk bonds, turning big profits on them until recently.
   But new federal laws forced Columbia to essentially return to
being a conventional mortgage lender. The thrift in October marked
down the price of its junk bonds to reflect their depressed market
value, as required by new federal law, taking a loss of about $350
million. Columbia plans to sell the junk bonds to a new subsidiary.
   Previously, thrifts didn't have to adjust the book value of
their bonds to account for market price because they carried them
as long-term investments.
   Columbia's high-yield portfolio is now worth $3.8 billion, down
from $4.3 billion at the end of last year, and Spiegel said the
thrift urgently needed to rid itself of the bonds.
   Spiegel said he would work full time as a consultant to
Columbia, trying to line up investors for the subsidiary into which
the junk bonds would be spun off.
   A thrift bailout bill signed by President Bush in August
requires thrifts to sell their junk bonds by 1994. Under the
legislation, thrifts can invest in junk bonds only through
separately capitalized affiliates rather than using
government-insured deposits.
   ``Business imperatives coupled with the publicity surrounding me
led me to conclude that a new CEO with extensive banking or thrift
experience was required to lead Columbia into the future,'' Spiegel
said in a statement.
   Columbia said it already had begun interviewing potential
successors.
   Spiegel is a friend of junk bond pioneer Michael Milken, who has
been indicted on racketeering and securities fraud charges. New
charges against Milken reportedly will include allegations of
illegal stock and bond deals with Columbia.
   Spiegel was unavailable for an interview, but Columbia
spokeswoman Lenore Hatch said he intended to hold the bonds to
maturity in the new Columbia subsidiary. She said it was too early
to describe in detail how the subsidiary would work.
   ``Hopefully the structure we're considering would have the
effect of removing the volatility that's in the high-yield
market,'' she said.
   Spiegel said in his statement that the depressed market for junk
bonds had created big opportunities.
   ``During the eight years in which I have been actively involved
in the high-yield securities market, I have never seen better
values,'' he said.
   Spiegel, 43, noted that his family owns more than half of
Columbia's common stock. ``I believe that it is urgent that I move
rapidly to preserve and enhance the value of our securities
portfolio,'' he said.
   Fueled largely by Spiegel's investments in junk bonds,
Columbia's assets jumped to $13 billion this year from $400 million
in 1974.
   But in the third quarter of this year Columbia lost $226 million
as a result of $357.5 million in losses related to those bond
holdings.
   Columbia said that because of problems with junk bond
investments it will be unable to meet the tougher requirements for
risk-based capital under the savings and loan bailout law.
   In order to boost its capital, Columbia has agreed to sell
nearly all its mortgage-backed securities for about $90 million,
and to sell ``certain public and private equities'' for a gain of
about $75 million, the thrift said in a statement.
   Columbia said it has raised $10 million more through various
asset sales and other actions.
   Thrift institutions like Columbia that do not meet the new
capital requirements are required to file a capital plan acceptable
to federal regulators by Jan. 8. Columbia said its plan will, as
required, detail its financial strategy for compliance, but the
thrift provided no details.
   Spiegel was paid $5.6 million in 1987 and $4.1 million last
year. Ms. Hatch said his pay package as a consultant has not been
determined, and she declined to estimate how much he will make this
year.
   His high salaries have angered federal thrift regulators for
years, as has his amassing of the huge portfolio of junk bonds.
   He also is known for his close ties to political figures. He set
up the junk bond investment for former House majority whip Tony
Coelho that forced the Democrat to resign last May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0322 </DOCNO>
