<HEAD>Thomas Cook Travel, Crimson-Heritage Form Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Cook Travel Inc. has formed a business
partnership with Crimson Travel Service and Heritage Travel, saying
the new agency is the nation's third-largest travel company.
   Thomas Cook Travel, which was acquired in April by Britain's
Robert Maxwell, will own 50 percent of the new partnership, while
the other 50 percent will be owned by the Crimson-Heritage owners.
   The combined company will have more than 325 offices nationwide
with 2,500 employees and travel sales in excess of $1.3 billion
annually.
   David Paresky, who founded Crimson Travel Service about 25 years
ago, will head the partnership, which will be known as Thomas Cook.
   He said Crimson Travel formed a partnership with Heritage Travel
about 18 months ago and began discussing about an affiliation with
Cook a year ago.
   He said Crimson-Heritage, based in Cambridge, Mass., operates
from 175 locations in 22 states and had about $700 million in sales
last year.
   Its offices will continue to operate for the time being under
their current names but eventually will be known as Thomas Cook
operations, Paresky said.
   Thomas Cook Travel, based in New York, operates from about 150
locations and had sales of about $650 million last year, Paresky
said.
   A spokesman for Crimson said the new operation, which will be
the U.S. member of the multinational Thomas Cook Group network
based in London, will be the third-largest U.S. travel company,
following those operated by American Express Co. and Carlson Cos.'
Ask Mr. Foster.
   ``We have created a company with the leadership and resources to
provide our customers with unequaled global travel service,''
Maxwell said in a statement.
