<DOCNO> AP891211-0328 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Sagansky-CBS     12-11 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sagansky-CBS,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS May Pick Movie Executive As New Programs Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite industry speculation that CBS is about
to name Tri-Star Pictures President Jeff Sagansky as its new
programming chief, no deal has been made, the network said Monday.
   ``To the best of my knowledge, the deal is not done,'' said
Susan Tick, a CBS spokeswoman in Los Angeles. She declined to
comment on whether CBS has been negotiating with Sagansky,
appointed to his Tri-Star post only last March.
   Sagansky once worked in finance for CBS, whose entertainment
president, Kim LeMasters, resigned last week after two years on the
job. Sagansky had been among those whom network sources said was
being considered for the post.
   But then CBS began talks with two top Hollywood producers, Marcy
Carsey and Tom Werner, about taking over CBS Entertainment, whose
prime-time schedule has been third in the ratings for two
consecutive years.
   The production company of Carsey and Werner makes NBC's ``The
Cosby Show'' and ABC's ``Roseanne,'' both top-rated comedies.
   When CBS' negotiations with them collapsed Friday, Sagansky's
name arose again as a prospect to head CBS Entertainment, network
sources said.
   A senior NBC Entertainment executive until joining Tri-Star in
1985 as its president of production, Sagansky did not return a
phone call Monday to his Burbank office.
   Mark Gill, a Tri-Star spokesman, declined to comment on whether
Saganky plans to join CBS.
   A 1974 Harvard graduate, Sagansky is credited with developing
and overseeing production of such Tri-Star films as ``About Last
Night,'' ``Steel Magnolias,'' and the recently released ``Glory.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
